<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, March 22, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Steps Up Attack on Gore
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican George W. Bush sharpened the attack on his
rival, saying Democrat Al Gore is an ''obstacle to reform'' who is too partisan
to be president, much less fix Social Security or enact meaningful changes to
the campaign finance system. In an interview Wednesday with the Washington Post,
Bush pledged to stick with his plan for a sizable tax cut despite polls showing
tepid voter interest in one. He also said he would make saving Social Security a
focus of the fall debate against Gore.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
US Envoy's Mission to Taiwan Begins
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Praising the island's vibrant democracy, a U.S. envoy
began a mission to Taiwan on Wednesday in hopes of learning how serious the
newly elected president is about avoiding war with China. Lee Hamilton came to
Taipei hours after a U.S. diplomat wrapped up talks with Chinese leaders in
Beijing, saying he was encouraged by China's cautious attitude with Taiwan. The
diplomatic missions followed opposition leader Chen Shui-bian's stunning victory
in Taiwan's presidential election Saturday. Beijing distrusts Chen, 49, because
his party supports Taiwan independence.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Administration Maintains Pressure on Gun Cos.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Maintaining pressure on gun manufacturers, the Clinton
administration announced that 29 cities and counties will give preference to gun
makers that follow the lead of Smith &AMP; Wesson -- producing safer firearms and
adopting a code of responsible conduct. Secretary of Housing and Urban
Development Andrew Cuomo urged communities of every size to join the effort and
said preferential buying can force the gun industry to fall in line behind the
Smith &AMP; Wesson agreement because sales to law enforcement agencies represent 20
percent to 30 percent of the U.S. gun market.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Richardson: OPEC Will Hike Output
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- U.S. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson expressed confidence
Wednesday that oil-producing nations will increase production in a move likely
to reduce soaring oil prices. OPEC cut production by 4.3 million barrels a day
more than a year ago after prices plummeted to below $11 a barrel. Since then,
prices have soared as high as $34 per barrel. The Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries meets March 27 in Vienna.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pope Reaches Out to Palestinians
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, West Bank (AP) -- Despite the Vatican's portrayal of his trip to
Israel as purely spiritual, Pope John Paul II touched on contentious issues of
clear consequence to the region. The pontiff Wednesday proclaimed Palestinians'
''natural right to a homeland'' and visited a camp for refugees exiled from
their homes since the 1948 Mideast War. Earlier in the day, John Paul called for
international action to end Palestinian suffering. ''Your torment is before the
eyes of the world,'' he declared. ''And it has gone on for too long.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lewinsky Touts Her New Role
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Enough with the talk about the president, Monica Lewinsky
has embarked on her next calling in life: Businesswoman. Lewinsky has put an
''Inc.'' after her name and is selling a line of high-end handbags on the
Internet and at one of New York's toniest designer shops. But she still faces
skeptics who wonder if she can build her name into a respected brand or will
quickly fall from notoriety like other celebrities-by-scandal. Lewinsky first
started stitching the bags the while being cooped up at home during the Clinton
mess.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Study Dispels Herpes Myths
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- People infected with genital herpes can spread it even
between flare-ups, when they have no symptoms, new research suggests. Up until
recently, patients and even most doctors thought people with herpes could safely
have unprotected sex when they had no symptoms, which can include painful,
oozing blisters, ulcers and fissures and tingling and burning. Most doctors
advised patients to abstain from sex during flare-ups, but some said sex with a
condom was OK.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Higher at Midday
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei Stock Average gained 23.43 points to 19,757.02 at
the end of the Thursday morning session. On Wednesday, the average closed up
131.23 points. In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average slipped 40.64
points to 10,866.70 at Wednesday's close.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Penn St. Beats Kent at NIT 81-74
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- Jarrett Stephens, playing in his final game at
home, had 24 points and 10 rebounds as Penn State beat Kent 81-74 on Wednesday
night to advance to the NIT semifinals for the second time in three years. Joe
Crispin added 18 points, including eight free throws in the final minute for the
Nittany Lions (18-15), who are fast forgetting their ninth-place finish in the
Big Ten. The Lions go to New York on Tuesday to face the winner of Wednesday's
Notre Dame-BYU game.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY FOSS
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
