<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euphemistically speaking, that is the way government talks  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A ''euphemism,'' according to Webster's New
World Dictionary, is the use of a less distasteful or offensive
word or a phrase to substitute for another.
</P>
<P>
   A ''euphemism,'' according to many in government in New York --
if not the rest of the country and the world -- is a stock in trade,
a modus operandi, an everyday way of describing for the public its
activities using words and phrases that really don't describe
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, for instance, the state Department of
Environmental Conservation (DEC) approved some rule changes for the
state's ''ozone non-attainment area.'' Translation: The smoggiest
region of New York, encompassing New York City and nearby counties.
</P>
<P>
   ''Non-attainment'' is a euphemism for failure, as in Syracuse
University's basketball team has a record of ''non-attainment'' in
winning an NCAA championship or Mario Cuomo was a ''non-attainer''
in his run for governor against George Pataki in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The state DEC isn't the only agency which finds the use of the
word ''failure'' distasteful.
</P>
<P>
   State education officials, in grading new standardized tests for
New York school children, have come up with the category of
students who showed only ''partial'' or ''minimal'' achievement or
-- worst of all -- ''no evidence'' of achievement on the
examinations.
</P>
<P>
   To most of the rest of the world, that means the students
failed.
</P>
<P>
   And smoggy counties and struggling students are hardly the only
ones getting put through the government's rhetorical wringer, New
York style:
JUST SHOOT ME
</P>
<P>
   Hunters, sometimes euphemistically known as ''sportsmen,'' like
to think of themselves as a hale and hearty lot, capable of waiting
stoically in a blind or doggedly tracking prey for hours, if not
days.
</P>
<P>
   Yet government would not dare offend these rugged individuals
when taking account of their activities, or perhaps not dare offend
the rest of New Yorkers who don't hunt.
</P>
<P>
   In the DEC's annual reports on hunting in New York, wildlife is
never ''killed'' or ''shot'' but rather ''taken'' or ''harvested.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's growing deer herds are ''managed'' by hunters with
the help of their guns and crossbows. In areas where herds really
need hunters' special form of management, hunters can shoot a
second deer -- their big-game licenses entitled them to one -- if
they hold a special ''Deer Management Permit'' from the state.
</P>
<P>
   Hunters may not kill deer, but cars do. The DEC is not squeamish
when reporting that deer are ''killed'' by motorists in the
agency's annual tallies of the car-deer collisions occurring across
the state.
FINE BY ME
</P>
<P>
   A top aide to Pataki paid $2,000 to the state Ethics Commission
last week. But don't think that state operations director James
Natoli was being punished by the commission for accepting expensive
dinners from Philip Morris' chief lobbyist in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Natoli's check represented a ''payment in lieu of assessment''
as part of a ''disposition agreement'' Natoli signed with the
commission. Translation: He paid as part of a deal which precluded
the commission from formally fining him in its inquiry of the
dinners, all in excess of the $75 limit, that lobbyist Sharon
Portnoy put on her corporate credit card. Natoli acknowledged doing
nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   This bit of legal hairsplitting is first cousin to the ''consent
decree,'' which the DEC, the state attorney general's office and
other state agencies frequently enter into. Usually, companies,
individuals and others signing consent decrees are being
investigated by the state. They typically agree to pay a fine, are
allowed to state in writing that they did nothing wrong and the
state gets them to promise never to do it again.
TAKING A TOLL
</P>
<P>
   The state Thruway Authority created a new variation this year on
''revenue enhancer,'' the now-classic government euphemism for a
tax or fee increase.
</P>
<P>
   The Authority's board was considering what it referred to as a
''toll adjustment plan.'' Translation: Annual toll hikes for
motorists of up to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, amid criticism from politicians, commercial truckers
and other motorists, the ''toll adjustment plan'' was ''taken'' by
the board and consigned to ''non-attainment'' status. There is ''no
evidence'' of its ''achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   Euphemistically speaking.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Joel Stashenko first worked for The Associated Press at the New
York state Capitol in 1980. He can be reached at P.O. Box 7165,
Capitol Station, Albany, N.Y., 12224.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
