<HEADLINE> Giuliani snubs fellow Republican mayor  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Guess who didn't come to dinner?
</P>
<P>
   GOP officials said Wednesday that Rudolph Giuliani intentionally
snubbed a fellow Republican mayor last week when he assembled
Republican leaders from the Utica-Rome area to discuss his Senate
candidacy. Giuliani is running against Democrat Hillary Rodham
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City mayor had a private dinner Saturday night at a
downtown Utica restaurant with several dozen GOP bigwigs. Not
invited was Rome Mayor Joseph Griffo.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't receive an invitation. I was not aware of the dinner
... until the day after it happened. I saw it on the news,'' Griffo
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Republican sources, including one very close to Giuliani, said
Griffo was excluded from the session because he was one of the
mayors assembled by Gov. George Pataki to speak out against Sen.
John McCain and for Texas Gov. George W. Bush before New York's
March 7 presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   ''The guy was taking shots at Rudy. It wasn't the McCain thing
per se'' said one Giuliani confidant, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor of Rome said he couldn't understand the move given
that he is a supporter of the mayor's Senate candidacy and felt he
had good relations with his New York City counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know of no reason they should not have included me,
particularly if you're looking for the support of your colleagues
across the state,'' Griffo said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Giuliani and Clinton are working hard at building upstate
support. It is considered a key geographical battleground in the
Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Griffo said he has made no derogatory statements about Giuliani.
The Rome mayor said he had told a news conference in Yonkers that
he was disappointed Giuliani hadn't joined the other mayors on hand
to help boost Bush's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Griffo recalled Wednesday that he had also said at the time that
''the mayor's going to be needing to make a contrast between Mrs.
Clinton and himself, so I don't see the difference'' between that
and contrasting the Bush and McCain records.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know he's an opinionated person and has strong beliefs ...
but I don't understand if you're trying to build a coalition to
undertake a campaign and win why you would want to try to
disenfranchise anybody,'' Griffo added.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he still was a Giuliani supporter, Griffo said:
''Presently, I am.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rome mayor said he hadn't yet called Giuliani or his aides,
but planned to.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to make an effort to reach out to make a
determination if there's a problem and what their problem is,''
Griffo said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and Pataki, who headed up Bush's successful New York
primary campaign, got in a snit just before the voting when the
mayor refused to join in on attacks against McCain. Giuliani said
that while he was backing Bush, he considered McCain a friend. The
Pataki camp complained that Giuliani was more worried about turning
off McCain supporters who he needed for the Senate race than about
helping Bush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
