<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCall calls on Pataki to speak out on NYPD shooting  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- State Comptroller H. Carl McCall says Gov.
George Pataki should speak out on police shooting victim Patrick
Dorismond's death and convene a commission to investigate the
relationship between the police and the communities they patrol.
</P>
<P>
   McCall, the first black to win election to statewide office,
also criticized New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's handling of
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a time for thoughtful action, not antagonistic
attack,'' McCall, a Democrat, said in a letter to the Republican
governor Wednesday. ''Absent any leadership from the mayor, it is
imperative you become involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki thinks McCall's letter is just a political ploy, Pataki
spokesman Michael McKeon said. McCall has expressed interest in
running for governor in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would have expected the comptroller to join the governor in
waiting for a full investigation of the facts of this case before
rushing to judgment,'' McKeon said. ''We're certain that is the
tact he would have taken in the past. Unfortunately, it's clear
that his political ambitions now come first.''
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller, who said Giuliani ''has chosen to drive a wedge
to further divide the city'' and is ''unable or unwilling to
provide the leadership to restore calm and confidence'' called on
Pataki to appoint a commission to study NYPD-related issues,
including the use of street crime units, officers' use of deadly
force, racial profiling and minority police recruitment.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every New Yorker wants to have trust in the police officers
that patrol their neighborhoods. Unfortunately, that confidence and
trust has been undermined,'' McCall said. ''And Mayor Giuliani is
doing nothing to restore that trust. The governor must step up.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond, 26, was fatally shot by a New York City policeman
last week during an attempted drug sting outside a midtown
Manhattan bar. He was unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   After the shooting, Giuliani defended the police officer and
released Dorismond's criminal record, including a sealed juvenile
offense. Democrats, including U.S. Senate candidate Hillary
Clinton, have since criticized the mayor's handling of the
situation, including the release of the sealed record.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver has even scheduled hearings on
how Giuliani and the NYPD got hold of the sealed juvenile records
and how to stop it from happening in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am saddened that the mayor is continuing his pattern of
dividing and polarizing New Yorkers,'' Clinton said. ''At a time
when New Yorkers are in desperate need of leadership that can bring
the city together, Rudy Giuliani continues to tear people apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has lashed back, saying all of the attacks are
political in nature. ''The reality is that this is a politicized
response ... this is political piling on,'' he said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   McCall, who also has clashed with Giuliani in the past when the
mayor challenged his right to audit the books of New York City
agencies, said politics has nothing to do with what he's trying to
do.
</P>
<P>
   ''The police are fearful about going into some communities and
some communities are fearful about the police being in them,''
McCall said. ''So I don't know who else to turn to except the
governor because the mayor is incapable of addressing this
situation and it's not just a New York City problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-23-00 0011 </TRAILER>
