<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stores seek relief from gas, cigarette taxes  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- More and more these days, when cars roll
into Charlie Schmidt's service station in Sanborn it's not a
fill-up the drivers want.
</P>
<P>
   It's directions to the Tuscorora Indian Reservation, about two
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel like that's a slap in the face,'' the businessman says.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers are undoubtedly looking for the cheaper gas and
cigarettes available from his Native American competitors.
</P>
<P>
   It's just one way consumers are skirting high taxes, say gas
station and convenience store owners who rely on fuel and tobacco
sales for two-thirds of their business. Add competition from the
Internet and border states, they say, and it's getting harder to
stay open.
</P>
<P>
   While encouraged by proposals before lawmakers to limit Internet
sales of tobacco and temporarily suspend the state sales tax on
gasoline, the New York Association of Convenience Stores on
Wednesday said more relief is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''This issue is not about the current cost of gasoline nor is it
an issue about smoking,'' said Robert Newman, president of NOCO
Express and chairman-elect of NYACS. ''This is an issue of tax
fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statewide public awareness campaign, the 3,000-member
association is taking aim at the state's doubling of the cigarette
tax to a highest-in-the-nation $1.11 effective March 1, and the
state sales and petroleum business taxes levied on gasoline. All
should be reduced or repealed, NYACS said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The convenience store industry contributes over one billion
dollars a year into the western New York economy alone,'' said
NYACS President Jim Calvin. ''However the current tax structure
threatens many operators and we anticipate that this flow of
dollars will shrink considerably.''
</P>
<P>
   Permanently eliminating the sales tax on gasoline and lowering
the 13-cent per gallon petroleum business tax to a nickel would
bring the cost of gas down by 12 to 15 cents a gallon without
depleting funds set aside for road and bridge maintenance,
supporters said. A state tax official did not return phone calls
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   State taxes add between 31 and 33 cents to the price of gasoline
in New York, while the state tax in Massachusetts is 21 cents and
in New Jersey, 14 cents. No state tax is charged on reservation gas
sales.
</P>
<P>
   As for cigarettes, the state should roll back the 55-cent tax
increase, NYACS said, or begin collecting tax from reservation
cigarette sales, an unlikely prospect. Cigarettes sell for about
$2.29 on tax-exempt reservations and $4 to $5 a pack elsewhere in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Calvin said members are reporting sales decreases of 30 to 50
percent since the increase took effect.
</P>
<P>
   The cigarette tax is designed to raise $400 million a year to
help fund a new medical insurance program for working poor New
Yorkers. Advocates predict it will compel 270,000 adult New Yorkers
to quit smoking and 30,000 youngsters not to take up the habit.
</P>
<P>
   Calvin said that is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the universe of smokers were to gradually shrink and
thousands of smokers quit smoking because the higher tax made it
too expensive, store owners could and would adapt,'' he said. ''But
that's not what is happening here. Rather than exiting tobacco
road, smokers are simply detouring to the reservations, the
Internet and border states to avoid paying the higher tax.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
