<HEADLINE> Taiwan Shares Surge  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwan shares closed higher for the third
consecutive session Thursday, boosted by a 3.25 percent jump in the
Nasdaq composite index and growing confidence in President-elect
Chen Shui-bian, analysts and traders said.
</P>
<P>
   The Weighted Price Index surged 5.1 percent, up 464.48 points at
9,533.87. On Wednesday the index had risen 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were encouraged by Chen's circumspect statements on
future relations with Beijing, which dispelled initial concerns he
may assert Taiwan independence and provoke a war with China.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the time being, the atmosphere is good on the market side
and on the politics side,'' said Alan Tseng, a senior analyst at
Capital Securities Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Chen has been conciliatory toward Beijing and investors almost
immediately shook off any war fears early this week, focusing
instead on Taiwan's bright economic outlook.
</P>
<P>
   China and Taiwan have been governed separately since they split
amid civil war in 1949, although Beijing views Taiwan as territory
that must eventually reunify with the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, turnover was a hefty $7.9 billion, up from
$7.1 billion Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most active shares was chipmaker Macronix
International Corp., which gained 16 cents to $2.66 (82.5 Taiwan
dollars). United Microelectronics Corp. rose 22 cents to $3.53
(109.5 Taiwan dollars), while Winbond Electronics Corp. rose 18
cents to $2.83 (88 Taiwan dollars).
</P>
