<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer Who Defended McCarthy Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Warren E. Magee, a lawyer whose best-known
clients were Nazi war criminals and Sen. Joseph R. McCarthy, is
dead at age 91.
</P>
<P>
   Magee, beginning in 1948, took part in the Nuremberg war crimes
trials by defending Baron Ernst von Weizsaecker, the former German
secretary of state and wartime ambassador to the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   The German diplomat received a five-year prison term, later
commuted, and Magee's vigorous defense was rewarded with a Papal
Gold Medal from Pope Pius XII.
</P>
<P>
   Magee defended McCarthy, R-Wis., in a $2 million
libel-slander-conspiracy suit against Sen. William Benton, D-Conn.
Benton had called the Wisconsin senator a corrupt liar deserving of
expulsion from the Senate. McCarthy gained notoriety for leading
investigations of alleged communist infiltration in the U.S.
government in the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Magee, a resident of Bethesda, Md., died Feb. 25 at his winter
home in Tampa, Fla.
</P>
</TEXT>
