<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suns 114, Kings 93  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- A broken ankle to Jason Kidd tempered the Phoenix
Suns' 114-93 victory over the Sacramento Kings on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star guard will miss the rest of the regular season
after breaking his left ankle with .2 seconds left in the first
half while racing the clock to take a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Fie, the Suns director of media relations, said Kidd
fractured a bone high in the left ankle and will have surgery on
Thursday. She said Kidd is ''questionable for the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Kidd is a serious blow to the Suns, who also lost
forward Tom Gugliotta for the season when he ruptured ligaments in
his left knee on March 10.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Robinson scored a game-high 26 points for the Suns, who
remained 1{ games ahead of the San Antonio Spurs for fourth place
in the Western Conference. The Spurs beat the Los Angeles Clippers
103-78 earlier Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve Rodney Rogers had 18 points and Randy Livingston,
subbing for Kidd, added 17 for Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Webber, who battled foul trouble much of the game, scored
16 points to lead Sacramento. Vlade Divac and Jason Williams each
had 14 for the Kings, who saw their three-game winning streak
snapped.
</P>
<P>
   After the Kings had taken a 52-50 lead, Kidd took an inbounds
pass and drove down the right sideline before Williams forced him
to stop. Kidd fumbled the ball out of bounds, then spun and reached
for the ball. When the clock stopped, Kidd remained doubled over,
holding his lower calves.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd, who had no points but seven assists and five rebounds,
tried to walk off the court, but took one tentative step before he
was carried into the locker room by teammates.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns, who won for the 16th time in 19 games, rallied after
Kidd departed.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Marion hit a 14-foot jumper and Robinson added a 3-pointer
in the first 50 seconds of the third quarter as Phoenix took the
lead for good, 55-52.
</P>
<P>
   Webber tied the game at 58 with a long jump shot with 9:54
remaining. But Marion scored six straight points and Penny Hardaway
added a 3-pointer to spark a 15-0 run and give the Suns a 73-58
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns hit 16 of 24 shots to outscore the Kings 38-22 en route
to an 88-74 lead after three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson took advantage of two quick fouls on Webber to help the
Suns take the lead in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   While guarded by Webber, Robinson missed his two field-goal
attempts and committed a turnover. After Webber left with his
second foul with 9:17 left in the quarter, Robinson scored 13
points on 5-of-6 shooting to lead Phoenix to a 34-25 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Everything reversed in the second quarter as Phoenix, which shot
70 percent in the first period (14-of-20), missed nine of its first
12 field-goal attempts. The Suns went 5:42 without a field goal and
committed 11 of their 18 first-half turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings hit seven of their first 12 shots, including Darrick
Martin's 3-pointer with 4:34 left in the half that gave Sacramento
a 44-41 lead.	   
Notes: The Suns are 28-5 when they score more than 100 points. ...
The Kings, who lead the NBA in scoring, were held below the
100-point mark for the fourth time in five games ... Phoenix's
16-point second-quarter matched a season low and the Suns' 38
points in the third quarter set a season high. ... Robinson has led
the Suns in scoring in four straight games and five of six. ...
Webber was 6-of-6 from the floor and 4-of-4 from the free-throw
line. Webber also was whistled for a technical after he'd left the
game in the fourth quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 0044 </TRAILER>
