<DOCNO> APW20000323.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Free gun locks offered by a gun industry group  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EASTON, Conn. (AP) -- Marilyn Davies has two good reasons for
getting gun locks: under the same roof where she keeps 10 guns, she
also babysits her two grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Even though she's told them over and over again, ''don't play
with the guns,'' she can't be sure they'll listen to her. So Davies
and her husband Bob, once competitive target shooters, were among
the first Easton residents to pick up free gun locks offered by a
gun industry group.
</P>
<P>
   ''You try to reinforce, reinforce, reinforce, but there might be
that one time they might pick it up,'' said Davies, who watches her
grandchildren in her home two or three days a week.
</P>
<P>
   During the last six months, the National Shooting Sports
Foundation has given away 50,000 locks in 28 cities, towns and
counties across the country. Another 111 communities will begin
distributing locks this summer.
</P>
<P>
   In Augusta, Ga., sheriffs have been unable to keep up with
demand. Five thousands locks have been given out since November.
</P>
<P>
   ''We ran out last weekend,'' said Mark Gibbons, an assistant to
Augusta Mayor Bob Young.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have parents with kids, we have hunters, we had a U.S.
Congressman come in and get some locks from us. It's pretty much
across the board -- businesspeople, truck drivers, you name it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Orlando, Fla., 3,000 locks have been distributed to
residents, plus another 633 to each of the city's police officers.
</P>
<P>
   And in Minneapolis, police gave out 1,000 locks on the first day
of their giveaway last week after an earlier survey revealed that
14,000 of the 34,000 residents with guns in their homes admitted
they were not locked up.
</P>
<P>
   In the raging debate over gun violence, gun locks have become
hot commodities.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, New York Gov. George Pataki called for mandatory
trigger locks for all guns.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Smith &AMP; Wesson -- the nation's largest gun
manufacturer -- agreed to provide external safety locks on all its
handguns within 60 days and internal locks within two years.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Jorgensen, a spokesman for Smith &AMP; Wesson, said the company
has shipped trigger or cable locks with all of its handguns since
September 1997. He said the company will continue to provide those
locks until it can develop internal locks.
</P>
<P>
   SigArms Corp., in Exeter, N.H., began supplying trigger locks
with its guns about two years ago. Fairfield-based Sturm, Ruger has
shipped its pistols and revolvers in lock boxes with padlocks for
more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The National Shooting Sports Foundation is distributing cable
locks, which resemble bicycle locks. The cables are pulled through
gun handles or barrels to prevent the weapon from being loaded or
fired. They differ from trigger locks, which keep the trigger from
being pulled, but allow the gun to remain loaded while the lock is
in place.
</P>
<P>
   In Easton, a woodsy town of about 6,500, including many hunters,
about a dozen people showed up to pick up cable locks Tuesday
evening as police began the program.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Kusovitski, a dentist, has four guns in his house --
three pistols and a .22-caliber rifle. He already has locks on two
of his guns. Even though he stores the other two in a locked safe,
Kusovitski picked up two cable locks as an extra deterrence for his
three children.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think many people don't take the responsibility seriously,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Aiken County, S.C., sheriffs have given out 500 locks since
November.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you have tragic cases like the little boy who shot the
little girl in Michigan ... we are being proactive in this
community to hopefully prevent a similar incident,'' said Lt.
Michael Frank.
</P>
<P>
   While the communities who receive the free locks praise the
program, some gun control groups question the motive and timing of
the National Shooting Sports Foundation, a Newtown-based trade
group representing about 1,800 gun, munitions and accessory
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I definitely think it is a public relations move largely due
to the fact that they haven't done anything to make guns safer in
so many years,'' said Nancy Hwa, a spokeswoman for Handgun Control
Inc., the nation's largest gun control lobbying group.
</P>
<P>
   Hwa said she believes the program was started to deflect
criticism after a barrage of lawsuits were filed against the gun
industry last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact that they undertook this campaign basically shows
that the lawsuits have merit,'' Hwa said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the sports foundation, however, insist that they
began working on the project about a year before the first lawsuits
were filed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has everything to do with public safety and nothing to do
with public relations. We have initiated many national safety
programs over many, many decades, and this is another such
program,'' said Doug Painter, executive director of the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   To pay for the locks, the foundation set up a voluntary 1
percent assessment on industry sales. Painter said about 60
firearms and munitions manufacturers have agreed to the assessment.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Shooting Sports Foundation: http://www.nssf.org
</P>
<P>
   Handgun Control Inc.: http://www.handguncontrol.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
