<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Court upholds state's law  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNE YOUMANS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The state Supreme Court has rejected the
appeal of a man who claimed his conviction for possessing child
pornography should be overturned because the law does not define
the term minor.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond C. Ehlers Jr., convicted in Middlesex Superior Court in
1998, had argued the law was unconstitutionally vague. He also
claimed his crime did not fall under the statute, which requires
the illicit action take place before an audience.
</P>
<P>
   The high court ruled Wednesday the law's intentions are clear
and the photographs Ehlers had are proof of an audience of at least
one, the photographer.
</P>
<P>
   The case stems from the February 1996 arrest of Ehlers, who
prosecutors said was found with photographs of children in the
nude. Some allegedly depicted children performing sex acts with
each other and with adults.
</P>
<P>
   Ehlers sought to have the case dismissed, arguing the state's
child pornography statute does not specify whether a minor is a
child under 18, 17 or 16. He said that because the law concerns his
First Amendment rights, he can challenge its constitutionality on
the basis that it is vague.
</P>
<P>
   Ehlers also argued the law stipulates an audience must be
present or the action must be a live performance in order to be
considered pornography. He said the photos he had showed no
spectators to the acts.
</P>
<P>
   The Middlesex Superior Court judge denied the request and Ehlers
pleaded no contest on the condition that he have the right to
appeal. He received a three-year suspended sentence and was ordered
to serve three years probation.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court, in a unanimous ruling, upheld the lower
court's decision. Justice William J. Sullivan, writing the opinion,
conceded the law does not specifically define the term ''minor.''
But he said related statutes clearly define a minor as a child
under 16 and Ehlers, having admitted possessing photographs of
younger children, has no basis to challenge the law for vagueness.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan also said that because child pornography is not
protected under First Amendment rights to free speech, Ehlers
cannot challenge the constitutionality of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ''The defendant had fair warning that his conduct was
prohibited,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ehlers' contention that an audience must be present, the
high court found that the statute specifies an ''audience'' to
discourage the market for child pornography. Ehlers' interpretation
of an audience as two or more people watching or depicted in a
reproduction of an illicit act would negate the statute's impact,
the court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   ''Marketers and consumers of child pornography could avoid
prosecution merely by ensuring that their pornographic materials do
not depict any audience members,'' Sullivan wrote.
</P>
<P>
   An audience, the court found, could consist of a photographer,
anyone who witnessed the acts or anyone who viewed a reproduction
of the acts.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Donovan, an attorney for Ehlers, faulted the high court for
relying on related statutes in defining the term ''minor.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's significant that neither the state of
Connecticut, a learned judge of the Superior Court nor I could
agree on the definition of age as contained in the statute,'' he
said. ''That speaks to the fact the common man would be lost within
the words of the statute.''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan also said the Legislature should remove reference to
''audience'' in the law to avoid confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you include a term in a statute, it should have meaning,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who answered the phone at the Ehlers' home in Haddam
said he was not available for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-23-00 0106 </TRAILER>
