<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Third person charged in shooting of 8-year-old  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- A third man has been charged with
capital felony and murder in the killing an 8-year-old boy and his
mother.
</P>
<P>
   Gary ''Mello G'' Garner was expected to be a key prosecution
witness in their cases against Russell and Adrian Peeler. Police
say Garner admitted driving the getaway car for Adrian Peeler after
the Jan.7, 1999 shootings of Leroy ''B.J.'' Brown and Karen Clarke.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors claim the pair were shot to prevent the boy from
testifying against Russell Peeler in the 1998 murder of Clarke's
boyfriend, Rudolph Snead Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Peeler is currently serving a 105-year sentence for that
slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Garner, who had previously been charged with only conspiracy to
commit murder, was arrested on the new charges during a pretrial
conference. He faces a possible death sentence if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut Post, citing sources close to the investigation,
reported Wednesday that the new charges are an attempt by the state
to put pressure on Garner, who recently reneged on an agreement to
testify against the Peelers.
</P>
<P>
   Garner, 30, of Bridgeport, allegedly drove Adrian Peeler to
Clarke's North End home and waited outside during the slayings. He
then drove Peeler to a Milford motel, police said.
</P>
<P>
   But Russell Peeler's girlfriend, Angelina Keene, told police
that on a prior occasion her boyfriend had asked Garner to kill the
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Garner is awaiting sentencing in federal court on charges of
selling crack cocaine. He faces a potential life sentence on that
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, lawyers for the Peelers asked the state Supreme Court
to hear their appeal of a judge's ruling keeping a letter from a
state witness out of their hands.
</P>
<P>
   In a motion filed in state Supreme Court, the attorneys asked
for an expedited appeal of a decision by trial Judge G. Sarsfield
Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Ford refused to turn over to the defense a letter written by the
state's eyewitness, Josephine Lee, to her lawyer. The letter
inadvertently fell into the hands of a prosecutor. Ford said that
while the contents of the letter may help the defense, it is
inadmissible under lawyer-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers maintain a delay in hearing the appeal would render
the murder trial constitutionally flawed.
</P>
<P>
   If the Supreme Court agrees to hear the appeal, it would delay
the start of Russell Peeler's trial, set to begin next month.
Adrian Peeler is not expected to be tried before summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
