<HEADLINE> Disagreement leads to three budget proposals  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The refusal by state Senate Democrats to
reopen Connecticut's two-year budget is drawing fire from both
Republicans and House Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   A division of House and Senate members of the Appropriations
Committee on Wednesday means there are now three budget adjustment
plans: one from the House, one from the Senate and one backed by
Republican Gov. John G. Rowland and GOP lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican proposal calls for tax cuts and program spending
adjustments, but Senate Democrats have refused to consider making
major spending changes.
</P>
<P>
   Democratics have been bickering since early February when Senate
leaders said they would agree to only technical revision in the
biennial budget approved last year by the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their intention is to preclude discussion, preclude
deliberations and preclude this body from doing what it does every
year, and that is pass a budget for the people of Connecticut,''
said Sen. William Aniskovich, R-Branford.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Patricia Dillon, D-New Haven, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''This process will be tainted, and the public ... will watch
it. I beg my friends in the Senate, do not first exclude the people
and then deny your own colleagues the right to participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Crisco, co-chairman of the Appropriations Committee,
said splitting the committee would speed up the budget
negotiations. The legislative session ends in seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''We worked very diligently trying to come up with an
agreement,'' said Crisco, D-Woodbridge. ''That agreement cannot be
reached ... and I feel that we have no other options than to
proceed the way we are proceeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Pro Tempore Kevin Sullivan and House Speaker
Moira Lyons downplayed the skirmish in Appropriations, and said
they will begin negotiating with other legislative leaders on April
4.
</P>
<P>
   ''We still have three basic approaches to this budget -- all of
which are negotiable, all of which are compromisable and all of
which will lead to a conclusion that's bipartisan and successful,''
said Sullivan, D-West Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said the last time the Appropriations Committee split
to pass two budget bills was in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The three proposed changes for the 2001 budget are close, and
don't stray too far from the original $12.1 billion already
approved by the Legislature. Rowland's revisions push the budget to
$12.2 billion; the Senate plan increases it to $12.31 billion; and
the House bill inflates it to $12.35 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Genuario, R-Norwalk, criticized the proposal from
Senate Democrats for using too much of the state's $241 million
surplus for ongoing costs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their bill is not an adjustment bill, Genuario said. ''It uses
the gimmick of invading the surplus to fund operating budgets,
thereby setting up a significant deficit.''
</P>
<P>
   And Marc Ryan, Rowland's budget director, said both the House
and Senate leadership plans will put the state over the mandated
spending cap. He said Rowland's adjustments will keep the budget
well below the cap.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan insisted that the plans backed by his caucus and House
Democrats would not break the spending cap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-23-00 0107 </TRAILER>
