<HEADLINE> Fox Entertainment Head Herzog Quits  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Fourteen months after he left Comedy Central to
take over programming for the struggling Fox network, Doug Herzog
is calling it quits.
</P>
<P>
   Herzog has been trying to leave since one of his predecessors,
Sandy Grushow, was installed last November to supervise the network
and Fox's television studio.
</P>
<P>
   His year in the hot seat was a nightmare of falling ratings,
failing shows and fallout from the ''Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire'' fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would imagine that the worst is behind us,'' Herzog said
Wednesday. ''I'm sorry I had to live through it. That's timing. At
the same time I'm walking out of here with two comedy successes to
look back on.''
</P>
<P>
   His slate of new programs for last fall, including the
critically praised comedy ''Action'' and the drama ''Harsh Realm,''
all failed in the ratings. Fox's average prime-time viewership has
slumped from 11.2 million last year to 9.3 million this season.
</P>
<P>
   The promising performance of midseason replacement comedies
''Malcolm in the Middle'' and ''Titus'' has given Fox hope
recently. Yet two stalwarts of its schedule, ''Beverly Hills,
90210'' and ''Party of Five,'' are in their last season and Fox
still isn't sure that ''The X-Files'' is coming back for another
year.
</P>
<P>
   Herzog, 40, was Fox's fifth entertainment president in eight
years.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Grushow was widely seen as a no-confidence
vote and set up an awkward shotgun marriage in the executive suite.
</P>
<P>
   ''The landscape changed and it ended up being a different
situation than the one I had signed up for,'' Herzog said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has also taken heat for its reality specials with car chases
and attacking animals. Grushow said the network is leaving that
genre behind.
</P>
<P>
   Herzog said his departure has nothing to do with last month's
ill-fated TV marriage of Rick Rockwell and Darva Conger. The
special attracted a storm of criticism when it came out that a
former fiancee had served Rockwell with a restraining order and
Conger quickly moved for an annulment.
</P>
<P>
   The network's investigation into the special is expected to be
complete by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Grushow will assume Herzog's duties through this spring, when
Fox must present a new schedule to advertisers, and search for a
successor this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''Doug has made important and lasting contributions to the
success of the network, particularly in the area of live action
comedies,'' Grushow said. ''We wish him the same success in his
future endeavors that has always characterized his career.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
