<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Population Surge Surprises County  </HEADLINE>
By SONJA BARISIC, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUSSEX, Va. (AP) -- Sussex County is bursting with peanut, cotton
and hog farms. There are no fancy office buildings, traffic-choked
highways or even suburbs to speak of.
</P>
<P>
   For culture seekers, there's a folk art museum and a peanut
museum. Gourmands make do with the Virginia Diner and its tempting
Southern-style buttermilk biscuits, salty Virginia ham and peanut
pie.
</P>
<P>
   This 496-square-mile rural patch of south-central Virginia is
the fastest-growing county in the nation?
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes. Sussex's population surged by 22.8 percent to 12,345
people between 1998 and last year, according to Census Bureau
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 2,291 new residents, however, moved into
less-than-plush accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew we were going to have some changes as a result of two
state maximum-security prisons being built,'' County Administrator
Mary E. Jones laughed when asked about the population explosion.
</P>
<P>
   The Sussex I prison opened in May 1998 and has 1,160 inmates,
state Department of Corrections spokesman Larry Traylor said.
Sussex II opened in January 1999 and houses inmates convicted in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 800 people work at the prisons; Traylor did not know
how many live in Sussex County.
</P>
<P>
   County officials say the prisons eventually could help spur real
growth and economic development in Sussex and reverse a steady
decline in population since World War II. Young people too often
must leave to find jobs or further their education, said Jones, who
grew up in the county.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to more people, the county got a wastewater
treatment plant and public water system from the state for becoming
home to the prisons. Thinking those improvements will attract more
businesses, county officials are making plans to build a commerce
park, said Andre Greene, the county's director of planning.
</P>
<P>
   ''The prisons allowed the county to do things it would not have
been able to do, or would have taken longer to do,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Sussex, formed in 1754, has much to offer with Interstate 95,
other major U.S. highways and rail lines running through the
county, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The county is 45 miles southeast of Richmond and 60 miles
northwest of the Hampton Roads region and its ports. It's a
four-hour drive from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   County residents already enjoying that rural lifestyle said they
were surprised to hear that the prisons boosted the population so
much.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh really? Well,'' said Shirley S. Yancey, who lives on six
acres in the county. She said she never gave much thought to the
prisons when there was talk about them being built.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's one of those things you know is going to happen, so why
get all shook up?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The Census Bureau: http://www.census.gov
</P>
<P>
   http://www.uscounties.com/Virginia/Sussex-County/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.sussex.k12.va.us/SUSSEX--MAIN.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
