<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mentally ill man convicted of subway shove murder  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A schizophrenic man who pushed a woman to her
death under the wheels of a subway train has been convicted of
murder in a case that led to tougher laws regarding the mentally
ill.
</P>
<P>
   A jury in Manhattan's state Supreme Court took just three hours
to convict Andrew Goldstein, 30, of second-degree murder Wednesday
in the shove slaying of Kendra Ann Webdale, 32, on Jan. 3, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, whose first trial on the same charge ended in a hung
jury, faces a maximum sentence of 25 years to life in prison when
Justice Carol Berkman sentences him on April 6.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Canfield, Goldstein's lawyer, shouted, ''I have no
comment!'' as he and an associate fled down a stairwell from the
11th-floor courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Several jurors said later that they were convinced that
Goldstein is mentally ill but that he acted violently for reasons
other than insanity. They also said they hope he is put some place
where he can get help.
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict was read, Goldstein showed no emotion, but
members of the Webdale family wept and hugged each other.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been such a nightmare that I wouldn't want to use the
word happy,'' said Patricia Webdale, the victim's mother, ''but I
feel like jumping for joy.'' She added, ''I hope we learn from
Kendra's death.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Webdale, Kendra's father, said, ''I'm happy that it's over
and I'm happy with the outcome. I'm sorry that we had to sit
through this twice.''
</P>
<P>
   The victim's sister, Kim Webdale, said, ''The jury's verdict
absolutely reinforced our opinion. The verdict shows that Andrew
Goldstein was violent for reasons other than his psychosis.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm happy that he'll be in a place where he won't be able to
kill or hurt anyone for a very long time,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal is not quite over for the Webdales. They have several
multimillion-dollar civil lawsuits pending against the city and
several mental facilities that had treated Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, of Queens, was charged with second-degree murder
after he pushed Webdale to her death onto the tracks in front of an
oncoming N train at the 23rd Street-Broadway station. Webdale, who
aspired to a career in the recording industry was originally from
Fredonia, N.Y., a town near Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Because Goldstein attacked Webdale while refusing to take his
antipsychotic medicine, the case led to a law -- called ''Kendra's
Law'' -- last year that allows for violent mental patients to be
medicated by force.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm pleased the Webdale family has received the justice they
have sought for so long. Out of this tragedy came Kendra's Law,
which will help people with mental illness while protecting New
Yorkers,'' Gov. George Pataki said in a statement. ''The jury
verdict ends a sad chapter for the Webdale family but the reforms
they championed will help all New Yorkers long into the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers in both trials admitted that Goldstein pushed
Webdale but said he did it because he is mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   In the second trial, Canfield cited defense psychiatrist Dr.
Spencer Eth, who testified that Goldstein had suffered an
''earthquake'' in his mind and was not aware of what he was doing
when he pushed Webdale onto the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   But Assistant District Attorney William Greenbaum argued that it
was revenge, not mental illness, that drove Goldstein. Rebuffed by
one blonde woman on the platform, he targeted Webdale to get even,
Greenbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenbaum quoted prosecution psychiatrist Dr. Angela Hegarty,
who said violence is not a feature of schizophrenia. She also said
that the planning and execution of the act suggests he was
completely aware of what he did.
</P>
<P>
   One juror, a nurse, said she was not quite sure at first that
intentional murder was the correct verdict but after thinking about
Goldstein's planning, timing and execution of the push, she was
convinced to convict.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-23-00 0135 </TRAILER>
