<DOCNO> APW20000323.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Holy Land Lives its Extremes  </HEADLINE>
By MORT ROSENBLUM, AP Special Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Deep within the Church of the Holy Sepulcher, a
priest's angry shouts bounced off ancient walls, giving
Christendom's holiest shrine the air of a rug bazaar on a bad day.
</P>
<P>
   ''Okay, no more! Go!'' the corpulent Greek Orthodox priest
bellowed at lined-up tourists, slamming the doors to the small
vaulted tomb where tradition holds Christ was buried and
resurrected. He fumed, flailing the air in unexplained ire.
</P>
<P>
   A disconsolate Spaniard turned his palms heavenward when asked
what happened. His party of 27 had come to visit sacred sites for
the millennium, just like John Paul II. The pope is having an
easier time of it.
</P>
<P>
   Against the backdrop of a Jubilee papal pilgrimage, life in the
Holy Land continues as usual: Spiritual highs are offset by sudden
tension in a wider context of relaxed Middle Eastern laissez-faire.
</P>
<P>
   At Holy Sepulcher, the pontiff's visit Sunday will be the first
time in long memory that the six Christian denominations that
occupy it pray together for peace and goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   Since an uneasy compromise of 1757, custody has been shared by
Roman Catholics, Greek Orthodox, Armenian Orthodox, Syrian
Jacobites, Ethiopians and Copts. Because of mutual mistrust, a
local Muslim family keeps the door key.
</P>
<P>
   The Greek priest plowed into the crowd without a word when asked
his name and his grievance. Later, a Franciscan friar smiled
ruefully when asked to describe interfaith relations at Holy
Sepulcher. A disgrace, he replied.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   John Paul first saw the Jordan Valley and Jerusalem beyond as
Moses must have seen them, planted with emerald fields from fresh
rains and a mild winter, speckled with vivid crimson wild poppies,
a land of promise.
</P>
<P>
   He rode up Mount Nebo in Jordan past silvery green olive trees,
citrus groves, and vegetable gardens. From the summit, the
breath-catching panorama took in purple mountains and open plains.
</P>
<P>
   Had he stopped to chat alongside the road, however, farmers
would have given him a different picture, close-up. In the 3,500
years of human progress since Moses, a lot of promise has gone out
of the land.
</P>
<P>
   For most of its final course, for example, the River Jordan is
no more than a saline, polluted brown trickle that can be forded in
a popemobile. Between the Israelis and Jordanians, it is pumped
nearly dry from its headwaters.
</P>
<P>
   ''Farmers around here depend on rain for their crops, and
domestic water supply comes by pipe from Israel,'' said Mohammad
Waheeb, the Jordanian archaeologist who unearthed a site that might
have been where John baptized Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Two millennia ago, he said, numerous fresh springs fed
tributaries to the Jordan which ran, as the old writings say, muddy
and wide. Now most springs have dried up and the washes -- wadis --
run only briefly after heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Holy Land, water is a fighting word.
</P>
<P>
   But if the pontiff did not stop to investigate, he is hardly
unaware.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just recently, I received a call from the Vatican wanting to
know all about water, food supplies and agriculture in the Middle
East,'' said Shaul Arlosoroff, an eminent Israeli expert in those
matters. ''The pope wanted to know.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The pope captivated the ancient heart of Bethlehem on Tuesday,
but a block off Manger Square, it was another world entirely.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul's Mass was broadcast live. Just up the old
cobblestones of Najajeheh Street, however, no one watched the
television glowing in a hole-in-the-wall barber shop. Anyway, it
showed Kermit the Frog, singing in Arabic.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was different at the eternal open-air city market.
Wizened old men and women in shawls squatted behind colorful wares:
monster cauliflowers, odd-shaped tasty tomatoes, fat pomelos,
garlic bunches, spices, hot peppers.
</P>
<P>
   Racks of lamb and beef flanks hung outside on hooks. Pungent
odors of grilled kebabs wafted over open sacks of orange lentils
and multihued beans. Friends exchanged local gossip, pausing to
suck at hubbly-bubbly water pipes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I went to see him, for fifteen minutes,'' Amir Hermas said in
his spacious store that sold everything from kitchenware to Koranic
calligraphy mounted on green felt. ''He is an important man, and we
must welcome him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hermas, a Muslim, was more interested in what John Paul had to
say about Palestinian rights today than a son of God born three
blocks away in another era.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to the square, John Shaheen sat in his empty cafe built
under ancient arches. A Christian, he was happy to have the pope
nearby, but he did not close up shop to see him. Shaheen was not
sure what to think about the visit.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must find a way with the Jews,'' he said. ''It's a small
land, but both can fit. Maybe the pope can push just a little bit
and make it work.'' He paused a moment to draw at a cigarette, then
added: ''Or not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
