<HEADLINE> Pope Has Physical Ups and Downs  </HEADLINE>
By VICTOR L. SIMPSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- With his days packed full of events, speeches,
car trips and helicopter rides, the Holy Land pilgrimage is one of
the biggest tests in years for the frail Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   The pontiff spends 11 to 12 hours in the public spotlight each
day, interrupted only by the afternoon rest time planners sketched
in for him.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting Bethlehem on Wednesday, John Paul sat slumped in his
chair on the altar during Mass in Manger Square, hands trembling as
he waited during a pause for the Muslim call to prayer from a
mosque a hundred yards away.
</P>
<P>
   But at the end of a long day, he joked with Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat after accepting a gold medal for his moral support of
the Palestinian ''struggle,'' then walked unaided to a waiting
Israeli helicopter that would fly him back to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Such ups and downs are increasingly frequent for the pope, who
turns 80 in May and suffers from a variety of ailments. He is
hobbled by a shuffling gait, slurred speech and a tremble in both
hands -- symptoms of Parkinson's, a progressive neurological
disorder.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican has added a second personal physician to the papal
entourage, but Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro-Valls insisted
last week that this was not done out of any particular concern.
</P>
<P>
   The pope was clearly shaking during a stop in the Caucasus
mountain nation of Georgia last October, but aides blamed that on a
chill from the sudden change following the previous stop in balmy
India.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's current trip, the 91st pilgrimage of his 22-year
papacy, contrasts with some recent travels, which were short
journeys with schedules purposely kept light.
</P>
<P>
   His schedule Wednesday, for example, began at 8 a.m. when he was
driven from his Jerusalem quarters to a heliport and then flown to
Al-Maghtas near the banks of the Jordan River, one of two reputed
sites of Christ's baptism.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the pope was flown to Bethlehem for a ceremony
welcoming him to the Palestinian territories, a two-hour Mass, a
stop at the grotto believed to be Christ's birthplace, a visit to a
Palestinian refugee camp and the meeting with Arafat. He delivered
four speeches. His day officially ended at 7:30 p.m. upon his
return to his Jerusalem residence.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not a day he would have willingly passed up.
</P>
<P>
   Bethlehem, he said, was the ''heart'' of his millennium
pilgrimage, a trip he said he had first hoped to make for Christmas
1978 -- just two months after he assumed the papacy. ''That was not
possible then, and was not possible until now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''How can I fail to praise the God of all mercies'' for allowing
the trip to take place, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The pontiff's trip began Monday in Jordan and concludes Sunday
in Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
