<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Travelers Prepare for US Air Strike  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL TOLME, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Caroline Suarez isn't worried about getting home from Florida if
US Airways shuts down Saturday to avoid walkouts by flight
attendants. For her, it will just mean more time in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going on vacation,'' Suarez, 35, said as she waited
Wednesday at Philadelphia International Airport with her husband
and 3-year-old son for a flight to Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   If their return flight is canceled, Suarez said her family will
just extend their trip.
</P>
<P>
   Other US Airways ticketholders were not so calm. Many revised
their vacation plans, booked backup tickets on other airlines or
canceled trips.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways, based in Arlington, Va., has said it will shut down
rather than face random walkouts by its 10,000 flight attendants,
who want increased pay and benefits. The flight attendants have
threatened to disrupt flights on 49 of the airline's busiest
routes, a strategy they have dubbed CHAOS, for ''Create Havoc
Around Our System.''.
</P>
<P>
   A shutdown would hit hardest in the East, where the airline
controls a third of the market. Charlotte, Philadelphia and
Pittsburgh, all US Airways hubs, would be affected most.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Stephen Wolf, chief executive Rakesh Gangwal and
negotiators for the nation's sixth-largest airline have been
meeting daily with representatives from the Association of Flight
Attendants in Washington, hoping to reach agreement before the
strike deadline of 12:01 a.m. EST Saturday. The talks were being
overseen by the National Mediation Board.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers such as Wendy Lathrope, 28, of Williamstown, N.J.,
hoped for a quick resolution to the talks. She fretted about her
return flight to Philadelphia from Orlando, Fla., next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm worried I won't be able to get back. I have a full-time
job and I'm a graduate student,'' Lathrope, who hopes to see a
friend's new house, said in a phone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Some travel agents have stopped booking flights on US Airways,
and others have been bombarded with calls from travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've had at least 40 calls'' from travelers, including one in
the middle of a trip who was worried about running out of his
medication, said Howard Reynolds, owner of Boulevard Travel
International in Pawtucket, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Gordon, a travel consultant at Robertson Travel Bureau in
North Canton, Ohio, said many customers who planned spring break or
Easter trips are booking flights at as much as double the cost they
were paying on US Airways, just to ensure their vacations won't be
disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the trick is finding them space on other flights with
other airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is one of the busiest times of the year,'' she said. ''In
a lot of cases, it's like looking for a needle in a haystack. There
aren't a lot of seats available.''
</P>
<P>
   The last major labor-related airline disruption came in February
1999, when American Airlines pilots staged an illegal sickout,
forcing the airline to cancel about 6,700 flights over a 10-day
period. The last strike occurred in 1998, when Northwest Airlines
was grounded for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, flight attendants staged demonstrations or passed out
leaflets in Charlotte, N.C., Reagan National Airport, Los Angeles,
Baltimore, Boston, Pittsburgh, and Columbus, Ohio on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In Pittsburgh, about 150 flight attendants marched to a US
Airways ticket office and then to the office of PNC Bank chief
executive Thomas O'Brien, who is on the US Airways board.
</P>
<P>
   The airline has offered a package that would link flight
attendants' pay to the average of the four largest airlines plus 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants, whose contract expired in 1996, say the
airline's offer would actually cut pay and fringe benefits by 5
percent. Flight attendants have had no raise since 1996 and their
pay ranges from $17,145 to $36,918.
</P>
<P>
   Union spokesman Jeff Zack said the decision by some travel
agents to avoid the use of US Airways is likely costing the airline
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a product of their own doing for announcing they will
shut down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways spokesman Richard Weintraub declined to comment on
the union's statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''The uncertainty and randomness of the CHAOS campaign is
disruptive and we will not subject our customers to that kind of
treatment,'' Weintraub said. ''You can be certain that we will make
every effort to accommodate our customers' needs,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from many other major airlines, including American,
TWA and Southwest, said they would accept US Airways tickets, as
did Amtrak, which planned to add extra rail cars to its trains in
the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Turneabe-Connelly, a spokeswoman for Southwest
Airlines, said their ticket sales spiked this week but it's
impossible to tell whether that was caused by the US Airways
situation or because of spring break travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Association of Flight Attendants:
http://www.afausairways.org
</P>
<P>
   US Airways: http://www.usairways.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 0148 </TRAILER>
