<DOCNO> APW20000323.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Via Dolorosa Sparks Confusion  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, West Bank (AP) -- The Palestinian Authority isn't up
on the latest in Roman Catholic liturgy -- a representation of the
Via Dolorosa presented to Pope John Paul II on Wednesday was a
station short of what the church has recently determined is the
route of Christ's crucifixion and resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   Yasser Arafat presented the pope with 14 flat ovals set in
velvet, each marking a station of Christ's last journey through
Jerusalem. As he opened the velvet box, the Palestinian leader
explained to the pope: ''These are the 14 stations of the cross.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Fifteen,'' Pope John Paul II interjected.
</P>
<P>
   ''Your Holiness, right you are,'' said Afif Safiyeh, Arafat's
envoy to the Vatican. ''The 15th station is that of the
resurrection.'' Arafat and the pope laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Christian pilgrims to Jerusalem have retraced the stations for
at least 16 centuries, often bearing a cross. Some stations are on
the same spot: for instance, pilgrims mark the crucifixion,
entombment and resurrection of Christ in the same cramped room of
the Church of the Holy Sepulcher.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican ended centuries of confusion over the stations in
the 18th century by saying there were 14. This century, however,
Roman Catholic liturgists have added the resurrection as a station.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just the first papal pilgrimage to
Palestinian-controlled areas -- it was the first time the pope had a
necklace placed over his neck.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat presented John Paul with a gold Bethlehem 2000 medal --
hanging at the end of a green ribbon -- after a proclamation was
read thanking the pope for his support of the Palestinian
''struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope has received many gifts during his 22-year papacy, but
this is the first time one has been hung on his person.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   John Paul had just uttered ''amen,'' sealing his homily
Wednesday during an outdoor Mass near the grotto believed to be
Christ's birthplace when a piercing cry of ''Allahu Akbar'' rang
out across Manger Square.
</P>
<P>
   It was close to noon, time for the Muslim call to prayer, and
the muezzin at the Omar Mosque on the opposite side of the square
was not about to be amiss in performing his regular duties.
</P>
<P>
   The pontiff and thousands of Christian worshippers waited
patiently for several minutes until the prayer call, broadcast over
a loudspeaker attached to the mosque tower, was completed.
</P>
<P>
   A few in the crowd fidgeted uncomfortably, and a nun shook her
head in apparent disbelief. Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat,
sitting in the front row close to the stage, checked his watch just
before the call of prayer was sounded.
</P>
<P>
   Bethlehem Mayor Hanna Nasser said a compromise had been worked
out ahead of time, with the muezzin agreeing in deference to the
pope to shorten his prayer call to three minutes of ''Allahu
Akbar,'' Arabic for ''God is Great,'' and not reading the customary
Koranic verses.
</P>
<P>
   Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro-Valls said the brief
interruption of the Mass underscored religious coexistence.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was just something that happened in a very mutual and
respectful way,'' Navarro-Valls said, noting that the starting time
of the Mass had been delayed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
