<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grasslands Face Fire Danger  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN MacDONALD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARGO, N.D. (AP) -- Forest Service officials are watching the
skies and hoping for rain, worried that abnormally dry conditions
in North Dakota's national grasslands could increase the risk of
fire, endangering cattle ranchers.
</P>
<P>
   A sea of wind-swept grass and wildflowers, the Little Missouri
National Grasslands in western North Dakota is largest in the
nation. The area covers about 1 million acres, a quarter of all the
publicly owned grasslands administered by the U.S. Forest Service.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have basically had no measurable, significant precipitation
since August and that's not good,'' said Gary Petik, a rangeland
specialist for the agency's McKenzie Ranger District, which
includes half of the Little Missouri grasslands.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're pretty concerned at this point,'' he said. ''We're
setting up to have a very dry summer.''
</P>
<P>
   An obvious concern is a repeat of fires that burned an estimated
70,000 acres of the national grasslands last fall and damaged the
property of about 40 ranch families.
</P>
<P>
   Lesley Thompson, the ranger for the Medora District, said it is
too early to predict the seriousness of the fire threat. But every
day without rain only increases the danger, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We definitely need precipitation,'' Thompson added. ''But
there's still time for that to occur.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the fire danger here is already considered moderate,''
said Scott Fitzwilliams, another Medora District ranger. ''For this
time of year, that is very odd.''
</P>
<P>
   What worries Petik more is what the dry conditions could mean to
the ranchers who use the National Grasslands for grazing.
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service determines the number of cattle a rancher may
graze, based in part on the conditions of the grasslands each year.
If the land appears fragile because of a lack of moisture, overuse
or fire damage, grazing may be restricted.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been cautioning folks throughout the district,'' Petik
said. ''They've all been told that if we don't have significant
moisture, we're going to have to adjust the numbers downward.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   GLASGOW, Mont. (AP) -- Although not happy about the possibility
of summer drought, cattle producers across Montana say the dryness
and mildness of late winter have reduced calf mortality.
</P>
<P>
   ''You couldn't have ordered better weather,'' said Jim McIntyre,
who raises beef cattle in the Glasgow area. ''It's a cowboy's
dream.''
</P>
<P>
   He is optimistic about the spring calf crop and thanks Mother
Nature for the mild temperatures and dry ground that have
comfortably welcomed dozens of his calves into the world this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Montana cattle producers are seeing a drop in calf deaths that
are attributable to cold weather and diseases associated with the
cold. This could be the second year in a row that ranchers will
have larger, healthier calf crops.
</P>
<P>
   Warmer weather brought calving season a bit earlier than usual.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of February, 27 percent of the roughly 1.6 million
calves expected to be born in Montana this year were hobbling
alongside their mothers. The state average for that time of year is
16 percent, according to the government's Agricultural Statistics
Service.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been an excellent winter,'' said Verlin Koenig, Montana
State University extension agent for Valley County.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
