<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Supporters Courted  </HEADLINE>
By GLEN JOHNSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In their quests for the presidency, Al Gore
and George W. Bush are eagerly courting the supporters of John
McCain, although with vastly different pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the vice president, is the circus barker, flailing his
arms and shouting as if through a bullhorn while urging these
so-called ''McCainiacs'' to step inside the Democratic tent.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to say a word to the supporters of Senator John McCain
in the Republican primaries,'' he told nearly 1,000 people Monday
in Springfield, Ill. ''To any who can hear the sound of my voice,
whatever party you're in ... I'd like to ask for your support.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Texas governor, is trying the soft sell, sitting back
and waiting for those voters, mostly independents and some
Democrats, to appreciate the superiority of the product -- himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's going to win his supporters over is when they realize
that Al Gore is no John McCain,'' Bush said after he beat the
Arizona senator for the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   After trouncing McCain on Super Tuesday, Bush said he would be
''reaching out to the people he energized,'' but has had to
backtrack after sounding dismissive of McCain last week in an
interview with The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ''I appreciate the hard campaign that John McCain waged,'' Bush
said after the interview was published. ''Of course, he and I agree
on a lot and it starts with this: The best reform for America is to
end the Clinton-Gore era in Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   As party labels fray, independent-minded voters are increasingly
a prized commodity in elections.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton won among independents in 1996, while in 1992,
Clinton and Bush's father, then-President Bush, each got about a
quarter of the independent vote. Ross Perot got almost half.
</P>
<P>
   The latest polls on the contest between Bush and Gore show
independents roughly splitting between the two, if not leaning
toward Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Though not an independent, McCain created a political stir by
pledging to attack the Washington establishment, particularly over
the way lobbyists influence policy through campaign donations.
</P>
<P>
   He also drew support from people who were enthralled with his
personal story. The son and grandson of Navy admirals, McCain was a
Navy fighter pilot who spent 5{ years in a prison camp after being
shot down during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   The race for the nomination seesawed between Bush and McCain
before the Texas governor won it with a string of victories on
Super Tuesday, March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls showed McCain's voters were more likely to be older
men who were not part of the religious right with moderate feelings
about abortion. A third of his supporters were independents, and
almost half of the men who voted for him were fellow veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Four in 10 of McCain's voters also didn't think Bush knew enough
to be president, and two-thirds had unfavorable views of Bush, the
polls showed.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Rothenberg, a Washington political analyst, said the
feelings are understandable and may explain Bush's laid-back pitch
immediately after his win.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem for Bush is he beat McCain, so immediately that
will leave a bad taste in the McCain people's mouths,'' Rothenberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the appeal to these voters from Gore, who defeated
the reform-minded Bill Bradley, has been as more of a compatriot
than conqueror.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as he secured the Democratic nomination, the vice
president overtly asked for their support. He later pledged to make
McCain's signature issue -- campaign finance reform -- a centerpiece
of his own effort, although the move resurrects questions about his
fund-raising problems that stem from the 1996 Clinton-Gore
re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the March 14 primaries in six southern states,
Gore used a fund-raiser in the predominantly Republican Nashville,
Tenn., suburb of Belle Meade to make a direct -- if self-conscious --
pitch to supporters of both McCain and Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm naturally going to want to provide a home for those who
were drawn to their candidacies in part because of that issue,''
Gore said at the $500-per-person reception. ''That's not the only
reason I'm saying (I support campaign finance reform). I've said it
beforehand.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Gore appeared with Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, a
third-party politician who supports campaign finance changes, and
openly appealed for support from political independents.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also visited places like Wayne State University in Detroit,
telling the Michigan independents who had supported McCain: ''I'm
anxious to talk to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush says Gore's new campaign finance push shows the vice
president ''will say anything to get elected.'' He says the
approach is the opposite of the ''straight talk'' that McCain
practiced throughout his candidacy, and that voters will flock to
him as they realize that.
</P>
<P>
   ''People want to focus on areas where we disagree,'' he said
last week of McCain. ''I'm going to focus on areas where we agree,
and there's a lot of agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Gallup Poll: http://www.gallup.com
</P>
<P>
   Voter.com-Battleground 2000 Poll: http://www.voter.com
</P>
<P>
   Bush site: http://www.georgebush.com
</P>
<P>
   Gore site: http://www.algore2000.com
</P>
