<DOCNO> APW20000323.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Fight for Reform Party Control  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE KELLMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYNCHBURG, Va. (AP) -- One of two men laying claim to the Reform
Party chairmanship and its millions of taxpayer dollars contends in
federal court that the wrong guy was improperly elected at a party
meeting last month in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ''The events at Nashville were fraught with people who shouldn't
have been voting,'' Tracey Lenox, the attorney for Jack Gargan,
said Wednesday in a preview of the testimony he was expected to
give when the trial resumed today. ''The outcome was preordained.''
</P>
<P>
   Gargan, an ally of Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, follows rival
chairman Pat Choate to the stand. Choate, the 1996 running mate of
party founder Ross Perot, was elected in Nashville to replace
Gargan. Gargan argues that the meeting was illegally convened and
that he is still chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Both men have run parallel chairmanships and dueling
''official'' party Web sites and are planning rival nominating
conventions with $2.5 million in federal funding -- some of which is
missing.
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry -- and the raucous nature of the Nashville meeting --
has cost the third party significant credibility this election
year, Choate testified Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It adversely affects our capacity to make a meaningful run for
the presidency this fall,'' he told U.S. District Judge Norman K.
Moon, who is expected to pick the real chairman at the close of the
scheduled three-day trial.
</P>
<P>
   Choate specifically pointed to a March 14 electronic letter from
a Robert Tice urging recipients to file criminal charges against
leaders of Perot's faction ''for attempting to violate our civil
rights,'' as well as $100 million in civil suits against the same
people. A copy of the e-mail was provided to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really a form of political terrorism,'' Choate said.
</P>
<P>
   Lenox objected to the document being admitted into evidence on
grounds that there was no evidence that the author acted at
Gargan's direction.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know anything about it,'' Gargan said during a court
break. ''That's called guilt by association.''
</P>
<P>
   Gargan also said he has instructed the people who posted an
''official'' Reform Party Web site loyal to him to take it down,
but he acknowledged plans to replace it with his own ''official''
party site.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing is only one fight facing the Reform Party, and may
not be its last in federal court. Joining Pat Buchanan, who is
seeking the Reform presidential nomination, the party is
challenging the Commission on Presidential Debates on the grounds
that its rules would unduly bar the party from those events in the
fall. If the Federal Election Commission does not rule in the
party's favor, Choate and Buchanan intend to pursue the matter in
federal court.
</P>
<P>
   In federal court this week, Choate and others allied with Perot
sought a court order to bar Gargan and his supporters from acting
as leaders and planning the convention in Ventura's state.
</P>
<P>
   Each man blames the other for the turmoil that has gripped the
party well into the election year.
</P>
<P>
   On the stand, Choate complained that Gargan's allies, in a flood
of e-mail and press releases, had caused confusion and driven away
party members ''in droves.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Choate's, Gargan's supporters painted the trial's outcome
in broad historic terms.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we do not prevail here, democracy and our future will be in
great jeopardy,'' said Virginia Reform Party Chairman Sue Harris de
Bauche, a Gargan ally who was asked to leave the Nashville meeting
after shoving a Perot supporter. She is married to Ronn Young, the
party treasurer who also was ousted in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   But Dale Cooter, Choate's lawyer, put a professional
parliamentarian on the stand who had been hired by Perot's allies
to rule over the procedures of that meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''Generally, it was handled properly,'' Ben Carpenter, of
Memphis, Tenn., told the court. He said he had not received money
or anything else that would have slanted his rulings.
</P>
<P>
   About $2 million of the $2.5 million in federal funds for the
party convention is currently in the court's custody. Gargan said
he doesn't know where the rest of the money is, but assumes it was
spent on deposits for contracts on the Minnesota convention.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.reformparty.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.rpusa.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
