<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton says mayor's reaction wouldn't wash in Senate  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's reaction to
criticism of the Police Department after the latest shooting of an
unarmed black man reveals a characteristic that wouldn't serve him
well in the Senate, Hillary Rodham Clinton said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to work with people you don't necessarily agree with,
who may say terrible things about you, who may engage in rhetoric
and strategies that you disapprove of,'' said Clinton, Giuliani's
Democratic opponent in the Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''But you have to get up every day and work with those people
and get things done for the people who elect you and for the state
you represent.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady said Wednesday that the mayor's actions after
last week's police killing of Patrick Dorismond -- releasing the
victim's sealed juvenile record and his girlfriend's complaint that
he'd hit her -- ''have aggravated tensions in the city and have
helped drive a wedge between the police and the communities they
serve.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Giuliani had ''basically written off'' New York City's
black residents when he said he felt no responsibility to reach out
to the community after the killing.
</P>
<P>
   ''What does that say about how people would be represented by
him?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's campaign spokesman, Bruce Teitelbaum, said, ''It
sounds like Mrs. Clinton is still reading off the same script
prepared by (black activist) Al Sharpton.''
</P>
<P>
   Statewide polls on the Senate race have routinely shown the
Republican mayor getting less than 10 percent of the black vote,
while Clinton, the likely Democratic nominee, gets more than 80
percent.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the mayor was asked if he felt any responsibility to
talk or meet with black people after the third fatal shooting of an
unarmed black man in 13 months.
</P>
<P>
   ''No, I don't think so,'' he said. ''I think this is a situation
that clearly had nothing to do with race. The three police officers
were Hispanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the mayor has an ''enormous trust chasm'' and ''has
presented a false choice to New Yorkers.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not necessary to choose between effective policing and
respectful policing,'' she said. ''It is not necessary to give up
trust and good relations between the police and the communities
they serve in the pursuit of lowering the crime rate.''
</P>
<P>
   NAACP President Kweisi Mfume echoed the tone of Clinton's
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rather than trying to demonize Patrick Dorismond, an unarmed
Haitian American killed during a police encounter, Giuliani should
be reviewing police training standards to see what steps the
department can take to avoid the unnecessary use of lethal force,''
Mfume said Wednesday in a statement from the National Association
for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke Wednesday to reporters in White Plains after
talking about schools with a crowd of about 250 educators, parents
and students at the YWCA. She said she is a supporter of charter
schools, but that New York's law was ''guaranteed to cause
problems'' because it recognized two different chartering
authorities -- the Board of Regents and the State University -- and
because it does not properly enforce the separation of church and
state.
</P>
</TEXT>
