<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nazi Labor Talks To Wind Up  </HEADLINE>
By BURT HERMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- As time runs short for the aging victims of
Nazi-era forced and slave labor, negotiators say they are nearing
agreement on how to divide up a $5 billion compensation fund after
more than a year of talks.
</P>
<P>
   The latest two-day round of negotiations was due to wind up
today, after a group session led by the U.S. and German envoys to
the meetings that include class-action lawyers, Jewish groups and
the governments of eastern European countries and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The talks have stalled over the question of how to divide the
money between the various groups who would benefit, along with how
much should be set aside for a fund for academic projects on the
Nazi labor policies that were used to help fuel Hitler's war
machine.
</P>
<P>
   Eastern European countries have also criticized the amount being
set aside for claims for Nazi-confiscated bank accounts and
insurance policies, which are also to be covered under the fund
that seeks to give German firms legal security from class-action
lawsuits in the United States. They say that takes away money for
labor victims.
</P>
<P>
   The head German envoy to the talks, Otto Lambsdorff, said
Wednesday he felt the negotiations were near a final breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   But the spokesman for German industry was cautiously optimistic
about predicting results.
</P>
<P>
   ''As is always the situation when people are very close, they
are looking for smaller differences and sometimes the smaller
differences become larger and larger,'' Wolfgang Gibowski said
Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Germany has proposed $4 billion of the fund go to labor victims,
with $500 million for property claims. The rest of the money will
cover the foundation and administrative and legal costs.
</P>
<P>
   Slave laborers -- those held in concentration camps or ghettos
and expected to be worked to death -- are to receive $7,500 each.
Forced laborers in industry, who lived under less severe
conditions, are to receive $2,500, while those put to work on farms
are to get $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gibowski said the amounts each victim would receive could be
decreased if too many people apply for the fund. The estimate of
surviving victims has ranged widely, up to 2.3 million people,
mostly non-Jews from Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's Cabinet approved a
bill to set up the fund, which is to be split by the government and
German industry. The government hopes the bill will be passed by
parliament before its summer break.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
