<HEADLINE> Taiwan's President To Resign  </HEADLINE>
By MARCOS CALO MEDINA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwan's president will resign as the
leader of the ruling Nationalists, officials said today, granting
the demands of party members who blamed him for last weekend's
humiliating election defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of Lee Teng-hui comes less than a week after his
chosen presidential candidate, Vice President Lien Chan, finished a
distant third in Saturday's election.
</P>
<P>
   Lien will take over as acting chairman of the Nationalists on
Friday when party leaders gather for an emergency meeting, said
Ting Yuean-chao, a spokesman for the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Since the election, protesters have gathered outside the party's
headquarters in downtown Taipei, demanding that Lee take the blame
for the defeat and resign immediately. On Sunday, Lee said he would
step down in September, but that was not soon enough for his
critics.
</P>
<P>
   ''He had wanted to resign after the election setback, but he
wanted to initiate it himself, not under pressure,'' said Wang
Tan-ping, a top official in the party's central policy committee.
''He's a man who has great concerns about his historical legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Also today, Lien apologized to supporters during his first
formal public speech since his election loss, which ended the
Nationalist's 50-year grip on Taiwan's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to himself and his running mate, Premier Vincent Siew,
the vice president said, ''The most important factor in the loss
was that two guys weren't diligent enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Lien urged party members to ''bravely stand up'' and reunify the
party.
</P>
<P>
   The loss to Chen Shui-bian of the Democratic Progressive Party
has sparked an extensive shake-up in the party's high ranks. Today,
the head of the Nationalists' vast business empire, Liu Tai-ying,
said that he would step down when a successor was picked.
</P>
<P>
   Also resigning are Secretary-General Huang Kun-hui and Deputy
Secretary-General Huang Cheng-hsiung, Ting said.
</P>
<P>
   The stiff, professorial Lien struggled to convince voters that
he could reform the Nationalist Party, long accused of deep-rooted
corruption. Late in the campaign, Lien said if elected, he would
try to put the party's business assets into a trust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
