<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Youth Flocks to Putin  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW KRAMER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- In Russia's last presidential election, an ailing
Boris Yeltsin waved his arms in the air and tried to dance at a
rock concert, pleading with young people to back him. But Vladimir
Putin is getting the support of many of those voters without
lifting a finger.
</P>
<P>
   Jaded by years of botched reforms and massive corruption, young
Russians are flocking to Putin because they are worried about being
able to find employment and their financial security.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to finish university and be sure of finding a normal
job,'' said 18-year-old Alexei Papygin.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm voting for Putin. All the others don't have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from being discouraged by the ex-KGB agent's conservative
image, polls show support for Putin among voters under the age of
30 is 60 percent, slightly higher than in the population as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
   Strong backing from younger voters will help ensure Putin's
victory in Sunday's presidential vote, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's image as a tough, competent leader appeals to many
younger voters, who are not worried about warnings that he may roll
back democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas six years ago, about 20 percent of young people said
they supported a ''strong hand'' in government, between 40 percent
and 50 percent now say they want the strong government Putin is
promising, according to the Youth Institute, which conducts monthly
surveys of young people's opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Young people are waffling. They want to live in a free country
with opportunities for a career, but they want a strong hand and
discipline in the country,'' said Vladimir Radionov, director of
the institute.
</P>
<P>
   ''The contradiction will be difficult to reconcile in the
future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most young Russians' disillusionment starts with their wallets
and a widening gap between rich and poor in their own generation.
Better-off young people are likely to be in college and more likely
to live in cities, free to spend evenings in the bars and
nightclubs that flourished after the collapse of communism in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The other extreme can be seen on the streets of the seedy
districts in Moscow and scores of other Russian cities. Young men
in leather jackets loiter around shell-game tables or kiosks
selling cut-rate vodka. Young prostitutes stand on the sidewalks
and smoke, waiting for clients who arrive in flashy Mercedes or BMW
cars.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before, sports clubs and entertainment were for everybody. Now
they're a thing for the rich, and the middle-class kids spend their
time on the streets, and the streets are covered with prostitutes
and narcotics,'' said Oleg Zolotov, a 29-year-old part-time worker,
while drinking a beer on a park bench at lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
   Like many young Russians, Zolotov was downbeat about his career
prospects. The average monthly wage in Russia was about $60 in
1999, and opportunities for travel and education are shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   Even among elite university students, many say the country is
drifting and needs a strong leader. At Moscow State University,
Russia's most prestigious, students say they hope a Putin victory
will mean a new beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Others fear Putin has put the country on the slope to
authoritarian rule, pointing to his tough campaign against Islamic
separatists in Chechnya. At least 1,600 young Russian soldiers have
been killed in the war, a chilling statistic in a country where
most men face compulsory military service.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not clear what to expect from him,'' said Tanya Ivanova,
an 18-year-old geography major who plans to vote for someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Others express disillusionment, saying nothing will change, no
matter who wins.
</P>
<P>
   ''My vote won't count for anything. They already decided who
will be president,'' said Kirill Torzhevsky, 19, a math major.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only choice is to boycott the vote,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
