<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 02:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> School Plan in Denver Controversial  </HEADLINE>
By JON SARCHE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- A governor-supported plan to link school
performance to monetary rewards has failed to make the grade with
hundreds of Colorado parents and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   A school principal has resigned to protest the legislative
measure, which would establish a formula for issuing letter grades
to schools depending on how students score on a statewide
standardized test.
</P>
<P>
   Schools that receive As and those showing the greatest
improvement would receive financial bonuses. Those receiving Fs
eventually could be put under new management.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes amid efforts by lawmakers and educators
throughout the country to improve student achievement.
</P>
<P>
   What is in question is whether accountability systems for
schools actually lead to improvement, said Tom Jandris, state
services director for the Denver-based Education Commission of the
States.
</P>
<P>
   ''We still lack a wide body of systemic research that
demonstrates whether grading schools accelerates student
achievement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Denver, supporters of the bill say grades would expose and
correct problems, while critics contend they would unfairly target
low-income and inner-city schools already troubled by low parent
involvement and high levels of student turnover.
</P>
<P>
   Low-scoring schools would be permanently stigmatized,
eliminating any chance at improvement, and could even affect
neighborhood property values, the critics say.
</P>
<P>
   ''I cannot stand behind this idea of saying to these 600
children, 'You are F material,''' said Mitchell Elementary School
Principal Lynn Spampinato, who tendered her resignation in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Under the grading system, Mitchell, in a predominantly black
inner-city area, would receive an F despite dedicated teachers,
relatively high parent involvement and innovative programs,
Spampinato said.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Coleman, who has two children at Mitchell, said: ''I'm
looking at my kids' report cards and looking at the other kids, and
to say that that school is an F is a misconception.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathy McKittrick, a teacher at Abraham Lincoln High School,
joined about 300 people at a recent protest outside the Capitol.
She argues that the bill is ''based on the false premise that all
kids can be measured by the same yardstick.''
</P>
<P>
   Education Commissioner Bill Moloney said the purpose of the
report card system -- advancing through the Legislature with Gov.
Bill Owens' blessing -- is to draw attention to problems.
</P>
<P>
   Of states with school evaluation systems, 21 issue specific
ratings on schools, while only Florida and California use letter
grades, said Shelby Samuelsen, education policy analyst for the
National Conference of State Legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   Such laws are so new that there is little data available to
determine whether they are working, Samuelsen said, but added that
Texas and North Carolina, whose systems have been in place for a
while, have seen gains in student test scores.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's proposal is modeled closely on the 6-year-old Texas
system, which has resulted in significant gains in student
achievement, said Texas Education Agency spokeswoman Debbie
Ratcliffe.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe a lot of that has to do with the accountability
system because it shines a spotlight not only on successes, it
shines a spotlight on weaknesses,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The Colorado Department of Education,
www.state.co.us/edu--dir/edumenu.html
</P>
<P>
   The Education Commission of the States, www.ecs.org
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Education Agency, www.tea.state.tx.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 0237 </TRAILER>
