<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 02:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Fence Dispute Magnified  </HEADLINE>
By BURT HERMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Complaining to a neighbor about a bush growing
through her fence got Regina Zindler nowhere. So she took him to TV
court.
</P>
<P>
   The simple tale of yet another neighborly dispute in Germany
might have ended there, except for the 50-something housewife's
distinctive Saxon drawl. The way she pronounced the word for
chain-link fence, ''Maschendrahtzaun,'' captured the imagination of
a comedian-singer whose country music parody has turned the
backyard dispute into one of the most talked about conflicts in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old chain-link fence entered German lore after
Zindler sought television justice in October for a decade-old
complaint about the way neighbor Gerd Trommer's snowberry bush was
pushing through her Maschendrahtzaun (pronounced
MUSH-in-drawt-tsaun). She lost.
</P>
<P>
   But as fate would have it, comedian Stefan Raab was watching.
Zindler's drawn out way of saying Maschendrahtzaun kept playing
through his head -- and he used her sampled voice to immortalize the
utterance in a country tune he composed in English:
</P>
<P>
   ''And if I ever be king/and I get a crown/then it would surely
be made of/Maschendrahtzaun,'' goes one verse; others include
obscenities relating to the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Performed on Raab's show making fun of German TV clips, the song
went to No. 1 on the German charts and stayed there for seven
weeks. Frau Zindler and her fence were catapulted into media
stardom.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands descended upon Zindler's small town of Auerbach,
population 25,000, to hold impromptu fence parties at the edge of
the property and clamor for autographs.
</P>
<P>
   The trespassing snowberry bush wasn't nearly as bothersome by
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to be a normal person like before,'' Zindler has said.
''It was terrible that people would stand for hours on the
sidewalk.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was too late to retreat to anonymity. Local tourism
authorities and businesses were in the act.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's more to experience than the quarrel at the fence,''
offers a tourism brochure for Vogtland, a region near the Czech
border where Auerbach is located. The city also plans an exhibit on
the ''Fence Queen,'' as Zindler has since been dubbed.
</P>
<P>
   There are Maschendrahtzaun souvenirs, including T-shirts,
pottery with fence designs, chocolate and marzipan fence pastries --
even replicas of a pink jogging suit Zindler had been seen wearing,
which have sold out at $25 each.
</P>
<P>
   Someone even replaced the sign at the Auerbach city limits with
one reading ''Grosse Maschen-Draht-Zaun Stadt,'' or ''Big
Chain-Link Fence City.'' The sign is now enshrined in the city's
museum.
</P>
<P>
   While the catchy tune is credited with bringing fame to Auerbach
and a certain notoriety to Frau Zindler, the tale's true appeal is
that the conflict typifies the way Germans often relate to each
other.
</P>
<P>
   The fence dispute is emblematic of the daily squabbles in
densely populated Germany, where privacy and order are so highly
valued that neighbors regularly complain about barbecue smoke
blowing into their windows and neighbors flushing their toilets at
night or making home repairs on a Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a quarrel between neighbors, which happens every day
in Germany ... but never in Germany has there been such a
well-known argument between neighbors,'' said Juergen Preuss, who
worked for the tourism office on the brochure.
</P>
<P>
   The frenzy grew so great that Raab called for the hundreds of
fans who were descending on Auerbach to leave Zindler alone. His
request came after a piece of the beloved barrier was stolen,
although a local construction store donated a replacement. Later,
someone also made off with a piece of the famed foliage.
</P>
<P>
   ''Have fun and celebrate your Maschendraht-parties at home with
friends. And leave the fence there where it belongs,'' Raab said in
January, announcing he would skip a ceremony marking the single's
rise to platinum sales to help quiet the hype.
</P>
<P>
   A parody of the parody has even made it to neighboring Austria,
where the opposition used it to play off the trademark bow tie of
the new chancellor, Wolfgang Schuessel, whose government has been
under pressure from its European partners since entering a
coalition with the far-right party of Joerg Haider. In the Austrian
dialect, the word ''Mascherl'' means bow tie, similar to
''Maschen'' in the word for fence.
</P>
<P>
   ''And the EU takes their trust away/We'll send them our veto
over the Mascherl-Draht-Zaun'' -- or bow tie fence -- go the lyrics
that have been widely circulated by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, fan pressure finally got to the snowberry bush's
owner, who uprooted the bush and moved it away from Zindler's
beloved Maschendrahtzaun.
</P>
<P>
   Zindler, in return for the gesture of reconciliation, offered
her own tribute: a musical retort recorded last month under the
stage name ''Regina Z.''
</P>
<P>
   Its name? ''Peace at the Fence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 0241 </TRAILER>
