<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nuclear Waste Bill Clears House  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Legislation that would clear the way for
thousands of tons of highly radioactive nuclear waste to be shipped
to the Nevada desert has passed Congress, but likely will not
become law.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has promised a veto and supporters in neither
the Senate nor the House appear to have enough votes to override a
veto. The measure passed the House on Wednesday by a 253-167 vote,
after clearing the Senate last month 64-34.
</P>
<P>
   It takes at least two-thirds of those voting to override a
presidential veto.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fate of Nevada's future is now in the president's hands,''
said Rep. Jim Gibbons, R-Nev.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would require that shipments of used nuclear
fuel, building up at reactors in 31 states, begin to be shipped to
Nevada in 2007, once the Nuclear Regulatory Commission approves a
license for a permanent waste site in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The NRC is expected to decide as early as 2006 on whether the
Yucca Mountain underground nuclear waste repository 90 miles
northwest of Las Vegas should be licensed. Now under scientific
review, the site is proposed for opening in 2010. State officials
have pledged to fight it.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to win broader support, the bill's sponsors
deleted provisions that would require creation of a temporary waste
storage site and require that the federal government immediately
take title of the waste now held by electric utilities.
</P>
<P>
   But Nevadans continue to oppose any legislation that would bring
the nation's highly radioactive wastes, which remains dangerous for
10,000 years, to the state.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has opposed the legislation partly because the
bill raises questions about the authority of the Environmental
Protection Agency to independently determine radiation exposure
standards for a future Yucca Mountain underground repository.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was just an exercise in futility,'' Rep. Shelley Berkley,
D-Nev., said in an interview after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the legislation argued that the government has a
legal obligation to take more than 40,000 tons of highly
radioactive used reactor fuel now kept at commercial reactors in 31
states.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government broke its promise to begin storing nuclear
waste. The (Clinton) administration still refused to deal in good
faith ... to fix the problem,'' said Rep. Fred Upton, R-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   While Nevada's lawmakers sought to keep waste out of their
state, other opponents of the bill said it does not go far enough
to ensure a central storage facility is built. Still other House
members said they were concerned about thousands of waste
shipments, many by truck, crisscrossing the country.
</P>
<P>
   This bill ''does more harm than good, it's a sham. It's nothing
more than bait and switch,'' complained Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   He said the House should take up its own legislation, which
would create a temporary storage facility and require the Energy
Department to take title of the waste.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has struggled for six years over how to deal with the
buildup of used reactor fuel now mostly held in water pools at 71
reactor sites around the country. Some utilities complain they are
running out of storage room while electricity users have
contributed $13 billion into a federal waste fund.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation, the EPA would have to consult with the
NRC and the National Academy of Sciences if it wanted to issue the
standards before June 1, 2001. The NRC has suggested less stringent
standards than the EPA is considering for the Yucca Mountain site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
