<BODY>
<HEADLINE> INS Slammed For Releasing Criminals  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE MITTELSTADT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A key House lawmaker is harshly critical of
the immigration service for releasing 35,000 immigrants with
criminal records into U.S. communities over the past five years,
saying one-third of them went on to commit new crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just find this another absolutely catastrophic failure of
this agency,'' Rep. Harold Rogers, R-Ky., said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, who chairs the House appropriations subcommittee that
funds immigration operations, made clear his displeasure during a
sharp round of questions lobbed at Immigration and Naturalization
Service Commissioner Doris Meissner during a hearing by his panel
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 35,318 criminal aliens freed by INS during the five-year
period ending last May, 11,605 went on to commit new crimes, Rogers
said, citing newly compiled Justice Department figures.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we're dealing with here is mayhem on the American people,
and that cannot be tolerated,'' Rogers fumed, saying 98 homicides,
142 sexual assaults, 347 robberies and 1,214 assaults were among
the total.
</P>
<P>
   Meissner defended her agency's performance, although she
acknowledged that the numbers are ''of great concern to us.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The custody of criminal aliens is a top priority of this
agency and the removal of these aliens is occurring at a very rapid
rate,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the releases weren't at INS' discretion, Meissner said,
ordered either because the incarcerated immigrants had won their
deportation cases or because bond was allowed by judges.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, she said, INS exercised its discretion to
release criminal aliens viewed as posing no flight risk or danger
to the community. Included in that category are a class of
essentially stateless immigrants whose home countries -- Cuba,
Vietnam and Laos among them -- refuse to accept their return and who
otherwise would remain indefinitely incarcerated, long after
completing their sentences.
</P>
<P>
   And, included in the total, are an as-yet uncalculated number of
criminal aliens who were deported but slipped back into the United
States, INS officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Recidivism ''occurs at an alarmingly high rate for U.S. citizen
criminals just as it does for criminal aliens,'' Meissner said.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal aliens' recidivist rate of 37 percent pales in
comparison to the 66 percent rate posted by the U.S. criminal
population, INS officials said, though they acknowledge the
five-year snapshot might not provide a complete picture.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over criminal alien releases was touched off
after the INS' parent, the Justice Department, complied with a
demand for information from the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Angered by the INS' release of a Mexican drifter suspected in
nine killings, the Judiciary Committee's chairman issued subpoenas
last August for information on recidivist criminal aliens.
</P>
<P>
   INS has been under fire for allowing Angel Maturino Resendez,
the suspected ''railroad killer,'' to slip repeatedly through its
fingers. Also known as Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, he is charged in
connection with murders in Texas, Illinois and Kentucky. His trial
in one of the Texas slayings begins next week.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's inspector general, in a report earlier
this week, blamed Resendiz' release on errors by poorly trained
immigration agents and design flaws in their computerized lookout
system.
</P>
<P>
   Resendiz allegedly murdered four more people in this country
after the Border Patrol released him back to Mexico last June. When
released, he was wanted by the FBI, Texas Rangers and Houston
police for questioning about murders near U.S. rail lines.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: House Appropriations Committee Web site:
http://www.house.gov/appropriations
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
