<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 02:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Envoy Meets Taiwan's New Leader  </HEADLINE>
By ANNIE HUANG, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- A former U.S. congressman wrapped up a
brief meeting today with Taiwan's newly elected president aimed at
determining whether his policies toward China could bring the two
countries closer to war.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides declined to speak to reporters after their meeting,
holding their comments until unofficial U.S. envoy Lee Hamilton's
departure on Friday. Hamilton is a former Indiana congressman with
expertise in Asian affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Washington and Beijing have been closely watching Chen Shui-bian
since he won Saturday's three-way race with 39 percent of the vote.
Both are looking for signs he might take Taiwan dangerously close
to war with China.
</P>
<P>
   During the presidential campaign, Chinese leaders made it clear
they reviled Chen because of his past support for Taiwan
independence. In newspaper editorials, policy papers and speeches,
Beijing tried to scare voters away from him.
</P>
<P>
   During the presidential campaign and since his election victory,
Chen has worked hard to assure Beijing and Washington that he will
try to ease tensions with China.
</P>
<P>
   Before he was elected, Chen began distancing himself from his
party's support for allowing Taiwanese to vote on whether the
island should declare independence. He said he would only call such
a referendum if China attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan and China split amid civil war in 1949, and Beijing has
repeatedly threatened to use its massive military against the
island if it tries to split away for good.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton is a presidential emissary to Taiwan in everything but
name. He was traveling as a private citizen because Beijing would
fiercely protest an official U.S. visit. China insists Taiwan is a
Chinese province that should not have diplomatic ties with other
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Visits to Taiwan by unofficial U.S. envoys are usually low key,
and it was not unusual for Hamilton to decline to speak to
reporters or discuss his meeting with Chen. Hamilton also planned
to meet retiring President Lee Teng-hui, who officials said would
step down Friday as his party's leader because of the election
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving Wednesday night, Hamilton said in a brief
statement that he was looking forward to learning ''more about the
policies (Chen) seeks to carry out when he assumes office and
pleased to have the opportunity to exchange views with leaders in
Taiwan.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen was also mum about today's meeting. Later in the day, he
met with Defense Minister Tang Fei and praised the military for
remaining neutral in the run-up to the election.
</P>
<P>
   ''National security will be my top priority,'' Chen told Tang.
''National interests will take precedence over any party
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   When reporters pressed him for comment about his meeting with
Hamilton, Chen would only talk about how Taiwan's stock market
soared 464 points today.
</P>
<P>
   Share prices had nose-dived Monday as jittery investors dumped
stocks on worries about war and Taiwan's uncertain political
future. But the fears seem to be fading and the market has closed
up the past three days.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Chen has expressed a wish to meet Chinese leaders and
hold discussions about topics of their choice. He has invited
Chinese leaders to visit Taiwan, and Chinese President Jiang Zemin
said he would like to visit the island.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that both sides are stuck on disagreements that
have blocked talks with Taiwan's current government. Beijing
insists that before negotiations begin, Taipei must agree that the
island is an inseparable part of ''one China.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen and Taiwan's current president have refused to accept that
condition. They think China's notion of ''one China'' means that
the ruling government of that nation would be in Beijing. That
would make Taipei a subordinate, unequal power that would have less
clout at the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   Chen has urged Beijing not to set conditions for talks -- a
request China has refused.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the other major candidates, Chen, a former Taipei
mayor and defense attorney, had the least amount of experience in
foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The other two main candidates -- independent James Soong and Vice
President Lien Chan -- have graduate degrees from U.S. universities
and can speak English. Chen, 49, never studied abroad and his
English speaking skills are minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, who retired from Congress in 1998, is the director of
the U.S.-based Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars. He
was once the ranking Democrat on the House International Relations
Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
