<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Braces for More Flooding  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE COHEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) -- Towns in southern Mozambique face
being swamped for the second time in less than a month by the
surging Limpopo River, relief workers said. Residents, many of whom
had just returned home, have fled to higher ground.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots took off early today from the airport in the capital,
Maputo, to conduct an aerial surveillance of the river but did not
immediately report back their findings, said Abby Spring, a
spokeswoman for the U.N. World Food Program.
</P>
<P>
   ''Weather remains the No. 1 concern for us,'' Spring said.
''Each day, we're monitoring to prevent further loss of life.
</P>
<P>
   The flooding was expected to hit some areas as soon as early
today following recent heavy rains in neighboring Zimbabwe and
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are hardly any people left in Chokwe,'' said Ian Macleod
of the U.N. Children's Fund. The town was first submerged by
floodwaters almost a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   During last month's floods, the worst on record in this
impoverished southeast African nation, thousands of people were
forced to seek refuge in trees and on rooftops until they were
rescued by helicopters. The confirmed death toll of 492 is expected
to rise.
</P>
<P>
   The government had urged people to stay away from low-lying
areas until the rainy season ends late this month, but an estimated
10,000 Chokwe residents returned anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Now almost all of them have left again after government warnings
that began Monday. Most have moved to Chaqualane village further
south, on higher ground.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Leonardo Simao said the wave of water was
expected to reach Xai-Xai, the capital of Gaza province, within a
few days and cause renewed flooding there, 80 miles southeast of
Chokwe on the coast. There were virtually no people still living in
low lying areas of Xai-Xai, Macleod said.
</P>
<P>
   Macleod said the rate at which water was being released into the
Limpopo from the Massingir dam on Mozambique's western border had
more than quadrupled between Sunday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Air Force spokesman Lt. Col. Tom Dolney said two
helicopters were on standby at Maputo airport for rescue missions.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also feared renewed flooding in Mozambique's
devastated central region, where the levels of the Buzi, Save and
Pungue rivers were rising.
</P>
<P>
   ''All road access has been cut off. At this point, they are not
saying it's a life-threatening situation, but it will require
careful monitoring,'' said Aya Shneerson of the U.N. World Food
Program, who flew over the area Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While floodwaters had receded in many areas, the ground remained
saturated and any fresh influx of water posed a serious threat, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mozambique asked international donors for another
$100 million in emergency aid. The additional money was needed to
ensure ongoing emergency aid to 650,000 flood victims until the end
of August, Simao said.
</P>
<P>
   The estimate of the number of people still displaced by the
floods has increased from 360,000 to 450,000 out of a total
population of 19 million.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 24, the government asked for $65 million in aid to meet
the immediate needs of 300,000 people, but this did not take into
account damage caused by subsequent flooding caused by Cyclone
Eline.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations said it had received more than $118 million
in pledges from 44 different donor countries and organizations,
including money spent on direct relief operations. The government
said thus far it had received at least $58.7 million, including
$8.2 million for food assistance and $36 million for infrastructure
repairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 0252 </TRAILER>
