<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Businesses Urge Seoul on Autos  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The American Chamber of Commerce,
concerned about foreign carmakers' small market share in South
Korea, urged the government Thursday to further lower tariffs on
autos.
</P>
<P>
   ''The current situation is politically unsustainable,'' said
Paul M. McGonagle, president of the American Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1998 agreement, South Korea reduced the tariff on
vehicles from 80 percent to 8 percent. But the current levy is
still three times the U.S. rate.
</P>
<P>
   About 910,000 passenger cars were sold in South Korea last year.
Of them, only 2,400 cars, or 0.26 percent, were foreign.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean automakers sold 410,000 passenger cars in the
United States during the same period, grabbing almost 2 percent of
the market.
</P>
<P>
   McGonagle said another reason behind the sluggish sales of
foreign cars was the ''negative public perception'' attached to
owning a foreign vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   After South Korea was forced to accept a $58 billion bailout
from the International Monetary Fund, many people felt spending
money on imported goods was unpatriotic. Civic groups staged a
''Buy Korean'' campaign amid the economic crisis in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Despite South Korea's significant economic recovery, McGonagle
said, resistance to owning a foreign car remains an obstacle to a
bigger market share.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber said it hopes South Korea's government takes
measures to improve access to the market, including supporting a
foreign auto show in May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 0254 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000323.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Britain officer acquitted of larceny  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A New Britain police officer has been
acquitted of attempted robbery and larceny, six years after he was
charged in a corruption case that focused on the Hartford police.
</P>
<P>
   A six-member jury found Kevin Cloukey, 38 innocent in Superior
Court on Wednesday. He was accused of assisting a drug dealer
shakedown clients and attempting to rob another dealer of money in
May 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Cloukey was one of eight police officers, including a former
state trooper, arrested during an 18-month probe conducted by
Hartford Superior Court Judge Arthur Spada.
</P>
<P>
   One Hartford officer charged in the investigation was acquitted
of criminal charges. Another Hartford officer, accused of larceny,
was granted a special form of probation that will allow him to
clear his record if he completes his probation successfully.
</P>
<P>
   All told, 26 suspects, not all of whom were arrested, were
developed during a probe that called 148 witnesses. Cloukey was the
second officer acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   Cloukey, a seven-year veteran of the force at the time, and
fellow New Britain Officer Daniel Phillips, then 38, were arrested
Oct. 25, 1994, and stripped of their guns and badges. They
initially continued to be paid, but later were suspended from the
payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, a detective with the gang task force, was charged with
perjury and using a false search warrant to enter a cafe dancer's
apartment to get a tape recording of him boasting of taking drugs
and money during a raid, police said. His case is awaiting trial.
Phillips was a 14-year veteran of the department when he was
arrested in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The jury in Cloukey's case deliberated for over two days
following more than two weeks of testimony. Judge John F. Mulcahy
Jr. presided over the trial.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Springer attacked two of the state's crucial
witnesses, brothers Johnnie and Luis Baez, both convicted drug
dealers, who accused Cloukey of being involved in assisting a drug
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Springer argued it was inconceivable that Cloukey could have
been involved since he was supplying information to police
narcotics investigators who at the time were constantly watching
Cancel's drug dealings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
