<HEADLINE> House Panel Approves Education Bill  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans are steering an education
savings account bill toward passage despite the threat of a
presidential veto and the opposition of most Democrats who say
there are fairer ways to spend education dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The tax-writing Ways and Means Committee on Wednesday approved
by 21-16 a five-point bill to give tax relief to parents and
encourage spending both for public and private schools. The vote
was along party lines except for Republican Rep. Nancy Johnson of
Connecticut, who voted against the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which could reach the House floor next week, parallels
a measure passed by the Senate earlier this month by 61-37, six
votes short of what would be needed to override a promised veto by
President Clinton. The president has vetoed two bills that
contained similar education savings account legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would allow parents to place as much as $2,000 per
year, per child, in education IRAs. Tax-free interest from those
contributions could be used for transportation, tutors, books and
any other expenses for K-12 public, private or parochial schools.
</P>
<P>
   It would expand an existing program that allows contributions of
only $500, and only for college students.
</P>
<P>
   The House measure, sponsored by Rep. Kenny Hulshof, R-Mo., also
would:
</P>
<P>
   --back a national public school construction initiative.
</P>
<P>
   --increase student loan interest deduction.
</P>
<P>
   --make earnings on prepaid college tuition plans tax exempt
rather than tax deferred.
</P>
<P>
   --provide incentives for companies to donate computer equipment
to public schools.
</P>
<P>
   It would cost an estimated $11.6 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, said the
legislation would give parents ''more choices as they design the
best education for their children.'' He said three-fourths of the
benefits would go to children in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats argued that the savings accounts would be used
mainly by affluent families and accelerate the abandonment of
public school systems.
</P>
<P>
   The National Education Association, in a statement, said the GOP
bill ''diverts billions of dollars to tax breaks for private school
education savings accounts'' and that families with children in
private school would receive more than half the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, the ranking Democrat on the
committee, joined Johnson in offering an amendment that would have
stripped out the education savings account provisions and
substituted language to subsidize $24.8 billion in zero-interest
school modernization bonds. It was defeated on a voice vote.
</P>
<P>
   Coming up with the money to hire more teachers and build and
modernize school facilities has been the top education priority of
the White House and Democrats. Republicans have emphasized giving
states, local school districts and parents more control over
education dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: The bill is H.R. 7
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://thomas.loc.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 0306 </TRAILER>
