<HEADLINE> Protesters in China Block Trains  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- People protesting the closure of a
company that had illegally raised money from investors blocked the
main train line in eastern China, delaying more than 40 trains,
officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The protest by 2,000 to 3,000 people in Zhenjiang, 180 miles
northwest of Shanghai, began early Wednesday, said an employee of
the Zhenjiang train station. She said the protest lasted seven to
eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters were upset by the closure of a Zhenjiang company
that attracted unauthorized investments by promising high interest,
the station employee said. She said depositors were unhappy with
repayment terms announced by authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Zhenjiang Public Cooperative refused to give
any information about the company or sums of money involved.
</P>
<P>
   Zhenjiang police said the protest ended peacefully but would not
say whether anyone was arrested or give any details.
</P>
<P>
   The line through Zhenjiang is the major train route in eastern
China, connecting Shanghai with Nanjing, Beijing and other major
cities to the north.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 42 trains were delayed by the protest, said an
employee of the Shanghai Train Station information office.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers were taken off some trains and bused to Nanjing.
</P>
</TEXT>
