<HEADLINE> Audit Looks at AIDS Care  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN GULLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Blacks and Hispanics with AIDS are getting
inferior care compared with whites who have the disease, government
auditors concluded in an assessment of how government funding on
AIDS programs was spent.
</P>
<P>
   ''Compared with whites, African Americans and Hispanics receive
less appropriate care for their HIV disease,'' said an audit to be
released today by the General Accounting Office, the investigative
arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The audit of funds administered to state and local AIDS service
groups through Ryan White Comprehensive AIDS Resource Act grants
was requested by Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., a doctor who has treated
patients with AIDS and HIV.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-year-old act, named for the Indiana boy whose battle with
AIDS attracted national attention, provides money for health
clinics treating low-income AIDS patients and for training for
those caring for HIV-infected individuals. It has provided nearly
$8 billion in government funds to AIDS programs. The money goes
primarily to cities with high concentrations of AIDS patients and
to states.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO audit showed that blacks, Hispanics and women were
receiving substandard care when compared to whites when it comes to
doctors' visits, emergency room visits, hospitalizations and drug
therapies.
</P>
<P>
   The findings come as research shows that the AIDS epidemic is
hitting minorities and women hard. Blacks, who make up about 13
percent of the U.S. population, accounted for 49 percent of AIDS
deaths in 1998, according to the Centers for Disease Control.
Thirty-two percent of deaths were among whites and 18 percent were
among Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   More than 23 percent of AIDS diagnoses reported in 1998 were
among women.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn blamed the disparity in care on ''faulty emphasis on AIDS
data in determining funding and priority setting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ryan White Care Act program does not take into account that
women and minorities account for many new cases of HIV infection
when funding decisions are made, Coburn said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those with HIV, of which women and communities of color are
the fastest growing segments, are currently not counted or
recognized when funding is determined,'' said Coburn in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO audit also found that rural areas may offer more limited
medical and social services than cities because urban areas
generally receive more money per AIDS case.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Flavin, spokesman for the HIV/AIDS Bureau at the Department
of Health and Human Services, which administers the Ryan White Care
Act grants, said he had not seen the GAO final report and could not
comment on the findings.
</P>
<P>
   HHS initiated a new program in 1998, in collaboration with the
Congressional Black Caucus, to help blacks and Hispanics get
services to their communities. Part of the $527 million in Ryan
White CARE Act grants appropriated to AIDS programs this year is
aimed at minority communities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 0309 </TRAILER>
