<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 08:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF: TB Threatens Asian Economy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Tuberculosis poses a serious threat to
Asia's sustained socioeconomic development, the United Nations
Children's Fund said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued ahead of World TB Day on Friday, UNICEF
said that Asia accounts for about 70 percent of all TB cases. It
said that each year there are 8 million new cases of TB and an
estimated 2 million people die of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The spread of tuberculosis -- an opportunistic disease which
afflicts especially weakened persons -- has been abetted by the
spread of HIV/AIDS, which has hit Asia hard. TB itself is a
bacterial infection that spreads through the air when an infected
person coughs, spits or sneezes, and which usually affects the
lungs.
</P>
<P>
   ''People whose immune systems have been weakened by HIV/AIDS
face a 30 times greater risk of developing the disease,'' UNICEF
said. ''Approximately 40 percent of people with HIV/AIDS also
develop TB, and in many countries TB is also the leading cause of
death for HIV/AIDS-infected people.''
</P>
<P>
   A separate U.N. agency dealing with AIDS, UNAIDS, noted that TB
hinders development because it frequently hits society's most
economically active sector, those between the ages of 15 and 54.
</P>
<P>
   The director of UNICEF's East Asia and Pacific office in
Bangkok, Kul C. Gautam, was quoted as saying that TB kills 750,000
women each year, more than any other infectious disease.
</P>
<P>
   ''The deep stigma of TB often results in women being ostracized
by their families and communities, which in turn has a devastating
impact on the well-being of their children, families and society in
general,'' Gautam said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that effective treatments are possible, and some Asian
nations, even poorer ones, have been trying to implement them.
</P>
<P>
   ''The remaining challenge is to mobilize sufficient political
will to attack TB and to build a social partnership that includes
governments, the business and private sectors, concerned
institutions, NGOs ,and communities and families,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
