<HEADLINE> Army Replaces Hundreds of Missiles  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS, AP Military Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army has replaced hundreds of Patriot
missiles in the Mideast and South Korea after discovering a pattern
of technical glitches in the air defense weapon system, the
Pentagon said today.
</P>
<P>
   Rear Adm. Craig Quigley, a Pentagon spokesman, confirmed a
report in today's editions of The Wall Street Journal that the
flawed missiles have been swapped out with newer ones. Quigley said
technical experts at the Army's Redstone Arsenal in Alabama are
attempting to determine the cause of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal quoted Army Lt. Gen. Paul Kern, a senior acquisition
officer in the Pentagon, as saying the decision to quickly replace
the suspect missiles was made after ''a significant number of
failures were found'' during testing.
</P>
<P>
   The number of withdrawn missiles is classified but they were
pulled over the past 10 days from approximately 11 batteries
protecting U.S. forces in South Korea, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia, the
Journal reported. Each battery has about 64 missiles, and Pentagon
officials today said the number pulled was in the hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriot is used to defend against aircraft and short-range
ballistic missiles at medium and high altitudes. An upgraded
version, called the PAC-3, is being developed to provide a greater
capability against short-range missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The part of the system that appears most vulnerable is a radio
frequency downlink that allows the missile to communicate with
radar guiding its flight. Quigley said it was possible -- though not
yet confirmed -- that the problem could be a result of aging. He
said the problem was detected in Patriot batteries that are kept
powered up constantly on full alert, but not in those in a lower
state of readiness.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. allies such as Israel which operate their own Patriot
missile batteries have been informed of the problem, Quigley said.
The issue is of particular concern to Israel, which, like the
United States, tends to keep more of its Patriot launchers on full
alert.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal quoted Kern as saying he did not know how long it
would take to find a solution. Dave Shea, a spokesman for Raytheon
Co., the missile manufacturer, said the company is working with the
Army to identify and resolve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots have been sold to Germany, Israel, Japan, Kuwait, the
Netherlands and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
