<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 11:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EPA Paperwork Claims 'Misleading'  </HEADLINE>
By LIBBY QUAID, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite an order from Congress to shrink
paperwork, the amount of time that businesses and governments spend
reporting to the Environmental Protection Agency is on the rise,
congressional investigators say.
</P>
<P>
   And EPA officials misled the public with claims to the contrary,
according to a General Accounting Office report.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as last week, EPA Administrator Carol Browner told a
House subcommittee the agency had eliminated more than 26 million
hours of paperwork over the past four years, saving industry $800
million.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher Bond, who requested the GAO study and is
chairman of the Senate subcommittee that oversees the EPA's budget,
said at a hearing today, ''This whole reinvention effort is
beginning to look like an effort to reinvent the facts. Only in
Washington would an agency confuse a goal with an accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond, R-Mo., asked for an explanation of Browner's earlier
statements about paperwork reductions as she testified before his
subcommittee today.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO found that despite an order by Congress to cut
paperwork, the amount of time spent reporting to the EPA actually
rose by 10 million hours -- or 9 percent -- between 1995 and 1998.
And it's projected to grow by another 5 million hours by the end of
this fiscal year, Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Browner said EPA must aggressively set new public health and
environmental standards that require polluting industries to report
to the agency. She also said that making more information public is
another goal.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the same time we are streamlining existing programs, we
have been expanding other programs. That is our job,'' Browner
said.
</P>
<P>
   EPA spokesman David Cohen defended the agency's efforts on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Technically, I think the senator has a point,'' he said of
Bond's remarks. ''But what he's not saying is the good news about
EPA taking burden reduction quite seriously. Compared to where some
of the programs might have been had we not taken action, the
paperwork reduction is significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed the Paperwork Reduction Act on the heels of the
1995 Republican takeover of the House, envisioning a 25 percent,
government-wide reduction in paperwork by the end of fiscal 1998.
The EPA was one of six agencies with an estimated paperwork burden
of 100 million hours or more.
</P>
<P>
   GAO investigators scrutinized areas where EPA said the biggest
reductions occurred. They challenged some, such as EPA's decision
to allow some wastewater facilities with good histories to report
less frequently, which the agency estimated reduced paperwork by
4.7 million hours.
</P>
<P>
   EPA officials who oversee that area told investigators the
change produced ''significantly less'' reduction, although they
could not say precisely how much.
</P>
<P>
   EPA also claimed credit for major reductions when it corrected
mistakes in earlier estimates of paperwork hours, even though
nothing had changed for those filling out the forms.
</P>
<P>
   ''EPA's revisions of agency paperwork estimates had no real
impact on the burden being borne by the public,'' the GAO report
said. ''The underlying reporting and recordkeeping requirements did
not change, only EPA's method of measuring their effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Sullivan, executive director of the National Federation of
Independent Business Legal Foundation, said businesses with between
20 and 50 workers typically spend 19 cents of every dollar on
regulatory costs.
</P>
<P>
   The intent of the 1995 law was to force agencies to consider
less burdensome alternatives, so ''when you have a report that says
EPA's paperwork burden is going up, then that shows EPA is ignoring
the intent of the law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bond, who also chairs the Senate Small Business Committee, said
federal paperwork is particularly burdensome on small businesses
and local communities ''who continue to tell us they are drowning
in paperwork.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   General Accounting Office: www.gao.gov
</P>
<P>
   Environmental Protection Agency: www.epa.gov
</P>
<P>
   Senate Small Business Committee: http://www.senate.gov/ ~sbc
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
