<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Precede WHITE PLAINS  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN MATTHEWS   
Associated Press Writer, 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's reaction to the latest
police shooting of an unarmed black man ''is not just meanness,
it's mental,'' the Rev. Jesse Jackson said today.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's something that is not well about his response to
unarmed people being shot by police,'' Jackson said. ''This
consistent reaction for the police who shoot unarmed people before
even asking for information, without showing sympathy to the
victims ... that sounds like a disturbed person.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's an ugly consistency, and people are beginning to see
that Mr. Giuliani's reaction to these things is not just meanness,
it's mental,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate response from Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's comments, after addressing students at Martin Luther
King Jr. High School in Manhattan, followed by a day similar
comments from an array of critics including Hillary Rodham Clinton,
his opponent in the race for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady said Wednesday that the mayor's actions after
last week's police killing of Patrick Dorismond -- releasing the
victim's sealed juvenile record and his girlfriend's complaint that
he'd hit her -- ''have aggravated tensions in the city and have
helped drive a wedge between the police and the communities they
serve.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Giuliani had ''basically written off'' New York City's
black residents when he said he felt no responsibility to reach out
to the community after the killing.
</P>
<P>
   ''What does that say about how people would be represented by
him?'' she asked. Instead of trying to ease tensions, she said,
Giuliani ''has lashed out at Patrick Dorismond, (Assembly) Speaker
(Sheldon) Silver, at the media, at the Justice Department and at
me.''
</P>
<P>
   NAACP President Kweisi Mfume echoed Clinton's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rather than trying to demonize Patrick Dorismond, an unarmed
Haitian American killed during a police encounter, Giuliani should
be reviewing police training standards to see what steps the
department can take to avoid the unnecessary use of lethal force,''
Mfume said.
</P>
<P>
   In Albany, state Comptroller H. Carl McCall, a black Democrat,
called on Gov. George Pataki to appoint a commission to study the
New York Police Department's use of street crime units, deadly
force and racial profiling, plus its recruitment of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   He said Giuliani apparently believes ''you put out a fire by
throwing gasoline on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to Clinton's remarks, the mayor's campaign spokesman,
Bruce Teitelbaum, said, ''It sounds like Mrs. Clinton is still
reading off the same script prepared by (black activist) Al
Sharpton.''
</P>
<P>
   Statewide polls on the Senate race have routinely shown the
Republican mayor getting less than 10 percent of the black vote,
while Clinton, the likely Democratic nominee, gets more than 80
percent.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the mayor was asked if he felt any responsibility to
talk or meet with black people after the third fatal shooting of an
unarmed black man in 13 months.
</P>
<P>
   ''No, I don't think so,'' he said. ''I think this is a situation
that clearly had nothing to do with race. The three police officers
were Hispanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the mayor has an ''enormous trust chasm'' and ''has
presented a false choice to New Yorkers.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not necessary to choose between effective policing and
respectful policing,'' she said. ''It is not necessary to give up
trust and good relations between the police and the communities
they serve in the pursuit of lowering the crime rate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
