<P>
Major Muslim groups offer help to imam arrested in shootout
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Four U.S. Muslim organizations that urged
fugitive Imam Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin to surrender to authorities
announced after his arrest that they would offer legal help and
monitor his trial.
</P>
<P>
   The imam, known as civil rights militant H. Rap Brown before his
conversion, is charged with fatally shooting one sheriff's deputy
and wounding another as they tried to serve an arrest warrant in
Atlanta for theft and impersonating an officer.
</P>
<P>
   The American Muslim Council, Council on American-Islamic
Relations, Islamic Society of North America and Muslim American
Society said they were not prejudging the case but noted Al-Amin's
''longstanding role as a community leader who had a positive impact
on the lives of so many people.''
</P>
<P>
   The groups said the charges were ''inconsistent with what is
known of his moral character and past behavior as a Muslim.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin's group is recognized as a member of the Islamic Shura
Council that issues orthodox religious rulings, along with the
Islamic Society of North America and Muslim American Society.
