<P>
Episcopalians cancel consecration of new bishop
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- The Atlanta diocese of the Episcopal Church
canceled the consecration of its new bishop on short notice, citing
''very recent discoveries of lack of disclosure in personal
financial and family matters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution said the Rev. Robert Trache and
his wife filed for personal bankruptcy in a Virginia federal court
Jan. 20.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Richard Callaway, head of the diocesan standing
committee, told the newspaper the issue was not so much the
couple's problems as ''how they handled the decisions they made and
how they were disclosed to the body of the faithful.''
</P>
<P>
   Trache was in Atlanta when the cancellation occurred but issued
no comment.
</P>
<P>
   The priest, who was also a candidate for bishop of Michigan last
year, was formerly rector of St. James' Episcopal Church in
Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Episcopal News Service said Trache would not be returning to the
Richmond parish, which has already begun the search process for a
new rector.
</P>
