<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stepfather shoots himself on roof after teen's remains found  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DIX HILLS, N.Y. (AP) -- A Long Island family's tragedy doubled
when a man allegedly butchered his stepson, scrawled an anti-black,
anti-gay slur on the remains, then killed himself during a police
standoff.
</P>
<P>
   John Fenrich Jr., 36, committed suicide Wednesday, a day after
police told him that remains found in a Queens park were believed
to be those of his 19-year-old stepson, Steen Keith Fenrich.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, Fenrich had called a local cable news station
and said his stepson's dismembered body had been found; but
investigators had not told him the body was dismembered, police
sources told The Associated Press, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   A skull, foot and pulverized bone fragments were found by a
passerby Tuesday afternoon in a plastic container in Alley Pond
Park in Bayside, Queens. The teen-ager's Social Security number was
scrawled on the skull, along with a racial epithet and derogatory
term for homosexuals, the sources said. Steen's mother, Wanda, is
black. John Fenrich was white.
</P>
<P>
   Police sources said today that the flesh from the bones had
either been boiled off or burned off with acid.
</P>
<P>
   Police downplayed a published report that, during hours of
negotiations, Fenrich confessed to killing his stepson because
Steen Fenrich was gay.
</P>
<P>
   After the stepfather, a self-employed carpenter, called News12
Long Island, the station called police to report that Fenrich was
considering suicide. News12 did not air the contents of the
conversation and would not confirm that Fenrich had mentioned body
parts.
</P>
<P>
   Suffolk police arrived at Fenrich's house in Dix Hills at 5:20
a.m. An hour later, Fenrich climbed onto his roof holding a handgun
and a high-powered rifle and fired several shots into the air.
</P>
<P>
   Fenrich's wife and 15-year-old son left the brown-shingled
split-level home a short time later. Neighbors were told to stay in
their basements while hostage negotiators tried to talk him down.
The elder Fenrich's brother, a sergeant in the New York Police
Department, was at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   One neighbor who refused to be identified said Fenrich told the
cops: ''Shoot me! Shoot me! What are you waiting for?''
</P>
<P>
   Another neighbor, who also would not give her name, said she
heard him telling police, ''I'm a failure as a father.''
</P>
<P>
   At 1:25 p.m., Fenrich put a gun to his head, pulled the trigger
and fell to the ground. He was pronounced dead at Good Samaritan
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ''He reached for the gun after someone screamed something from
the ground, then the shot went off,'' said Bill Paden, 25, who
lives across the street. ''He was just sitting there for most of
the morning and then it just got crazy the last 10 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Fenrich and his wife had a checkered past. According to court
records, they were indicted in 1998 in a bizarre scheme that
involved bilking insurance companies out of hundreds of thousands
of dollars. The Fenriches were charged with filing false claims
based on self-inflicted injuries, including staged car accidents
and phony slip-and-falls.
</P>
<P>
   In one claim submitted in 1998, John Fenrich said a son -- not
named -- was hit by a motorist while riding a bike. Fenrich also
claimed he lost his pinkie in a 1995 car accident; an investigator
found evidence the finger had been amputated years earlier, the
papers said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fenriches were out on bail while negotiating a plea bargain
in the case, according to Mrs. Fenrich's attorney, Steven Keats.
</P>
<P>
   Shari Lawrence, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Army Personnel
Command, said available records showed Steen Keith Fenrich, the
stepson, joined the Army in July 1997, went through basic training
at Fort Jackson, S.C., and was later trained as a food service
specialist. He was discharged after nine months, but the reason and
his status at the time were not publicly released, Lawrence said.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor, Ray Saper, said he ran into Steen Fenrich four
months ago and learned he had gotten his own apartment in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was just a very nice guy.... He was always jogging or
in-line skating through the neighborhood,'' said Karina Wahee, 21,
a neighbor who graduated a year ahead of Steen from Half Hollow
Hills East High School. ''When I heard, I thought, 'No, it just
can't be them.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Fenrich home, surrounded by trees, is in a mixed
neighborhood of middle-class homes, million-dollar mansions,
brand-new developments and wooded lots.
</P>
<P>
   The rifle could still be seen lying on the roof near several
skylights late Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Associated Press writers Donna De La Cruz and Tom Hays
contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
