<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Couple Who Sued Kmart Awarded $23M  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GASTONIA, N.C. (AP) -- A couple who claimed they were roughed up
by Kmart security guards while exercise-walking behind a store won
a $23 million judgment -- but state law capping punitive damages at
$250,000 will give the retail giant a break.
</P>
<P>
   Dan and Alice Rhyne of Gastonia claimed they were attacked in
1998 while walking a three-mile route around Kmart and other
stores. They said two men, who were not wearing Kmart uniforms and
did not identify themselves as store employees, attacked them
behind the Kmart store.
</P>
<P>
   The Rhynes said when they refused to follow security guard Shawn
Roberts into the store, he put Dan Rhyne in a choke hold until
police arrived. Police arrested them, and the Rhynes sued.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just knew somebody had to believe us, and they came
through,'' said Dan Rhyne, 57. ''It's been a long two years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gastonia County jury found Kmart and Roberts liable for
unlawful detention. The other guard was cleared of liability early
in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Rhynes' lawyer, Bill Moore, said he expects the judge to
reduce the $23 million verdict to the $250,000 allowed by the
state. He said he then will appeal in hopes of getting the state
Supreme Court to overturn the law restricting punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Kmart attorney John Honeycutt Jr. declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 1358 </TRAILER>
