<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000323.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate OKs cut in farmers' crop-insurance premiums  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER, AP Farm Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate today overwhelmingly approved
legislation that would sharply reduce the premiums farmers pay for
federally subsidized crop insurance and encourage growers to buy
higher levels of coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which passed 95-5, also would offer coverage for
the first time to livestock producers and expand policies for fruit
and vegetable growers.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, similar to a bill approved by the House last
year, would cost taxpayers $1.5 billion annually over the next four
years. A House-Senate conference committee will work out the
differences between the two bills.
</P>
<P>
   Policies can be purchased to protect farmers from
weather-related losses as well as drops in commodity prices. But
many farmers, especially in the South and East, say the insurance
is too expensive for the coverage it provides.
</P>
<P>
   ''Very few businesses have the economic situation that
agriculture has. Just a little more supply than is necessary will
cause prices to go down,'' said Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, said the legislation ''will
provide the security necessary to help farmers through lean years
so that they will be around to experience better prices and
increased revenue in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The government now pays from 13 percent to 57 percent of a
farmer's premium, depending on the level of coverage. Under the
Senate bill, the government's share on most policies would range
from 45 percent to 60 percent. The House bill would have the
government pay from 31 percent to 67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the legislation say it could pay for itself, if
sufficient farmers buy coverage to lessen the pressure on Congress
to provide disaster assistance each year. Congress has approved $15
billion in emergency aid over the past two years to compensate
growers for weather-related losses and a slump in commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
   ''Under this legislation, there will be enough incentives for
farmer to participate at high levels that in a future disaster the
need for disaster aid will drop significantly,'' said Ken Ackerman,
administrator of the Agriculture Department's Risk Management
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The program has tripled in size since the early 1990s and covers
about two-thirds of the eligible acreage nationally. The program is
paying farmers some $2.2 billion to cover losses on 1999 crops
caused by drought, hurricane and rain.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to senators earlier this week, the Agriculture
Department said the bill ''represents real progress'' but raised
several concerns about the measure, including a provision that
would reduce USDA's role on a board that oversees the program.
</P>
<P>
   Senators from the Northeast insisted on setting aside $126
million in the legislation to help farmers in their region get the
insurance. Few farmers in the region now buy the coverage,
including only 8 percent of producers in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Although lawmakers from the Plains states have been pushing
hardest for the higher subsidies, the legislation is ''going to
have to be viewed by people all across the country as having
something that's going to benefit them,'' said the chairman of the
House Agriculture Committee, Rep. Larry Combest, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Five Republicans voted against the measure, in addition to
Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi: Thad Cochran of
Mississippi, Judd Gregg of New Hampshire, John McCain of Arizona
and Jon Kyl of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 2559.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: USDA's Risk Management Agency site:
http://www.rma.usda.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-23-00 1358 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000323.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cops Say Man Killed Son and Himself  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DIX HILLS, N.Y. (AP) -- A man who fatally shot himself during a
rooftop standoff committed suicide after killing his stepson,
dismembering the body and scrawling racist and anti-gay slurs on
the remains, police said.
</P>
<P>
   John Fenrich Jr., 36, began his siege after telling a TV station
that the dismembered remains of his stepson had been found, even
though investigators never announced the body had been mutilated.
</P>
<P>
   Fenrich called News12 Long Island before dawn Wednesday, saying
he was considering suicide because of his son's slaying. The
station then called police, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, investigators told Fenrich they had found the
remains of 19-year-old Steen Keith Fenrich in a park in the borough
of Queens, New York City Police Detective George Nagy said.
</P>
<P>
   A skull, foot and pulverized bone fragments were found by a
passerby Tuesday afternoon in a plastic container in Alley Pond
Park. Police said Fenrich scrawled his stepson's Social Security
number on the skull, along with racial and homophobic epithets.
Steen's mother, Wanda, is black. The stepfather was white.
</P>
<P>
   After being called by the cable station, police arrived at
Fenrich's split-level home on Long Island. Fenrich climbed onto his
roof holding a handgun and a rifle and fired several shots into the
air.
</P>
<P>
   Fenrich's wife and 15-year-old son left the home a short time
later. Neighbors were told to stay in their basements while police
negotiators tried to talk Fenrich down. His brother, a New York
City police sergeant, also was at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Eight hours into the siege, Fenrich put a gun to his head and
pulled the trigger. He was pronounced dead at a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Fenrich and his wife were indicted in 1998 in an insurance-fraud
scheme in which they were accused of filing false claims based on
self-inflicted injuries and staged car accidents.
</P>
<P>
   In one claim, John Fenrich said a son -- not named -- was hit by a
motorist while riding a bike. Fenrich also claimed he lost his
pinkie in a 1995 car accident; an investigator found evidence the
finger had been amputated years earlier, authorities said in court
papers said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fenriches were out on bail while negotiating a plea bargain
in the case, according to Mrs. Fenrich's attorney, Steven Keats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 1400 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000323.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chaplain Candidate Offers To Quit  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Rev. Charles Wright, whose selection as
House chaplain triggered charges of religious bias in Congress,
offered to withdraw this week in a private meeting with Speaker
Dennis Hastert, Republican sources said today.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, his nomination in limbo for months, made his offer amid
signs that Hastert was moving quickly to find a replacement.
Republicans are eager to quell a controversy in which some
Democrats accused them of anti-Catholic bias for passing over a
priest last fall when Wright was tapped.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, a Presbyterian minister, could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   John Feehery, Hastert's spokesman, declined all comment on the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   But several sources said the speaker and Wright held an
unannounced meeting in the Capitol on Tuesday. They said the
minister decided on his own to offer his withdrawal, without any
pressure from the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Wright's nomination emerged last fall from a bipartisan
committee of lawmakers, but Hastert has the authority to name a
chaplain on his own authority. It was not clear how quickly he
would do so, or what the religion would be of his selection.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have been battered for months by charges of
anti-Catholic bias that first arose when the Rev. Tim O'Brien was
passed over for the chaplain's post.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am convinced that if I were a mainline Protestant minister
and not a Catholic priest, I would be the candidate,'' he said in
an interview in December, and some Democrats also alleged bias.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said O'Brien had been the top pick of the bipartisan
group of lawmakers that sifted through contenders, but Hastert and
Majority Leader Dick Armey turned to Wright instead. The two GOP
leaders said they had been given a list of three finalists -- Wright
and O'Brien included -- but were unaware of any ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans complain that Democratic leader Dick Gephardt first
agreed to Wright's choice, but has since sought to gain political
gain, particularly in view of the fact that Catholics are expected
to account for more than 25 percent of the voters in this fall's
election. In public comments, Gephardt has criticized the selection
process as flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Both Hastert and Armey have strongly denied any anti-Catholic
bias, and Hastert recently told a closed-door meeting of lawmakers
the matter had weighed heavily on him personally.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Republicans have initiated a series of
gestures in recent months that appeared part of an effort to
counter the criticism. These included awarding the Congressional
Gold Medal to an elderly and ill Cardinal John O'Connor of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Associated Press Writer Jennifer Loven contributed to this
article.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 1402 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000323.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Passes Crop Insurance Bill  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER, AP Farm Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
