<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved sharply higher today, led by
another advance in tech shares, after The Wall Street Journal
reported Microsoft is moving closer to resolving its antitrust
dispute with the government.
</P>
<P>
   In early afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 198.24 at 11,064.94. The Nasaq composite
index rose 110.91 at 4,975.66.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, which passed 1,500 and reached
a new closing high Wednesday, rose another 27.66 to 1,528.30.
</P>
<P>
   Tech stocks, following a big advance Wednesday, advanced today
as Microsoft surged on the Journal's report that the company and
the government are accelerating their talks toward settling a
wide-ranging antitrust suit. Microsoft was up 7~ at 111[.
</P>
<P>
   Other technology bellwethers also rose. Shares in network
equipment maker Cisco Systems rose 4 7/16 to 76|, and Oracle, a
major business software company, was up 3 1/16 to 87[.
</P>
<P>
   Brian G. Belski, chief investment strategist at George K. Baum &AMP;
Co., in Kansas City, said the big moves by tech leaders over the
past few days have been spilling over into smaller tech companies
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ''Microsoft, Cisco and Intel have been very strong over the past
few days, and some investors have started to think that they're
missing something,'' Belski said.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in chip maker Intel fell, however, as investors collected
some of the stunning 75 percent gains the stock has seen since the
beginning of this year. Intel was off 3[ at 140 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Blue chip industrial stocks also rose as fund managers adjusted
their portfolios for the end of the first quarter. Aluminum maker
Alcoa rose 3 to 69~, and International Paper rose 2 3/16 to 39
7/16. Both are components of the Dow 30.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors also rose 3 9/16 to 85 3/16 on a rumor that the
media conglomerate News Corp. was interested in making a bid for
the automaker in order to get its satellite subsidiary, Hughes
Electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues edged declining issues by a margin of 3-to-2 on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 710.97 million
shares, down slightly from the same time Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index, which includes smaller companies, was up
6.52 at 577.71.
</P>
</TEXT>
