<HEADLINE> Brokerage harassment suit settled  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Two Wall Street brokerage houses settled a $10
million sexual harassment lawsuit Thursday, giving female employees
a shot at damages for alleged outrageous sexual antics that
prompted comparisons to ''Animal House.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This case should send a strong message to all of Wall Street
that we will not tolerate an old boys' club or frat house
atmosphere in the workplace,'' said state Attorney General Eliot
Spitzer, who announced the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Garban LLC and its affiliated firm, Garvin Guy Butler, were
accused of allowing strippers onto the trading floor, permitting
pornography in the office, and allowing male workers to drop their
pants in the view of female workers.
</P>
<P>
   Women at Garban ''were subjected to continual, unwelcome sexual
harassment,'' according to the suit.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement was extended to include minority workers who were
allegedly subjected to racial epithets and racist jokes. Executives
at both companies were not only aware of the racist and lewd
behavior, but participated, the suit alleged.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed by the state attorney general in 1998, was
settled with a deal that clears the way for dozens of Garban
employees to collect back pay, lost benefits, lawyers' fees and
damages.
</P>
<P>
   Female and minority workers who were at the firm between
September 1996 and September 1998 are eligible.
</P>
<P>
   A private company was brought in to resolve any claims. The
process was expected to take about a year, and Garban will pay the
expenses, said Spitzer spokesman Scott Brown.
</P>
<P>
   A call for comment to Garban's office in lower Manhattan was not
returned Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other complaints contained in the lawsuit were that
male workers routinely bragged about their sexual exploits, used
the bathroom with the door open, and addressed women in vulgar
terms.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit claimed that the harassment began in 1984. Employees
who complained about mistreatment were often threatened or fired,
the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Garban will pay $200,000 to cover the
state's legal fees, as well as implementing several new policies to
prevent a repeat of the aberrant behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The company was also required to report any bias complaint over
the next three years directly to the attorney general's office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
