<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Florida Competing for Spring Break  </HEADLINE>
By BILL KACZOR, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- As he basked in the sun, sipping
a beer on a glistening white Florida Panhandle beach, Anthony
Keller was already looking ahead to his next spring break.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year-old Penn State University student said he'll likely
go to Cancun, Mexico, or one of the other foreign destinations that
are giving Florida a run for its spring break money.
</P>
<P>
   ''More freedom, more liberty,'' said Keller, of Palmerton, Pa.
''There's probably more things to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Panama City Beach remains the leading domestic destination for
spring break, annually attracting an estimated 400,000 to 500,000
visitors, according to Student Travel Services in Hanover, Md.
Other top spring break spots include Daytona Beach, South Padre
Island, Texas, Lake Havasu City, Ariz., Myrtle Beach, S.C., Miami's
South Beach and Key West.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, however, students are heading for foreign shores,
attracted by relatively low cost tour packages -- from around $600
to $700 per person with four to a room for a week including air
fare -- a lower drinking age and a virtual guarantee of warm weather
in tropical climates. North Florida can be chilly in late February
and early March, although temperatures have been mild this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cancun, Jamaica, Acapulco are all hot spots,'' said Kirk
Riley, president of Student Adventure Travel, based in Dallas City,
Ill. Some students are forsaking beaches altogether and opting for
Paris or London.
</P>
<P>
   Riley began in the tour business with spring bus trips, but he
stopped doing Florida after the drinking age increased to 21. He
didn't want to deal with students getting into trouble for underage
drinking and drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a problem in Cancun and other destinations where the
drinking age is 18 and students fly, rather than drive.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Baranoski, the office manager for Student Travel
Services, which serves as a ticket wholesaler from a number of tour
operators, said they sent a record 20,000 students to Cancun on
more than 100 charter planes during the week of March 11-18. The
company's overall spring break business has gone from 27,000
travelers last year to 40,000 this year, mostly to Cancun.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cancun's got everything,'' said Mike Rush, vice president of
Sun Coast Vacations in Waitsfield, Vt. ''It has the nightlife. It
has some cultural activities and day excursions. People can go to
the Mayan ruins.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing popularity of foreign destinations has not gone
unnoticed in Panama City Beach, where spring break has meant big
business in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Party central shifted west to Panama City Beach about 10 years
ago, when officials in Daytona Beach decided to clean up that
city's image as a place where drunken fraternity boys pass out on
the beach. Daytona Beach inherited spring break from Fort
Lauderdale, which parted ways with the college crowd in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   In January, some tourism officials blamed foreign competition
when hotels reported that spring break bookings were down as much
as 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of Panama City Beach's demise, however, were premature,
said Robert Warren, executive director of the city's Convention and
Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   A last-minute publicity push helped increase reservations, and
Warren predicted that revenues will equal past years. He said
bookings probably were slow to start due to a late Easter that has
spread spring break business, usually lasting five or six weeks,
over a two-month period.
</P>
<P>
   No changes are necessary as far as Scott Farrell, 23, of
Brooklyn, Ohio, is concerned. The winter graduate of Ohio Northern
University took time off from his sales job for a spring break
fling with a couple buddies still in college.
</P>
<P>
   Farrell said he found police to be lenient and got a good rate
at his hotel. He also said the recently renourished beach was a
vast improvement over the storm-eroded one he visited in Cancun
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is my first time here and I've definitely enjoyed it,''
Keller said. ''I'm having as good or better time than I did in
Cancun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 1432 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000323.0119 </DOCNO>
