<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Can Oil Riches Stabilize Nigeria?  </HEADLINE>
By GLENN McKENZIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) -- Beneath the swamps where poor Nigerians
eke out a living from fishing and farming are some of the world's
largest untapped oil fields.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the precious resource that gives troubled Nigeria hope for
the future also fuels spiraling violence that threatens the
political and economic prospects of Africa's energy giant.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when crude prices have tripled from 1998 lows, the
world's sixth-largest exporter has some of the industry's largest
untapped oil fields.
</P>
<P>
   Community activists in the oil-rich Niger Delta demand some of
that wealth for the impoverished region and stage frequent attacks
against petroleum facilities, kidnapping workers and sabotaging
pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   Police and soldiers have responded with deadly raids, razing a
village last November. Human rights groups estimate hundreds of
people have been killed in clashes with police.
</P>
<P>
   The government of President Olusegun Obasanjo, whose election
last year ended 15 years of military rule, has sent confusing
signals about how it plans to handle the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The state Nigerian National Petroleum Corp. has warned it will
fund a police unit authorized to shoot saboteurs on sight. But the
government has also made vague promises of development money to
appease restive communities.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria produces about 2 million barrels of oil a day, worth
nearly $17 billion last year. Roughly one-twelfth of the oil
imported by the United States comes from Nigeria, and the country
has proven reserves of 25 billion barrels.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite its oil wealth, years of corrupt military rule have
left Nigeria one of the world's 25 poorest nations. And the Delta,
where most of the drilling occurs, is one of its poorest regions.
</P>
<P>
   Sabotage forces costly pipeline shutdowns and other industry
delays. Last year, 497 cases of vandalism were reported, compared
to 57 a year earlier. These include frequent cases of local
residents siphoning off fuel by puncturing pipelines with picks and
shovels, then using buckets and barrels to collect the spilling
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   At least 35 people, including children, were killed Wednesday
when a fire broke out while they were siphoning off gasoline in a
remote part of southeastern Abia state. Twenty people were injured,
and authorities said 28 suspected vandals were taken into custody.
In October 1998, a huge explosion and fire sparked by scavengers
siphoning off fuel in the Niger Delta town of Jesse killed at least
700 people.
</P>
<P>
   ''Deliberate action is necessary to send a strong message'' to
those who sabotage the pipelines, a spokesman for the state oil
company, Ndu Ughamadu, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   But human rights activists warn that any move to crack down on
the vandalism with hired guns threatens to heighten tensions in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Officials warn the government will also get tough with oil
companies blamed by state officials and Delta villagers for water
and air pollution that has harmed fishing and farming.
</P>
<P>
   Environment Minister Imeh Okopido said he plans legislation that
would require oil companies to eliminate spills and the practice of
flaring -- burning natural gas produced as a byproduct of oil
drilling -- by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the 42 years since oil activities began in Nigeria, nothing
has been done about the atrocious state of the environment. That is
going to change,'' Okopido said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The oil companies agree that flaring could be eliminated by
selling the natural gas instead of burning it, but are pushing for
a more conservative target of 2008.
</P>
<P>
   The government also promises to boost development and tackle
corruption, which has diverted billions of dollars from the economy
in recent decades and left schools, roads and hospitals in decay.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pledges, no new government money has been channeled
to the Delta so far. Proposals to increase government and company
spending from 3 percent to 13 percent of overall revenue have also
stalled under Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies have advocated more government-led development as
a way to bring stability. The Shell Oil Co. spent $42 million on
community assistance projects in 1998, according to company
spokesman James Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not enough money from oil wealth is plowed back into the Delta
region for development,'' Herbert said in a telephone interview
from London.
</P>
<P>
   The oil companies' profit margin is among the world's highest.
Retrieval costs in the Delta hover between $3 and $5 a barrel,
while recent oil prices were over $30, said Aret Adams, a Nigerian
oil industry analyst and former government adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Observers say attacks against the industry could escalate if it
doesn't do more.
</P>
<P>
   ''The industry needs to put their money where their mouth is if
it expects to end communal violence,'' Adams said. ''People without
jobs or food in their stomachs can be moved to desperate acts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 1526 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000323.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Was Unanimous in Rate Hike  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve's policy-making committee
was unanimous in its decision to boost an important interest rate
by a quarter-point in February to keep inflation from becoming a
problem. However, some members had urged that the rate be pushed
even higher.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Open Market Committee, which includes Fed Chairman
Alan Greenspan, voted 10-0 to raise the federal funds rate -- the
interest that banks charge each other on overnight loans-- to 5.75
percent, according to minutes of the Feb. 1-2 meeting released
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   That marked the fourth time the Fed boosted the funds rate since
June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Even though there was no dissent on the February funds rate
increase, the minutes said that in discussion before the vote, a
few, unidentified members expressed a preference for a half-point
increase in the funds rate ''in order to provide greater assurance
against a buildup of inflationary expectations and inflation over
coming months.''
</P>
<P>
   And, other members acknowledged that the Fed ''might need to
move more aggressively at a later meeting'' should the rapidly
growing economy generate a pick up in inflation pressures.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the minutes said that all members agreed to the
quarter point move for a number of reasons, including uncertainties
about the outlook for growth in demand relative to that of supply,
the economy's response to previous rate increases and somewhat
unsettled conditions in financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Members ''saw little risk in a gradual approach,'' the minutes
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Fed boosted interest rates by another
quarter-point to slow the red-hot economy and keep inflation under
control. That action pushed the funds rate to 6 percent. The
minutes of that meeting are expected to be released in May.
</P>
<P>
   At the February meeting, policy-makers also were united in
expressing their concerns that inflation could spoil the economic
good times the country is currently enjoying.
</P>
<P>
   Members unanimously agreed that future risks to the economy were
''weighted mainly toward conditions that may generate heightened
inflation pressures in the foreseeable future.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed also decided to boost its mostly symbolic discount rate,
the interest that the Fed charges to make direct loans to banks, by
a quarter-point at the February meeting. It did so again on
Tuesday, pushing the rate to 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The Federal Reserve site:
http://www.federalreserve.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 1534 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000323.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Black Caucus Wants More African Aid  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL SHEPARD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional Black Caucus members called on
U.S. lawmakers to forgive the debt of flood-ravaged countries in
southern Africa and help the nations rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are witnessing a tragedy of catastrophic proportions,''
said Rep. Barbara Lee, D-Calif., at a news conference Thursday that
also drew ambassadors from several African nations.
</P>
<P>
   Caucus Chairman James Clyburn, D-S.C., said the widespread
flooding -- which has hit Zimbabwe, Swaziland, Madagascar and South
Africa -- threatens progress made by the hardest-hit country,
Mozambique, to end internal warring and feed its people.
</P>
<P>
   Clyburn said last year was the first year the impoverished
country didn't request international food aid.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't want to see the gains washed away with the flood
waters,'' Clyburn said.
</P>
<P>
   This week alone, low-lying southern Mozambican towns are at risk
of being flooded for the second time in less than a month as heavy
rains upstream in South Africa drove up water levels in local
rivers.
</P>
<P>
   More than a month of floods, the worst on record in the
southeast African nation, have displaced more than 1 million people
nationwide, according to the caucus.
</P>
<P>
   In Madagascar, flooding has killed more than 1,500 people and a
cholera outbreak brought on by the deluge has infected more than
25,000 others.
</P>
<P>
   The confirmed death toll of 492 is expected to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have been among the 1,400 aid workers, 1,000 soldiers
and 53 aircraft from eight separate armies to descend on the
southeast African nation this month.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., however, called the U.S. response
''inexcusably slow'' and plans to introduce legislation to forgive
the debts and provide reconstruction aid for eight southern African
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said last week the U.S.
Agency for International Development already has provided $7
million in emergency food aid and $5.7 million in disaster
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   She said the Treasury Department is moving to forgive the $4.9
million debt owed by Mozambique to the U.S. government, and
assistance is going to Zimbabwe, Botswana and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has already forgiven nearly all the debt owed
by Mozambique. But legislation is necessary to coordinate that debt
relief with other nations and to bestow U.S. approval for
international lending agencies like the International Monetary Fund
to engage in debt relief.
</P>
<P>
   Mozambique owes $87 million to creditors this year, of which
approximately $58 million is owed to countries and $30 million to
international institutions.
</P>
<P>
   On March 9, the House passed a resolution expressing support for
humanitarian assistance.
</P>
</TEXT>
