<HEADLINE> Clinton Feasts On Indian Delicacies  </HEADLINE>
By KRISHNAN GURUSWAMY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- What's on Clinton's plate in India?
Marinated shrimp, lamb cooked in a clay oven, spicy chicken,
vegetable pilaf, buttery lentil, cottage cheese, pickles, two
scoops of mango ice cream, an eggless Indian ice cream,
almond-pistachio fudge, almond-saffron sorbet, and three other
sweets.
</P>
<P>
   All in one meal.
</P>
<P>
   ''Wonderful. Thank you,'' Clinton told the staff after the
feast, detailed in Indian newspapers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   So much for lunch. Dinner was another mouthful.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton went to an Afghan restaurant that same day and shared at
least five meat dishes along with assorted vegetables, stews and
breads -- including a four-foot naan -- with daughter Chelsea and
mother-in-law Dorothy Rodham.
</P>
<P>
   Chef Gev Desai tried to persuade Clinton to have another helping
but the president demurred. ''If I eat any more, you guys will have
to carry me out on a stretcher,'' he said, according to the Times
of India.
</P>
<P>
   Lunch was with Indian President K.R. Narayanan at the Ashok
Hotel; dinner at Maurya Sheraton's Bukhara restaurant. Clinton has
been to at least four restaurants on his all-you-can-eat trip.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Clinton planned to give a dose of medicine to three young
tuberculosis victims in a visit to a Hyderabad hospital Friday. But
because he was coming, the hospital turned some patients away.
</P>
<P>
   Daga Shantilal, who is from the trust that runs Mahavir
Hospital, denied the hospital was ignoring ill patients and said
many people were trying to be admitted only to see Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Police and hospital guards were seen refusing entry to several
dozen people during a 30-minute period Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   One man, accompanied by two women, argued with a guard, shouting
''It is an emergency.'' The guard said, ''We are not taking any
patients,'' and the three eventually went away.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is this? So many patients are being shifted here and
there all the time because of him,'' said Kelaparthi Shekhar, 24,
who has chronic heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was to administer the last treatment in a six-month
course of medication to two 8-year-old girls and a 15-year-old boy.
He's marking World Tuberculosis Day in the nation with the highest
number of TB sufferers.
</P>
<P>
   The Mahavir Hospital is run by a trust fund of the minority Jain
community, a pacifist sect.
</P>
</TEXT>
