<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers: Push China on Rights  </HEADLINE>
By FREDERIC J. FROMMER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton should personally lobby
foreign heads of state to back a United Nations resolution
condemning China's human rights record, a bipartisan group of
lawmakers said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   ''We don't want our government to just go through the motions,''
Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., said at a news conference. ''We want
the president to be on the phone, calling other nations.''
</P>
<P>
	   Wellstone spoke in Washington while Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright addressed the 53-nation U.N. Human Rights Commission in
Geneva. She asked member countries to back a U.S. resolution
''expressing concern about widespread denials of political,
cultural, labor and religious freedom in China.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Chinese delegation to the U.N. has thwarted attempts at
censure since the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre, in which hundreds
of pro-Democracy activists died.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., applauded the Clinton
administration's efforts but said the president needs to get
personally involved, as he has on other issues.
</P>
<P>
	   ''I want the president to show that he feels just as strong
about human rights, by picking up that telephone and calling
leaders in other nations, and lining up the support that only he
can ensure to see the passage of this important resolution,''
Hutchinson said.
</P>
<P>
	   It was unclear whether Clinton planned to take an active role.
The White House press office referred calls to the National
Security Council, which did not immediately return a phone call
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Those at the Washington news conference gave the administration
credit for pushing harder for the resolution than in past years.
Mike Jendrzejcyzk, Washington director of Human Rights Watch's Asia
Division, said last year the administration made only a ''token
gesture'' to get the resolution passed.
</P>
<P>
	   Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., said she pointedly told Albright at a
hearing this month: ''Either the Chinese are outsmarting us in
Geneva, or we're not trying hard enough. Which could it be? I think
we weren't trying hard enough.''
</P>
<P>
	   Pelosi warned failure to pass the human rights resolution will
make it harder for Congress to approve a bill extending most
favored nation trade status to China, a move favored by the Clinton
administration. Pelosi is among the leading opponents of the
measure.
</P>
<P>
	   Song Yongyi, who was arrested last year and detained by the
Chinese government for nearly six months on charges of spying, said
he owed his release to international pressure.
</P>
<P>
	   ''Dialogue alone is not sufficient,'' said Song, a Chinese-born
librarian at Dickinson College in Carlisle, Pa., who became an
American citizen last month.
</P>
<P>
	   His release, he said, shows that China can ''no longer disregard
strong international pressures on human rights.''
</P>
<P>
	   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Human Rights Commission:
http://www.unhchr.ch/html/menu2/2/chr.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
