<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Give Pakistan Hard Facts  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT, AP White House Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAIPUR, India (AP) -- President Clinton will tell military-ruled
Pakistan it is ''a country that is in trouble'' and should not
waste its energy in a dangerous confrontation with nuclear neighbor
India, National Security Adviser Sandy Berger said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He said Clinton would tell the people of Pakistan that ''we care
about their future, that we don't want Pakistan to fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger said Clinton would ''convey some hard realities'' to Gen.
Pervez Musharraf, the military leader who took over Pakistan's
government in a coup in October and has refused to set a date for
national elections. The United States welcomed Pakistan's
announcement of local elections but said that was not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we're looking for is a roadmap for national elections and
a restoration of democracy in Pakistan,'' White House press
secretary Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Winding up a five-day visit to India and Bangladesh, Clinton
will fly to Islamabad on Saturday. After meeting with Musharraf,
the president is to make a live television address to the people of
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has labeled South Asia as perhaps the most dangerous
place in the world because of the nuclear arms race between India
and Pakistan and their bitter dispute over the Himalayan territory
of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is concerned that Pakistan, emboldened by its
longtime friendship with the United States, might escalate tensions
with India to the point of conflict -- believing that America and
other world powers would step in and force a settlement of
differences.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like giving a country a security umbrella,'' a senior
administration official said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
''That's not something we're going to do in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   If the United States is seen by Pakistan as a too-willing
peacemaker, ''we increase the possibility of war rather than
decrease the possibility of war,'' the official said at a dinner
meeting with reporters at a resort where Clinton stayed.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. policymakers say Clinton will make clear to Musharraf that
Pakistan cannot count on the United States to bail it out, even
though it was America's ally throughout the Cold War and helped in
the struggle against Soviet forces in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan wants the United States to mediate the Kashmir conflict
but India objects, saying bringing in outside help would reward
terrorism. Clinton has urged Pakistan and India to re-engage on
their own and that there be restraint on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The United States holds out the hope that both Pakistan and
India will sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty this year,
although neither side seems inclined to do so and the U.S. Senate
rejected the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan and India have fought two wars over Kashmir and clashed
again last summer when Pakistan-based fighters seized mountain
peaks inside India. More than 1,000 combatants died before Clinton
persuaded then-Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif to withdraw the forces.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said Clinton would tell Pakistan that the United States
is ''worried about the future of Pakistan.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Pakistan, where the per capita income is $441 a year,
has deep-seated economic and political problems, as well as the
problem of terrorist groups operating out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''And I think that in some way one of the great dangers in this
region is the potential failure of Pakistan,'' Berger said. ''So
the message the president will give in Pakistan is -- you've got to
decide what's important here in terms of your own future.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also said Clinton, particularly in his televised address,
would remind Pakistan of its friendship with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think we can turn our back on the Pakistani people
with whom we've had a very strong relationship,'' Berger said.
''But it's a country that is in trouble and really needs to put all
of its energy into self renewal and not territorial conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   ''They don't have the luxury of that,'' Berger said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 1555 </TRAILER>
