<DOCNO> APW20000323.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three workers injured in a Pennsville chemical plant explosion  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PENNSVILLE, N.J. (AP) -- An early morning explosion at a Salem
County chemical plant injured three workers, including one in
critical condition with burns to his arms and face.
</P>
<P>
   Two workers at Ganes Chemicals Inc., a manufacturer of
pharmaceutical ingredients, were loading an industrial dryer with a
powdery substance wet with solvents shortly after 4 a.m. Thursday
when the machine exploded, said plant manager William Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Whipkey, 42, of Carneys Point, was in critical condition at
Crozier-Chester Medical Center in Chester, Pa., with burns on 25
percent of his body, a hospital spokeswoman said. Davis said the
''flash and heat'' of the explosion burned Whipkey's arms and face.
</P>
<P>
   There was no sustained fire, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gillespie, 37, of Pennsville, suffered minor burns to his
face, Davis said. He was treated at Christiana Hospital in Newark,
Del., and released.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Potter, who was working nearby, was ''knocked off his
feet'' by the impact of the explosion. He initially refused medical
treatment and went home, but then told his wife he had trouble
walking, Davis said. A spokeswoman at Christiana Hospital said the
Smyrna, Del., resident was treated and released.
</P>
<P>
   The company closed the building where the incident occurred for
the day, and ceased all dryer operations until an internal
investigation is complete.
</P>
<P>
   No criminal charges have been filed, said Pennsville Police Lt.
Kelly O'Rourke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
