<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybean Futures Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures fell sharply Thursday
on the Chicago Board of Trade as a storm system moving across the
central United States provided welcome moisture for dry soil.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat prices were hardest hit, the result of heavy rains that
soaked the winter wheat belt before heading east. Lackluster weekly
export sales figures reported by the U.S. Department of Agriculture
also pressured the market.
</P>
<P>
   Corn followed wheat's lead, with the wet weather headed next for
the western corn belt. Sluggishness in weekly export sales
contributed to the decline.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans fell to a two-week low, with the showers due to enter
soybean growing regions Thursday night and expected to continue
into the eastern Midwest this weekend. As with other farm
commodities, soybean export sales figures failed to meet market
expectations, putting additional pressure on prices.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for May delivery fell 5{ cents to $2.56\ a bushel; May
corn fell 4\ cents to $2.30\ a bushel; May oats fell 2\ cents to
$1.19} a bushel; May soybeans fell 9 cents to $5.22 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef and pork futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   April live cattle fell .10 cent to 73.02 cents a pound; May
feeder cattle rose .15 cent to 84.27 cents a pound; April lean hogs
were unchanged at 62.52 cents a pound; May pork bellies rose .18
cent to 88.80 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
