<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Approves Crop Insurance Bill  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER, AP Farm Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hoping to induce more farmers to buy federally
subsidized crop insurance, the Senate overwhelmingly agreed
Thursday to sharply reduce premiums and cover new commodities. The
changes would cost taxpayers $1.5 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to cutting premiums by as much as half on some
policies, legislation that passed 95-5 would offer insurance for
the first time to livestock producers and expand coverage for fruit
and vegetable growers. A House-Senate conference committee will
work out differences between this bill and a similar measure that
passed the House last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department says the legislation could pay for
itself by making farmers less dependent on federal disaster
assistance and other programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Under this legislation, there will be enough incentives for
farmers to participate at high levels that in a future disaster the
need for disaster aid will drop significantly,'' said Ken Ackerman,
administrator of USDA's Risk Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has approved $15 billion in emergency aid over the past
two years to compensate growers for weather-related crop losses and
a slump in commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
   The government already spends $2 billion a year on the insurance
program, which has tripled in size since the early 1990s. But many
farmers, especially in the South and East, say the coverage isn't
worth the cost of the premiums at current subsidy levels. Premiums
average $7 an acre nationwide but vary widely depending on the
crop, location and deductible. About two-thirds of the eligible
acreage nationwide was insured last year.
</P>
<P>
   The policies, which are sold through private companies, can be
purchased to protect farmers from weather-related losses as well as
drops in commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
   ''Crop insurance is obviously an extremely vital part not only
of a safety net to guarantee income, but also as part of an overall
marketing strategy'' for farmers, said Senate Agriculture Committee
Chairman Richard Lugar, R-Ind.
</P>
<P>
   The government now pays 13 percent to 57 percent of a farmer's
premium, depending on the level of coverage. Under the Senate bill,
the government's share on most policies would range from 45 percent
to 60 percent. The House bill would have the government pay 31
percent to 67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Both bills would provide improved coverage for farmers who have
reported a series of crop losses.
</P>
<P>
   A key sticking point in upcoming House-Senate negotiations could
be a $500 million pilot project in the Senate bill that would let
some farmers get a cash payment from the government in lieu of the
subsidized insurance.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, in a letter to
senators this week, said the bill ''represents real progress'' but
raised several concerns about the measure, including a provision
that would reduce USDA's role on a board that oversees the program.
Under the legislation, the chairman must be from the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
   ''Establishing a major government program with a $32 billion
liability for which the taxpayers are ultimately responsible, under
the control of a part-time board not supervised by any government
official who is accountable to the taxpayers, and with a built-in
conflict of interest, disrupts channels of responsibility and
destroys financial and political oversight,'' Glickman wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Senators from the Northeast insisted on setting aside $126
million in the legislation to help farmers in their region get the
insurance. Few farmers in that region now buy the coverage,
including only 8 percent of producers in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is ''going to have to be viewed by people all
across the country as having something that's going to benefit
them,'' said House Agriculture Committee Chairman Larry Combest,
R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Five Republicans voted against the Senate bill: Majority Leader
Trent Lott of Mississippi and Sens. Thad Cochran of Mississippi,
Judd Gregg of New Hampshire, John McCain of Arizona and Jon Kyl of
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 2559.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Risk Management Agency site: http://www.rma.usda.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 1618 </TRAILER>
