<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Kohl Official Alleges Wrongdoing  </HEADLINE>
By BURT HERMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Ex-Chancellor Helmut Kohl was personally involved
in firing a party official in the 1980s who refused to sign a
questionable financial report, the former official told parliament
investigators Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The parliament investigating committee also issued its first
penalties Thursday, levying the maximum $500 fine on two key
figures for refusing to answer questions in the scandal over the
Christian Democrats' anonymous donations, secret accounts and
falsified financial reports.
</P>
<P>
   Ruediger May, former head of the party's financial office, said
that in 1989 he had questioned a $400,000 charge for postal fees
for a letter Kohl sent to all party members.
</P>
<P>
   May said he was given a check from an account he hadn't
previously known about to cover the charge and listed the money
under ''special revenue.'' He said he received the check from Horst
Weyrauch -- the party's longtime financial adviser and a key figure
in the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   When he asked where the money came from, he said he was told:
''You don't have to know everything.''
</P>
<P>
   May said he later refused to sign the party's financial report
and sent a note to party leaders retelling what happened. He was
fired a short time later. He said he was told by the party's
secretary general at that time, Volker Ruehe, that Kohl had ordered
him fired.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl has admitted accepting up to $1 million in anonymous -- and
therefore illegal -- donations during the 1990s. But he has denied
knowledge of the alleged extensive system of slush funds and
off-the-books cash that traded hands in the Christian Democratic
party during his 25 years as its chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl himself has raised almost $3.5 million to cover fines
anticipated for his illegal donations. The party also faces a $20.5
million fine for a falsified 1998 financial report, and could face
more.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers looking into influence-peddling allegations under Kohl
imposed a fine on Weyrauch on Thursday when for a second time he
refused the answer their questions, citing the right against
self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Also fined was Hans Terlinden, a former party office manager in
Bonn. He read a prepared statement to the committee in which he
said that between 1983-98 he had ''several times received money for
the CDU'' from Kohl ''and correctly transferred it further.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not know the source of the money, and could not
discount that he himself had accepted donations for the party. He
said he regretted it if this led to violations of party financing
laws.
</P>
<P>
   He then refused to answer any questions and was fined. The
committee said he also faced possible jail time if he refuses to
testify when called again April 6.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Terlinden and Weyrauch said they would appeal the
fines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 1630 </TRAILER>
