<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Mends Rift Before Election  </HEADLINE>
By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Acting President Vladimir Putin toured Moscow
Thursday with the capital's powerful mayor, a former adversary who
Putin praised in a move to end the longtime rift before elections
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''What has been done in Moscow causes respect,'' Putin told
reporters during a viewing of some of Mayor Yuri Luzhkov's latest
projects. Luzhkov enjoys wide popularity for his efforts to
refurbish the sprawling, often shabby capital.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-election polls have shown Putin with a substantial lead over
the 10 other candidates, but it is unclear whether he has enough
support to nail a first-round victory Sunday. That would require
more than 50 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Mending fences with Luzhkov could increase Putin's chances of
winning without a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov has been locked in a bitter feud with the Kremlin ever
since he was considered a leading presidential candidate. Luzhkov
abandoned his presidential bid after his party was routed in
December's parliamentary elections by a Kremlin-backed party.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov, although initially critical of Putin after he rose to
the presidency upon Boris Yeltsin's Dec. 31 resignation, has since
moderated his opposition. He recently voiced support for Putin and
accompanied the acting president on several official trips.
</P>
<P>
   Putin in turn has praised Luzhkov's leadership and on Thursday
accepted his invitation to discuss Moscow's problems.
</P>
<P>
   The trip went smoothly except for a visit to a subway station
under construction where a blackout left Putin, Luzhkov and their
retinue in pitch darkness and subway workers had to light the scene
with flashlights.
</P>
<P>
   Despite protestations that he is too busy with official duties
to campaign, Putin has proven a tireless and effective campaigner.
</P>
<P>
   He began the week with a sudden trip to Chechnya in a fighter
jet on Monday, then went on a three-day tour along the Volga River,
stopping in several cities and targeting separate interest groups
at each stop.
</P>
<P>
   The trip included stopovers in the republics of Tatarstan and
Bashkortostan, whose streaks of independence have long vexed the
Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Putin claimed victory, saying both republics agreed to
voluntarily end their defiance of the federal law and turn over
more revenues to the federal coffers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The strengthening of the Russian state is an absolute
priority,'' Putin said at a Cabinet session Thursday. ''A single
legal space is essential to make the country attractive for
investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said 983 foreign
observers have arrived to monitor the elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
