<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Minister Questioned  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Police questioned Transport Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai for nine hours Thursday, indicating he might face charges
of sexually assaulting a young worker in his office.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai, head of the small Center Party, was summoned to
police headquarters in Jerusalem and told he was being interrogated
under warning, a term that means that police might recommend
bringing charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the 23-year-old worker, whose name has not been made
public, was brought to police headquarters. Israel radio reported
that police brought them face to face to test their stories.
Mordechai has denied all wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The worker was interrogated extensively after filing the
complaint March 6. Police also questioned other members of
Mordechai's staff.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai took leave from office after police decided to open
the inquiry into the worker's charges. She alleged that on Feb. 25,
Mordechai summoned her to his office, flung her onto a sofa,
slipped his hand under her blouse and fondled her, her lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai, a career army officer before entering politics,
served as defense minister under Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu,
leaving his government to challenge him for the premiership in last
year's election. He dropped out the day before the voting, trailing
in the polls far behind Netanyahu and Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   After Barak won the election, Mordechai led his party into
Barak's coalition government. He was named transport minister and
deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   A decision over whether to indict Mordechai is to be made by the
attorney general after the police finish their investigation.
Mordechai is likely to be interrogated again, Israel radio
reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
