<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stocks Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Retail stocks led a decline in European shares
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks companies in
countries that joined the single currency, ended down 3.10 points
at 443.60. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index was down 9.2 points at
5,259.2 and the Dow Jones Stoxx 50 Index down 10.1 points at
5,060.1.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Sweden's Hennes and Mauritz plunged 30 percent
following the surprise announcement that its chief executive
officer, Fabian Maansson, was resigning and that first-quarter
pretax profit had fallen.
</P>
<P>
   This rocked confidence elsewhere in the retail sector.
</P>
<P>
   Stockholm's General Index ended down 2.1 percent, while the Dow
Jones Stoxx Index of shares in European companies fell 2.33 points,
or 0.6 percent, to 394.00, and the retail subindex underperformed
all others, closing down 5.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among other weak retailers, GUS was down 5.0 percent and
Kingfisher fell 3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fears that the European Central Bank and the Bank of England
will increase rates aggressively in coming weeks, were eased by
weaker-than-expected German producer prices data and a report on
March monthly U.K. trends from the Confederation of British
Industry.
</P>
<P>
   Producer prices in Germany rose 0.2 percent on the month and
were up 2.4 percent on the year in February, against analysts'
expectations of 0.4 percent and 2.6 percent rises, respectively.
Excluding mineral oil prices, the index rose only 0.7 percent on
the year and was flat on the month.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing orders in Britain were weaker in March but the
outlook among producers is more positive than in the first half of
1999, according to the CBI's Industrial Trends survey.
</P>
<P>
   London's FTSE-100 Share Index fell 0.2 percent to 6,594.6.
Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index fell 1.3 percent to 7,694.78, dragged
down by BMW and SAP, while the Paris CAC-40 Index was down 0.2
percent to 6,268.31.
</P>
<P>
   Milan's MIBtel Index fell 0.2 percent to 32,086, Amsterdam's AEX
Index was down 1.1 percent to 671.89 and Belgium's Bel-20 Index was
up 0.6 percent to 2,907.93.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
