<DOCNO> APW20000323.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mixed Reaction to Pope's Message  </HEADLINE>
By RON KAMPEAS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- The extraordinary symbolism of a Roman Catholic
pope paying his respects at Israel's Holocaust memorial moved many
Jews -- although some said John Paul II's words on Thursday fell
short of the apology they had hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   Israel Meir Lau, the Jewish state's chief rabbi, said he had
wanted the pontiff to at least implicitly criticize the wartime
pope, Pius XII, for failing to speak out during the Nazi genocide.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need the condemning of the silence of some during World War
II,'' Lau said, ''not for the victims, not for the survivors even
but for the future, for the young generations to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Efraim Zuroff, head of the Israeli office of the Los
Angeles-based Simon Wiesenthal Center, said the speech ''left a lot
to be desired,'' particularly in blaming what the pope called the
''godless ideology'' of the Nazis for the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   That ''shirked responsibility for the teachings of the Catholic
church, which helped create the conditions which lead to the
Holocaust,'' Zuroff said.
</P>
<P>
   Others Jewish leaders, though, were awed by the sight of the
frail 79-year-old John Paul greeting rabbis and listening intently
as a cantor intoned a prayer for the dead at Yad Vashem. Some
lauded the pope, who has made efforts to reconcile Christians and
Jews throughout his 22-year papacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''It went very far in spirit,'' said Malcolm Hoenlein, the
director of the Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish
Organizations in a phone interview from New York. ''It is something
that would have been unthinkable not long ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Haim Ramon, the government minister who is organizing the
Israeli end of the papal pilgrimage, said the pope's speech was
''another milestone in the relationship between the Catholic Church
and the state of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   At a reception for the pope Thursday, about 30 rabbis rushed
forward to greet him. Black-hatted rabbis mingled with
pink-skullcapped cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ''For many rabbis, it wasn't an easy step to take,'' said Chief
Rabbinate official Daniel Sperber. ''But I think that the mere fact
that the pope came to meet the chief rabbis, rather than the rabbis
coming to the pope, and thus displayed good Christian virtues like
humbleness and meekness, was a very important move.''
</P>
<P>
   John Paul nudged a deeply conservative Vatican into formally
recognizing Israel in 1994. More recently, he has asked God's
pardon for crimes visited upon the Jews by followers of the church.
</P>
<P>
   That, and the speech at Yad Vashem, led many to say that
expecting more from the pope was missing the point.
</P>
<P>
   ''One cannot ask for more,'' said Miriam Papish, a Polish Jew
who lost her whole family in the death camps. She watched the pope
in her tiny pensioner's apartment overlooking Jerusalem's gray,
sculpted hills, a box of tissues within handy reach. ''He has
already done so much by coming here, to Yad Vashem.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Eric Yoffie -- head of the Union of American Hebrew
Congregations, Reform Judaism's synagogue grouping -- had mixed
feelings. On the one hand, he said, ''if every step forward is
greeted with an attack, there is little incentive for additional
steps to be taken.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said he ''simply cannot understand the
failure of the pope to speak out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 1700 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
