Nasdaq Composite Index:       4,940.69  + 75.94
Gold(final) -    $284.90    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment Rises by 4,000
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- New claims for unemployment benefits ticked up
last week but were still in a range economists said indicated
employers are having trouble finding qualified workers. The Labor
Department said today that the number of Americans filing new
claims for unemployment benefits rose by 4,000 to 266,000 for the
week ending March 18. That was a smaller increase than many
analysts were expecting. Meanwhile, the more stable four-week
moving average of claims, which smoothes out week-to-week
volatility, fell slightly last week to 271,000, the lowest level
since Dec. 15, 1973, when such claims were at 256,750.
</P>
<P>
   Govt. Open To Microsoft Punishment
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department appears to be
retreating from demands in secret negotiations to break up the
Microsoft Corp., a concession that would dramatically improve
chances for settling the landmark antitrust case. Microsoft has
indicated it will not accept any settlement that divides the
company, and U.S. Assistant Attorney General Joel I. Klein believes
such a punishment may not be necessary to adequately restrain what
the trial judge characterized as Microsoft's monopoly power over
the technology industry, said two people close to the case,
speaking on condition of anonymity. Shares of Microsoft were at
111~, up 8|.
</P>
<P>
   EU Extends Vodafone Probe Deadline
</P>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Commission extended the
deadline for a decision in its antitrust probe into Vodafone
Airtouch PLC's planned takeover of Germany's Mannesmann AG by about
a week until April 11 or 12. The deal, valued at $180 billion when
it was announced in February, would be the biggest corporate merger
to date. The extension from the previous April 4 deadline gives the
European Union executive body more time to look into ''new
undertakings'' from the companies, Commission spokesman Michael
Tscherny said today. He declined to give details, but said they
concerned British mobile phone company Orange PLC, which is owned
by Mannesmann. Vodafone is Britain's largest mobile phone company
and Orange is the third biggest, so combining them may violate both
EU and British antitrust rules.
</P>
<P>
   GM Reducing Some Saturn Models
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. says it will reduce
production of the Saturn L-series sedans and wagons through the end
of May due to sluggish sales. The Wilmington, Del., plant where GM
builds the midsize sedans will begin idling one of its two shifts
on March 27 through May 30. GM said today it will alternate idling
the first or second shift every week. The 1,200 workers at the
plant will receive their normal pay while they're not working.
Saturn spokeswoman Sue Mallino declined to give an estimate of
exactly how much production would be cut. The plant is capable of
building 200,000 vehicles a year; Saturn has sold 10,643 L-series
sedans and wagons through February.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Beats Estimates
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co., the nation's
second-largest retail broker, reported earnings of $1.54 billion
for its first fiscal quarter, well above analysts' expectations.
Morgan Stanley's net income, which translates to $1.34 a share,
compared with $1.04 billion, or 88 cents a share, a year earlier.
Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial had estimated
that the New York-based securities firm and investment bank would
earn $1.06 a share in the quarter, which ended Feb. 29. Revenue was
$7.41 billion, up 39 percent from $5.34 billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Bausch &AMP; Lomb Eyes Wesley Jessen
</P>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Bausch &AMP; Lomb Inc. offered today to buy
Illinois-based Wesley Jessen VisionCare Inc. for about $600 million
to gain ground in the color contact lens market. The $34-a-share
bid could thwart Wesley Jessen's planned acquisition of Ocular
Sciences Inc., a rival contact lens maker in San Francisco. Wesley
Jessen of Des Plaines, Ill., said Monday it had agreed to buy
Ocular Sciences for about $18 a share, or $413 million. Bausch &AMP;
Lomb said it was interested only in buying Wesley Jessen and not
Ocular Sciences. Its proposed merger would expand Bausch &AMP; Lomb's
contact lens revenues of $488 million in 1999 by more than $300
million. Shares of Bausch &AMP; Lomb were at 55 5/10, down }.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerages Settle Harassment Suit
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Two Wall Street brokerage firms where sexual
harassment was said to be so pervasive that a prosecutor compared
it to ''Animal House'' have settled a $10 million lawsuit brought
by the state. Under the agreement announced today by state Attorney
General Eliot Spitzer, harassed female workers and minority
employees subjected to sexual or racial epithets are eligible for a
financial settlement from Garban LLC and its affiliated firm,
Garvin Guy Butler. The deal allows female and minority workers who
were at the firm between September 1996 and September 1998 to seek
damages, regardless of the statute of limitations. Dozens of
current and former firm employees are eligible, Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   FedEx Net Income Increases 45 Pct.
</P>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- FedEx Corp. reported its third-quarter
earnings rose 45 percent although soaring fuel costs raised its
expenses by more than $100 million. The overnight delivery company
said today its net income came to $113 million, or 39 cents per
share, for the quarter ended Feb. 29, compared to $78 million, or
26 cents per share, in the same period a year ago. The results beat
the 34 cents per share in operating earnings forecast by analysts
surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial. Revenue came to $4.5
billion, up 10 percent from $4.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, H&AMP;R Block Forge Alliance
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. is abandoning its own foray into
the tax preparation software market in favor of an alliance with
H&AMP;R Block Corp. aimed at developing Internet and desktop tax
preparation products. In announcing the move today, Microsoft said
it will drop development of its proprietary tax preparation
software, TaxSaver. Under the terms of the agreement, customers who
use Microsoft's financial Web site, MSN MoneyCentral, will be able
to download H&AMP;R Block's tax preparation software, TaxCut. The site
also will provide links to H&AMP;R Block's online tax site.
</P>
