<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 253.16; Nasdaq Up 75.86  </HEADLINE>
By SETH SUTEL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks advanced broadly Thursday, carrying the
Dow Jones industrial average over 11,000 for the first time in
seven weeks, as a rally in high-tech issues spread throughout Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft set the pace early on, rising sharply after The Wall
Street Journal reported the software maker was moving closer toward
resolving a government antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   The advance, which also drove the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
into record territory for the third straight day, cemented a
stunning comeback for the Dow, which has gained 1,300 points since
closing at just above 9,800 on March 14.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow rose 253.16 Thursday to 11,119.86, its first close above
11,000 since Feb. 3. The blue chip index is still 5.1 percent below
its closing high of 11,722.98, reached Jan. 14.
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech dominated Nasdaq composite index rose 75.86 to
4,940.61, while the S&AMP;P 500, which surpassed 1,500 for the first
time on Wednesday, gained another 26.71 to 1,527.35.
</P>
<P>
   The rally lifted industrial blue chips as fund managers
scrambled to put their cash to work before the first quarter closes
a week from Friday. Aluminum maker Alcoa rose 2| to 69{, and
International Paper rose 1~ to 39[. Both are components of the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been a very strong quarter in terms of tech stocks as
well as flows into mutual funds, so there's a lot of pressure on
fund managers to be fully invested by the end of the quarter,''
said Ricky Harrington, technical analyst at Wachovia Securities in
Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The real stars of the day were the major high-tech shares,
following the example set by Microsoft, which jumped 8| to 111~.
Network equipment maker Cisco Systems gained 5| to 77 13/16, and
Oracle, a major business software company, was up 2 13/16 to 86~.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the tech sector fared as well, however. Compaq
tumbled 2| to 29| on rumors the computer maker would report poor
first-quarter earnings, and chip maker Intel slipped 1 7/16 to 142|
as investors collected profits from the stunning 75 percent gain
the stock has enjoyed since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the rally in tech stocks was strong enough to lift other
parts of the market, which several analysts interpreted as a
positive sign after several weeks of sharp gains largely limited to
sensitive sectors such as biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of people are encouraged by the broadening-out
process,'' said William Meehan, chief market analyst for Cantor
Fitzgerald. ''We've had huge movement in a number of assets.''
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining issues by an 8 to-5
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 1.06
billion shares as of 4 p.m., vs. 1.07 billion the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   A sharp rally in the bond market also made its presence felt on
Wall Street. With fewer places to put their money and long-term
bond yields having fallen in recent weeks, fund managers were
looking again at stocks to buy in order to put their cash to work
by the end of the quarter. The long bond was yielding 5.91 percent
in late afternoon trading, down from 5.96 percent late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The runup in the Treasury market was all the more remarkable
since it came on the heels of Tuesday's rate increase by the
Federal Reserve. The Fed, which has raised rates five times since
June, has indicated it may make further increases this year, but
bond traders appear unfazed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bond market is out of control,'' said Harrington.
''Despite what the Fed has done so far, there's still so much money
out there. Momentum and money flow are driving this market.''
</P>
<P>
   Gains in shares of smaller companies were not as large as in the
broader market. The Russell 2000 index rose 2.60 to 573.79.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.2 percent.
Germany's Xetra DAX index was down 1.3 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100
was down 0.2 percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
