<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'woman.life.song' Premieres in N.Y.  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- It was some birthday gift: Singer Jessye Norman
and writers Maya Angelou, Toni Morrison and Clarissa Pinkola Estes,
all wrapped in music on the stage of Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   They delivered the world premiere Wednesday of composer Judith
Weir's ''woman.life.song'' -- commissioned by Wall Street takeover
king Henry Kravis to celebrate his wife's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The years are broken across my body like thin crystals,''
Angelou said in a husky, soothing voice, reading from the series of
songs that follow the stages of a woman's life.
</P>
<P>
   The texts of the 50-minute piece were first read by their three
creators, who sat side-by-side onstage. Norman, who conceived of
the project, then sang them, accompanied by the Orchestra of St.
Luke's.
</P>
<P>
   ''To the mother, the lover, who made thunder under the sheets,''
she sang in the words of Estes, a psychoanalyst who describes her
dying mother with hypnotic rhythms. Estes is a ''cantadora,'' a
keeper of old stories in her Latin oral tradition, as reflected in
her best-selling book ''Women Who Run with the Wolves.''
</P>
<P>
   As she stood reading and facing the audience, her empty chair
became a tiny stage that summed up the evening: Morrison's and
Angelou's hands suddenly linked across the seat, clasping under the
spotlights. The gesture united two grande dames of American letters
who had risen above their shared struggle, as minority women in a
race-troubled society.
</P>
<P>
   In ''woman.life.song,'' the three lyricists paint a woman's
progression from youth to age with words both shattering and funny.
</P>
<P>
   ''Breasts!! Song of the Innocent Wild-Child'' is Estes' teasing
fantasy about a girl blossoming into womanhood, set to
Spanish-style music: ''Oh, Breasts!! If I had breasts I would wear
them/ ever so smartly. I would use them to proudly point with, or
flash them in disdain, or lift them up in joy -- but I would never
flaunt them, nor stuff them, and especially, never fluff them...''
</P>
<P>
   Angelou wrote texts for the beginning and end of the piece
called ''On Youth'' and ''On Maturity.''
</P>
<P>
   A nostalgic, Southern tone suffused her reading of the first -- a
child's memory of being poor with a grandmother roasting peanuts in
the oven, ''and as the air became perfumed with the friendly aroma
of roasting nuts and my uncle ... began to hum the old songs of the
spirit: the aroma of the nuts, the sound -- the heavy silk sound of
the ancient spirituals, a glass of cold milk in my hand, my young
body -- obedient to my will -- made me rich beyond measure.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman performed those words as a larger-than-life declamation.
With her resplendent soprano, she gave a powerhouse performance
that also could be as delicate as a whisper.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison, the only black American woman to win a Nobel Prize in
literature, has her own take on a woman's youth. Norman's soaring
high notes were tense with expectation in Morrison's ''Edge,'' in
which an infatuated young woman is ''racing to the edge of love/
the bed of love/ the love-me-till-I'm-dead of love.''
</P>
<P>
   Weir's composition didn't always measure up.
</P>
<P>
   Though the texts are universal, they emanate an American spirit
that was learned -- and earned -- through the hardships of these
minority women. The music, while intricately crafted and executed,
at times sounded removed from that human landscape. The English
composer attempted to give Estes' lyrics an exotic touch, adding a
guitar to the orchestration, but the strummed lilt drew the
listener more into a Spanish mode than Estes' Mexican-American.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was an intriguing evening that ended with a touch of
humor.
</P>
<P>
   For a final bow, Morrison wore her winter coat with a purse
hanging over the shoulder -- ready to leave. She apparently hadn't
expected such a long accolade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 1735 </TRAILER>
