<HEADLINE> Indian Media Sizes Up Clinton  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Sizing up the significance of President
Clinton's visit, Indian newspapers said he's impressed the
country's legislators and people but what that means in the long
run is not clear.
</P>
<P>
   ''After euphoria, it's time for reality check,'' said The Times
of India on its front page.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clinton wraps hard message in soft words,'' The Statesman said
of the president's speech to members of Parliament earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
   R.K. Laxman, India's most popular political cartoonist, showed
Clinton lecturing on his ''grand vision'' to bring peace by
encouraging India to hold talks with Pakistan, even as missiles fly
and terrorists sneak across the border.
</P>
<P>
   ''Smart guy! Fantastic solution! It never occurred to us,'' says
a lawmaker depicted in the cartoon, in The Times.
</P>
<P>
   Indian Express said Clinton had tread carefully on issues such
as India's nuclear weapons capability and its dispute with Pakistan
over Kashmir. Clinton, who meets Pakistani officials Saturday, made
little headway in urging India's leaders to open a dialogue with
Pakistan and to slow its nuclear weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   ''Perhaps there is no point in India being so sensitive on
issues that are not purely regional, for in this age, no issue is
local,'' the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   Another paper, The Hindu, said India should resist any
temptation to use the United States as a mediator in its
territorial dispute with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   ''The relationship with the United States, which is a promising
and potentially multifaceted one, should not be held hostage to
India's regional stakes,'' it said in an editorial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
