<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Welcomes Rail Merger Halt  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE MITTELSTADT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senators welcomed the decision by federal
regulators to temporarily halt mergers in the rapidly consolidating
railroad industry, saying Thursday the deals are hurting
competition and service.
</P>
<P>
   ''As the railroads have become larger, the mergers have become
more complex and difficult,'' Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott
said at a hearing of the Senate Commerce subcommittee on surface
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the short term, it appears to me that it has drained
financial resources from the railroads and ... eroded service gains
and efficiencies at various points,'' said Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Surface Transportation Board last week ordered a
15-month moratorium on railroad mergers, effectively halting a
planned $6 billion deal between Texas-based Burlington Northern
Santa Fe and Canadian National Railway.
</P>
<P>
   The board acted after a four-day hearing on the future of the
railroad industry, which has been beset by service disruptions
since the 1996 Union Pacific-Southern Pacific merger and last
year's takeover of Conrail by CSX and Norfolk Southern.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Rockefeller, D-W.Va., said the order was an
''extraordinarily bold decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Burlington Northern and Canadian National have petitioned the
board to lift the freeze and are turning to federal court to try to
block the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Burlington Northern's chairman, Robert Krebs, in a written
statement submitted to the Senate subcommittee, said the board's
decision was ''illegal'' and that his railroad and would-be partner
should not be punished for previous mergers' failings.
</P>
<P>
   The board chairwoman, Linda Morgan, told senators that the board
had the authority to impose the freeze while regulators develop new
rules for what she said may be the industry's final round of
mergers.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are those who argue that what we did by suspending
merger activity was extreme and unnecessary,'' Morgan said. ''The
board's action was unprecedented, but bold action was necessary
given the extraordinary circumstances presented to the board.''
</P>
<P>
   The board believes ''the risk of creating more instability in an
already unstable rail sector was too great,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While applauding the board's action, senators also faulted
Congress for not giving the agency more guidance. Lawmakers have
not been able to agree on reauthorizing the agency.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee chairwoman, Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, said the
moratorium should prod Congress to act and grant the agency new
powers to weigh mergers' effect on competition.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe very strongly that Congress has a role to play here.
Sitting on the sidelines simply will not do while we witness the
rapid integration of the rail industry,'' said Hutchison, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledged the difficulty of enacting legislation that
fosters competition and protects shippers' rights while restoring
the railroad industry to financial health. Her own reauthorization
bill -- one of several in Congress -- is viewed by some as an attempt
to re-regulate an industry that was deregulated two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison rejected that criticism. ''My purpose is the opposite.
It's to keep competition in the industry and to avoid monopolies
from occurring that would put our shippers in a worse position,''
she said after the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Lott urged caution.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the situation will sort itself out as the railroads
digest the previous mergers,'' he said. ''We need to be careful
about rushing a legislative solution to what can probably be
handled by the industry itself and by the efforts of the (STB).''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The board's Web site: http://www.stb.dot.gov
</P>
<P>
   Burlington Northern's Web site: http://www.bnsf.com
</P>
<P>
   Canadian National's Web site: http://www.cn.ca
</P>
</TEXT>
