<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Star quintet offers Carnegie Hall world premiere of'woman.life.song'  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- It was some birthday gift: Singer Jessye Norman
and writers Maya Angelou, Toni Morrison and Clarissa Pinkola Estes
-- wrapped in music on the stage of Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, they delivered the world premiere of composer
Judith Weir's ''woman.life.song'' -- commissioned by Wall Street
takeover king Henry Kravis to celebrate his wife's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The years are broken across my body like thin crystals,''
Angelou said in a husky, soothing voice, reading from the series of
songs that follow the stages of a woman's life.
</P>
<P>
   The texts of the 50-minute piece were first read by their three
creators, who sat side-by-side onstage. Norman, who conceived of
the woman-as-theme project, then performed the work, accompanied by
the Orchestra of St. Luke's.
</P>
<P>
   ''To the mother, the lover, who made thunder under the sheets,''
she sang in the words of Estes, a psychoanalyst who paints a
picture of her dying mother with hypnotic rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   Estes is a ''cantadora,'' a keeper of old stories in her Latin
oral tradition, reflected in her best-selling book ''Women Who Run
with the Wolves.''
</P>
<P>
   As she stood facing the audience while reading, her empty chair
became a tiny stage that summed up the evening: Morrison's and
Angelou's hands suddenly linked across the seat, clasping under the
spotlights.
</P>
<P>
   Center stage at Carnegie Hall, the gesture united two grande
dames of American letters who had risen above their shared
struggle, as minority women in a race-troubled society.
</P>
<P>
   In ''woman.life.song,'' the three lyricists paint a woman's
progression from youth to age with words both shattering and funny.
</P>
<P>
   ''Breasts!! Song of the Innocent Wild-Child'' is Estes' teasing
fantasy about a girl blossoming into womanhood, set to
Spanish-style music: ''Oh, Breasts!! If I had breasts I would wear
them/ ever so smartly. I would use them to proudly point with, or
flash them in disdain, or lift them up in joy-- but I would never
flaunt them, nor stuff them, and especially, never fluff them...''
</P>
<P>
   Angelou framed the beginning and end of the piece, writing texts
called ''On Youth'' and ''On Maturity.''
</P>
<P>
   A nostalgic, Southern caress suffused her reading of the first --
a child's memory of being poor, alongside a grandmother who is
roasting peanuts in the oven, ''and as the air became perfumed with
the friendly aroma of roasting nuts and my uncle ... began to hum
the old songs of the spirit: the aroma of the nuts, the sound -- the
heavy silk sound of the ancient spirituals, a glass of cold milk in
my hand, my young body -- obedient to my will -- made me rich beyond
measure.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman performed the same words as a larger-than-life
declamation. With her resplendent soprano voice, she gave a
powerhouse performance that also could be as delicate as a whisper.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison, the only African-American woman to win a Nobel Prize
in literature, has her own take on a woman's youth. Norman's
soaring high notes were tense with expectation for ''Edge,'' in
which an infatuated young woman is ''racing to the edge of love/
the bed of love/ the love-me-till-I'm-dead of love.''
</P>
<P>
   Weir's composition didn't always measure up.
</P>
<P>
   Though the texts are universal, they emanate an American spirit
that was learned -- and earned -- through the hardships of these
minority women.
</P>
<P>
   The music, while intricately crafted and executed, at times
sounded far-removed from that human landscape. The English composer
attempted to give Estes' lyrics an exotic touch, adding a guitar to
the orchestration; but the strummed lilt drew the listener more
into a Spanish mode rather than Estes' Mexican-American one.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was an intriguing evening that ended with a touch of
humor.
</P>
<P>
   For a final bow, Morrison wore her winter coat with a purse
hanging over the shoulder -- ready to leave. She apparently hadn't
expected such a long accolade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
