<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Mexico Vulnerable to Outages  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD BENKE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Unusually dry weather and too few
electrical transmission lines led to New Mexico's largest-ever
power outage -- and utility officials warn that conditions are right
for it to happen again.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't lie to you -- the system is somewhat vulnerable,'' said
Don Brown, spokesman for Public Service Company of New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, a grass fire -- possibly caused by a tossed
cigarette -- sent thick smoke rising up 60-foot transmission towers.
The electricity-conducting smoke triggered a short-circuit that
shut down all three transmission lines feeding Albuquerque, the
state's largest metropolitan area with 500,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Power also was lost to towns along the Rio Grande, from El Paso,
Texas, to Taos, N.M., and as far west as Gallup, N.M. In all, 1.6
million people were affected, some for up to six hours.
</P>
<P>
   Brown blamed a shortage of power lines in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the main lines stretch side by side along the same
transmission path. When those lines automatically switched off
because of the short-circuit, the third line overloaded and shut
down in a domino effect.
</P>
<P>
   Power company officials maintain that the state needs to build
alternative paths for electricity in case of fire.
</P>
<P>
   But winning public acceptance for new transmission lines has
been a struggle, Brown said. His company has tried for 15 years to
convince New Mexicans of the need, but residents have considered
them an eyesore.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the state remains unusually dry and vulnerable to
fire, with rainfall this season at half its normal rate.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, 187,289 acres of New Mexico have burned,
compared with a little more than 52,000 for all of last year. Dry
weather is forecast through June.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the rest of the West is dry this year, too, but New
Mexico is particularly vulnerable to major outages because many
other Western states have a larger web of transmission lines that
enables utilities to route power around fires.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
