<HEADLINE> Clinton-Assad Talk Gauged Cautiously  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT, AP White House Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAIPUR, India (AP) -- President Clinton's meeting with Syrian
President Hafez Assad is unlikely to produce a timetable for
resuming peace talks with Israel but should provide a sense of
whether a new round of negotiations could result in a settlement, a
senior official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, ending a six-day trip to South Asia, will fly to Geneva
to meet with Assad on Sunday in hopes of restarting Israeli-Syrian
talks that broke off in stalemate in early January.
</P>
<P>
   ''The best case result ... is that we have a sense after the
meeting that there is enough common ground, they're close enough,
that if we actually resume negotiations that you could envision
them ending in success,'' said Sandy Berger, Clinton's national
security adviser, accompanying the president at a resort here.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials say they believe that Assad wants a peace
agreement with Israel but that there is no guarantee the two sides
can strike a deal. Clinton hopes to bolster Syria's and Israeli's
confidence that both sides' needs can be met.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the administration has been playing down expectations of
Sunday's meeting, saying there will be no immediate results. The
expectation is that Assad will return to Syria and Clinton will
brief Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the president also is to see Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Assad meeting, a senior administration official
said, ''We won't know the outcome, impact of the meeting, for a few
weeks.'' The official, insisting on anonymity, left open the
possibility that ''they're just too far apart and there's no point
in re-engaging.''
</P>
<P>
   A key issue is the extent of Israel's withdrawal from the Golan
Heights, captured in the 1967 Mideast War, and the line to which
Israel pulls back. Another problem is how Israel will make up for
the security advantage it had on the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   A third factor involves what specific pledges Syria would make
in promising peace with Israel. Barak is committed to submitting
any peace deal to a vote in Israel and will have to overcome doubts
about Assad's commitment. ''Israelis want a lot of up-front
manifestations of normalcy,'' the senior official said. Another
factor is the timing and sequence of Israel's withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Another track of Mideast negotiations is under way in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Palestinian negotiators held a third day of talks at
Bolling Air Force Base on Thursday. Neither they nor their U.S.
hosts said anything about the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   On the table are Palestinian demands for a state and for part of
Jerusalem as their capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
