<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Elects Koehler As New Chief  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER, AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The International Monetary Fund unanimously
elected Germany's Horst Koehler as its new managing director on
Thursday, while the drive to impose radical reforms on the
182-nation lending agency gained momentum in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Koehler, 57, ratified Thursday by the IMF's
24-member executive committee, came only after a bruising
four-month global power struggle which saw the United States
publicly reject Europe's first candidate for the job.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference last week, Koehler said he was ''open to
discussion and dialogue with the U.S. Congress about reforms'' and
pledged to focus the IMF on one of its main missions, preventing
global financial crises from breaking out.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler, a former top official in Germany's finance ministry and
since 1998 the head of the London-based European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development, was put forward by German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder after President Clinton rejected
Germany's first candidate as lacking sufficient stature for the
job.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF, which took the lead in assembling more than $100
billion in rescue packages during the global financial crisis in
1997-98, has emerged as one of the most powerful financial
institutions in the world. But a host of critics on both the right
and left charge that the IMF is too powerful and secretive.
</P>
<P>
   Various members of the House Banking Committee said Thursday
that the institution must accelerate its efforts to implement
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ''The IMF is in desperate need of structural adjustment. It must
become more accountable,'' said Rep. Bernie Sanders of Vermont. He
said the secretive selection process for Koehler highlighted how
much reform was needed.
</P>
<P>
   The committee heard from members of a congressionally appointed
commission headed by Allan Meltzer, an economist at Carnegie Mellon
University, that recommended a radical downsizing of both the IMF
and its sister lending agency, the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The Meltzer panel said the IMF should be restricted to offering
short-term loans to countries facing financial crisis and get out
of the business of long-term lending. It said the World Bank should
switch from offering loans, which increase the debt of poor
nations, and instead provide grants with more emphasis on such
problems as AIDs.
</P>
<P>
   The Meltzer report, released earlier this month, has won strong
backing from top Republican leaders in Congress, who have vowed to
attach the recommendations to an administration request to reduce
the debt burdens of the world's 40 poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, however, urged the banking
committee to adopt a less sweeping set of administration reform
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   He said adhering to the commission's proposals would have
prevented the IMF from providing critically needed loans to Mexico,
Brazil or South Korea as the battled recent financial crises.
</P>
<P>
   Summers was pressed by some members of the Banking Committee to
defend the IMF's handling of a recently disclosed incident in which
Ukraine's central bank, according to the IMF, engaged in a number
of questionable transactions worth almost $1 billion to generate a
falsely optimistic picture of the country's foreign currency
reserves between 1996 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Summers said the administration was ''deeply concerned'' about
the incident and in particular the fact that IMF staff did not
disclose until recently to its executive board information the
staff had uncovered in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate appearance before the panel, James Healy, the
global head of emerging markets for Credit Suisse First Boston,
said his financial institution had no way of knowing whether the
banking transactions it handled for the Ukrainian central bank
breached agreements the country had with the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not know of any misuse of IMF funds,'' Healy told the
panel.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: International Monetary Fund site: http://www.imf.org
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Department site: http://www.ustreas.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
