<HEADLINE> McCain Won't Back FEC Nominee  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Back in the Senate less than a week, John
McCain is also back to making his point that campaign finance rules
need an overhaul. Democrat Al Gore says George W. Bush ought to
follow his Republican colleague's lead.
</P>
<P>
   McCain says he will vote against the confirmation of Republican
Bradley Smith, a Federal Election Commission nominee who opposes
campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the likely Democratic presidential nominee who also
opposes Smith, said in Cincinnati on Thursday, ''I'd like to call
upon Governor Bush to take that same courageous position because
this nominee wants to dismantle all existing campaign finance
laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush defeated McCain in the battle for the Republican
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's comments came as he met Wednesday with his old campaign
finance partner, Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., about new
legislation to fight big money politics.
</P>
<P>
   McCain told reporters he would do everything he could to defeat
Smith on the grounds that he is against tightening fund-raising
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is strongly backed by senior Senate Republicans including
Majority Leader Trent Lott and Mitch McConnell of Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   McCain spokesman Mark Buse said his boss has not procedurally
blocked Smith's confirmation but will vote against any move to
break a Democratic filibuster and bring the matter to a final vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator's opposition indicates that his defeat on
the campaign trail did little to temper his independent streak.
</P>
<P>
   It sets up another confrontation with McConnell, who put McCain
on the defensive on the Senate floor last year by asking him to
name the colleagues that McCain felt had been ''corrupted'' by the
system, and how.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've all been corrupted,'' McCain responded, and he repeated
that phrase in the presidential campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
