<HEADLINE> Presidential Campaign Poll  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Some results from a poll by the Pew Research Center
for the
People &AMP; the Press on the presidential race. When results don't
total 100 percent, the remainder either didn't know or refused to
answer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suppose the 2000 presidential election were being held today and
the candidates were Al Gore, the Democrat, and George W. Bush, the
Republican. Who would you vote for?
</P>
<P>
   -- Al Gore, 49 percent
</P>
<P>
   -- George W. Bush, 43 percent
</P>
<P>
   (Bush led in December by double digits, while recent polls have
shown the two candidates close, with Bush having an edge in some
and Gore in others.)
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who you support, which one of the presidential
candidates -- Al Gore or George W. Bush -- do you think would do the
best job of:
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the economy strong
</P>
<P>
   -- Gore, 44 percent
</P>
<P>
   -- Bush, 43 percent
</P>
<P>
   Making wise decisions about foreign policy
</P>
<P>
   -- Gore, 41 percent
</P>
<P>
   -- Bush, 37 percent
</P>
<P>
   Keeping Social Security and Medicare financially sound
</P>
<P>
   -- Gore 47 percent
</P>
<P>
   -- Bush, 36 percent
</P>
<P>
   Representing your views on gun control
</P>
<P>
   -- Gore, 41 percent
</P>
<P>
   -- Bush, 37 percent
</P>
<P>
   Improving conditions for minority groups
</P>
<P>
   -- Gore, 55 percent
</P>
<P>
   -- Bush, 28 percent
</P>
<P>
   Improving the health care system
</P>
<P>
   -- Gore, 49 percent
</P>
<P>
   -- Bush, 33 percent
</P>
<P>
   Protecting and strengthening families
</P>
<P>
   -- Gore, 43 percent
</P>
<P>
   -- Bush, 37 percent
</P>
<P>
   Improving education
</P>
<P>
   -- Bush, 44 percent
</P>
<P>
   -- Gore, 41 percent
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 912 registered voters was taken March 15-19 and has
an error margin of plus or minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
