<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Vs. Yen, Down Vs. Euro  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The euro gained on the dollar, though both
currencies jumped against the yen on Thursday after the latest in a
series of interest rate hikes by Western central banks that have
made Japanese investment returns less competitive.
</P>
<P>
   In late trading in New York, the dollar was quoted at 107.32
Japanese yen, up from 106.90 yen at the same point on Wednesday,
while the euro rose to 97.19 cents compared with the prior day's
quote of 96.02 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank of Switzerland set the tone early in the day
with a surprisingly sharp increase in its short-term lending rates.
</P>
<P>
   The inflation-fighting measure followed rate hikes on Tuesday by
the U.S. Federal Reserve and last week by the European Central Bank
that have made dollar- and euro-denominated investments more
appealing.
</P>
<P>
   In other trading Thursday, the dollar was quoted at 1.6465 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6756; and 1.4697 Canadian dollars, down from
1.4700. The British pound rose to $1.5863 from late Wednesday's
quote of $1.5775.
</P>
<P>
   The currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are
no longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed
rate. Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 2.0121
German marks, down from 2.0370 on Tuesday; 6.7496 French francs,
down from 6.8318; and 1,991.95 Italian lire, down from 2,016.63.
</P>
</TEXT>
