<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Back $1.6B Aid for Colombia  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A panel of experts urged Congress on Thursday
to quickly approve a proposed $1.6 billion counter-drug aid package
for Colombia, saying that such support ''would signal a strong U.S.
commitment to help a troubled country at a critical moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation was contained in an interim report by an
independent task force sponsored by the Council on Foreign
Relations and the Inter-American Dialogue. The co-chairmen for the
project were Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., and former National Security
adviser Brent Scowcroft.
</P>
<P>
   While giving its backing to the aid proposal, the report said
that over the longer term the administration and the Congress
should give higher priority to supporting Colombian efforts to
remedy its social, economic and institutional problems.
</P>
<P>
   It said future legislation ''should focus more broadly, going
beyond drug fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   The title of the report -- ''First Steps Toward a Constructive
U.S. Policy in Colombia'' -- underscored the authors' view that
success in Colombia is a long-term proposition.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 11, President Clinton asked Congress for a $950 million
emergency supplemental appropriation this year and a total of $1.6
billion through fiscal year 2001. Among other items, the package
calls for 63 helicopters for counter-drug activities. Colombia is
the source of 80 percent of the cocaine and 60 percent of the
heroin used in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the proposal responds to an emergency situation,
expresses a strong U.S. commitment to Colombia and complements
important elements of a comprehensive $7.5 billion three-year plan
announced last summer by President Andres Pastrana. More than half
of that amount would be generated in Colombia itself.
</P>
<P>
   The panel recommended amendments to bolster a regional approach
to the drug problem, calling for additional resources for Bolivia
and Peru to help their successful counter-narcotics efforts.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it also urged an extension for an additional year
of trade preferences given to Andean countries and for the
inclusion of the same countries in pending legislation to grant
trade benefits to Caribbean nations.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-page report was designed to influence the debate in
Congress on the aid package. A final report will be published in
June.
</P>
<P>
   The report was released amid uncertainty over the fate of the
administration's proposal. The House could take up the legislation
next week but there are no assurances of majority support. In the
Senate, there may be no vote until later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Colombia request is part of a $9 billion bill that also
includes money for operations in Kosovo. The package has run into
opposition from some fiscal conservatives who believe the price tag
is too high and from liberals who are worried the United States
could become ensnared in Colombia's civil war or who believe
efforts to curb drug flows are doomed to fail.
</P>
<P>
   But backers of the package see grave dangers for the United
States in both Colombia and Kosovo if it is not acted on quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen wrote Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss., and House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.,
urging quick passage. If the Kosovo peackeeping money is not
available by this summer, Cohen said, the U.S. military will have
to make ''irreversible decisions'' to curtail spending on important
training and maintenance -- moves that would hurt troop readiness
and morale.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the Army faces the tightest pinch; it will have to
cancel exercises at its National Training Center and put off
promotions if the Kosovo money is not available by late April.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sens. Paul Coverdell of Georgia and Mike DeWine of
Ohio said the bill is vital for Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ''The longer we wait to address the crisis, the greater the
costs will be,'' they said. ''The requested assistance, designed to
curb the devastating effects of narcotics trafficking, is clearly
in our national interest. Too much is at stake not to take action
immediately.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 1828 </TRAILER>
