<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forest Service Fee Hikes Protested  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN HUGHES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- David Mead's patch of paradise is a rustic
cabin his family built 25 years ago atop a steep slope in the
Sawtooth National Forest in Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   For years the vacation home came at a bargain price -- just $390
a year for the half-acre lot. That changed in 1996, when a new
appraisal hiked Mead's fee to $2,500, although a second appraisal
brought it down to $1,750.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the fees are bringing howls of protest from many of the
15,200 cabin owners on Forest Service land in 25 states. They are
backing bills that would overhaul the Forest Service appraisal
system and keep the fees roughly where they were before the new
appraisals began.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of our cabin owners have already bailed out,'' Mead told
a House subcommittee Thursday. ''The 'cash cow' appraisal
objectives that appear to drive the Forest Service are now driving
retired people and average income families out of the forests.''
</P>
<P>
   But Forest Service officials say changes were needed in their
20-year-old appraisals, which had fallen out of line with market
realities. Bills backed by the cabin owners would essentially wipe
out the additional $10 million the agency expects to collect each
year under the new appraisals, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The use of national forest land for private recreation
residences is a privilege afforded to a relatively few number of
persons,'' said Paul Brouha, a Forest Service associate deputy
chief. ''Taxpayers should be adequately compensated for this
private use of their public lands.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service since 1915 has allowed Americans to build and
use cabins on forest lands for an annual fee, although the number
of cabins on forest lands has been declining in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The agency in 1988 adopted a new regulation on appraising the
land used by cabin owners and in 1996 launched a five-year effort
to reappraise the tracts.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly two-thirds of the new appraisals complete, four in
10 cabin owners would see their fees at least double, an average
increase of $1,110.
</P>
<P>
   Another 3 percent would see increases of more than 500 percent,
or an average increase of $4,098. Just 12 percent of cabin owners
would see their fees decline.
</P>
<P>
   The increased fees will double the Forest Service's revenue
collections under the program, from $9.6 million in 1998 to more
than $20 million by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Congress in the past two years passed legislation to slow down
the fee increases. But this year Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash.,
and Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, want to revamp the process by
requiring the Forest Service to consider factors that would lower
the appraisals.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, families cannot live on Forest Service property
year round or subdivide their lots, Nethercutt said. ''Families are
being unfairly penalized,'' he told the forests and forest health
subcommittee of the House Resources Committee, which held a hearing
on his bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 1831 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000323.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mentor Denies FDA Probe on Research  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) -- Trading of stock in breast
implant-maker Mentor Corp. was temporarily halted Thursday when the
shares plunged 50 percent because of a published report that it was
under criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Mentor denied the report that the Food and Drug Administration
was investigating it for alleged research irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   When trading resumed, the stock rebounded and closed at $30.50,
just 10.5 percent, or $3.56 below Wednesday's close.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to an article in USA Today, company officials
confirmed an open FDA investigation into ''manufacturing issues''
in 1998, but said it has nothing to do with how Mentor conducts its
implant studies.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have complete confidence in the integrity of our research
and believe that the allegations in the article are entirely
baseless,'' said Anthony Gette, Mentor's president and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   The company has since upgraded its manufacturing facilities, and
two audits found it to be in substantial compliance with good
manufacturing practices, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Mentor makes breast implants filled with saline solution and the
FDA has been examining the safety of these implants. Saline
implants have been the most widely used variety since 1992, when
the agency banned most implants made of silicone gel after
questions arose about whether they caused disease.
</P>
<P>
   FDA spokeswoman Sharon Snider refused to confirm or deny the
existence of an investigation Thursday. More information is
expected to be available once the agency responds to a letter about
the company from Rep. Tom Bliley, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia Republican, who heads the House committee that
oversees the FDA, asked agency Commissioner Jane Henney why a
company under investigation was allowed to participate in a saline
breast implant meeting on March 1, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   Bliley's letter did not name the firm, but a March 9 memo from
the FDA's Office of Criminal Investigations does, the newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, part of the FDA effort examining the safety of saline
implants, ultimately decided Mentor's products were safe and
effective, recommending that they be allowed to stay on the market.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Mentor Corp. home page: http://www.mentorcorp.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
