<HEADLINE> Employees Sue TRW Over Work Hours  </HEADLINE>
By KARIN MILLER, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Seven former and current employees of
TRW Inc.'s auto parts plant in nearby Lebanon filed suit Thursday
claiming they were forced to work off-the-clock for about 15
minutes of every work day for a decade or more.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court seeks back wages and
liquidated damages for all current employees and those who worked
at the plant over the past three years. It also seeks a jury trial.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland, Ohio,-based TRW Inc. employs about 650 workers at the
plant, which makes steering gears for trucks and operates 24 hours
a day.
</P>
<P>
   Central to the lawsuit is a written policy posted at the plant
stating an employee must: ''arrive at your work center in your
assigned department prior to the beginning of your shift so that
you and the employee on the job can properly communicate on any
issues and the status of the job.''
</P>
<P>
   It goes on to say that ''This is not a request: it is part of
your job and must be carried out every day.''
</P>
<P>
   David Sanford, an attorney for the plaintiffs, said supervisors
tell workers that those discussions ''do not count toward their
wages'' and they cannot clock in until afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ''They said you can't sign yourself in 'til 7, but you're
supposed to be there at 6:45. We were supposed to work in teams to
improve quality,'' said Robert Huddleston of Lebanon, who worked at
the plant for five months last year and is one of the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit alleges the company ''willfully, knowingly, and/or
recklessly violated'' federal law.
</P>
<P>
   ''TRW is systematically cheating employees out of thousands of
dollars and increasing their profits, potentially by millions, in
15-minute increments,'' Sanford said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Currently we are only aware of the situation at the Lebanon
plant, but if TRW implements this policy nationwide, or globally,
it has made substantially more millions on the backs of
uncompensated employees.''
</P>
<P>
   TRW spokesman Jay McCaffrey said he is ''not aware'' of such a
policy on pre-shift meetings. He declined to comment on the
lawsuit, saying the company's attorneys had not yet seen a copy.
</P>
<P>
   Plant manager Kenneth Caldwell did not return a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   TRW, which provides products and services for the automotive,
aerospace and information systems markets, has about 118,000
employees worldwide. The company had about $17 billion in sales
last year and reported net income of $469 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has Tennessee auto parts plants in Sevierville,
Rogersville, Vonore and Cookeville.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford said the off-the-clock work was discovered during an
investigation of race discrimination allegations at the plant. His
firm has asked the federal Equal Employment Opportunities
Commission for the right to sue over those allegations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
