<HEADLINE> McCurry, Fitzwater 'Join' Navy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In their familiar attire of dark business
suits and bright smiles, former White House press secretaries Mike
McCurry and Marlin Fitzwater ''joined'' the Navy on Thursday as
''honorary members.''
</P>
<P>
   In a Pentagon ceremony with Navy Secretary Richard Danzig
presiding, McCurry and Fitzwater were ''adopted'' by the crews of
two sister ships, the destroyers USS Arleigh Burke and the USS
Mitscher.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to expose more of the Navy to prominent civilians
like McCurry and Fitzwater, plus others that Danzig has lined up,
including soccer star Mia Hamm and entertainer Ed McMahon. The
civilians, in turn, are to use their status as ''honorary members''
to act as unpaid goodwill ambassadors for the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a relatively declining percentage of Americans have the
experience of military service, one question that concerns us is:
How do we convey a sense of that experience to the larger American
public?'' Danzig said.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, Danzig believes, is to enlist the help of more
civilians who can help connect America to it military.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry, who as President Clinton's press secretary gained
acclaim as a master at shaping, or ''spinning,'' a public relations
message, said he looks forward to getting aboard ship.
</P>
<P>
   ''The commander and I have already talked about the ship
schedule and where we can go out, and if you will teach me how to
navigate straight and true, I'll teach you how to spin,'' he said
with a laugh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
