<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mint Director Joins Zale.com  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The man who mints the nation's coins wants a
little change.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Diehl, director of the U.S. Mint, said he is leaving the
job he has held since 1994 to enter the dot.com world.
</P>
<P>
   Diehl, who spearheaded online sales of coins and other
collectibles at the Mint, said in an interview Thursday he will
leave the government Sunday and become president of Zale.com, which
sells jewelry online, around early April.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been able to cut my teeth on doing e-tailing at the
Mint,'' Diehl said, adding that he will use those skills in his new
job. ''This was as close to the ideal job that I could find'' he
said of Zale.com.
</P>
<P>
   Diehl also will become senior vice president of Zale Corp.,
parent to the online venture.
</P>
<P>
   The Mint began selling coins online in April and rang up $26
million in online sales during the final three months of 1999,
Diehl said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mint's deputy director, John Mitchell, will take over as
acting director. Set to become the next director is Jay Johnson, a
former Democratic congressman from Wisconsin who now works at the
Agriculture Department as deputy assistant secretary for
congressional relations.
</P>
<P>
   At the Mint, Diehl oversaw the introduction of the new
golden-colored Sacagawea dollar coins and has aggressively marketed
the new coin, particularly mindful of the flop of the Susan B.
Anthony dollar coin.
</P>
<P>
   He launched a $40 million ad campaign to promote the Sacagawea
coin and teamed up with Wal-Mart to use the coins when making
change for customers, a move that annoyed some small banks. He also
launched the popular, new series of quarters commemorating each of
the 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   Diehl has been credited for making the agency more efficient and
profitable. Over the past three years, the Mint's profits, which
flow to the U.S. Treasury, rose to $2.7 billion, six times what
they were in 1997, the Mint said.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.usmint.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
