<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reform Rabbi: Jews Harsh on Pope  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) -- Some Jews have been unreasonably harsh
toward Pope John Paul II's statements on the Holocaust, the head of
Reform Judaism's synagogue union said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Eric Yoffie, president of the Union of American Hebrew
Congregations, said the pope ''was expressing his sorrow not only
as head of a billion-member church but, also, as a man who knew
personally so many victims of the slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe that Jews everywhere were touched by the ceremony
and by his words, which so clearly came from his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoffie issued the statement just after the pope visited the
Holocaust memorial in Jerusalem on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Many Jewish spokesmen felt the Vatican's 1998 statement on the
Holocaust, and the pope's March 12 apology for Catholic failings,
were inadequate because blame was put on individual Christians
rather than the church as an institution.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech on Catholic-Jewish relations at Assumption College,
a Catholic campus, Yoffie said ''Jewish representatives should have
enthusiastically welcomed the recent statements as an important
step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not criticize any Jewish organizations or individuals by
name.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is surely inappropriate to greet a heartfelt act of
contrition with a pointed reminder of every act of wrongdoing that
I think may have been left off the list,'' he said. ''If every step
forward is greeted with an attack, there is little incentive for
additional steps to be taken.''
</P>
<P>
   He said John Paul has been ''both vigorous and daring'' in
condemning anti-Semitism and promoting friendly relations with
Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Union of American Hebrew Congregations: http://www.uahc.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
