<DOCNO> APW20000323.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NYC Cop Shooting a Campaign Issue  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- After several months of largely avoiding even
the mention of each other's name, Senate rivals Hillary Clinton and
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani are attacking each other over a fatal police
shooting that has become an issue of race, politics and decency.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady said this week that the GOP mayor's ''utter
failure of leadership'' was a sign that he couldn't be trusted as a
senator. The Rev. Jesse Jackson said Giuliani's combative response
to the shooting was ''not just meanness, it's mental.''
</P>
<P>
   The shooting of Patrick Dorismond alone would have likely
stirred anger in the city's minority communities. But Giuliani's
release of details about Dorismond's sealed juvenile record and his
suggestions that the victim was responsible for his own death drew
howls of protest.
</P>
<P>
   ''He should be expressing sympathy about the loss of life, and I
think that's the point that the average voter is thinking, 'What's
going on here?''' said Steven Cohen, director of the graduate
program in Public Policy and Administration at Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has maintained that the news media are incapable of
covering police shooting cases fairly, so his duty is to emphasize
the police point of view.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani campaign manager Bruce Teitelbaum said Thursday that
criticism from prominent Democrats is simply aimed at aiding
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why is anyone surprised that Hillary Clinton and her
supporters in the Al Sharpton wing of the Democratic Party,
including Jesse Jackson, are shamelessly exploiting this situation
for partisan political gain?'' Teitelbaum asked.
</P>
<P>
   But some Republicans are also wondering what political benefits
lay in Giuliani's refusal to meet with community members, as he has
done during past police shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think she can beat him, but he can beat himself,''
said Rich Bond, former chairman of the Republican National
Committee, who once worked for Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond, a black security guard, was shot March 16. An
undercover police officer approached him as part of a drug sting
and asked whether Dorismond would sell him marijuana. A scuffle
ensued, backup officers arrived and the gun went off.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting was the fourth of an unarmed black man by
undercover officers in the city in the past 13 months, and came
just a few weeks after a jury acquitted four white undercover
officers in the shooting death of Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   After initially cautioning people to withhold judgment about the
Dorismond case, the mayor criticized Dorismond's character --
including disclosing information about an arrest when Dorismond was
13 years old that was supposed to be sealed.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's something that is not well about his response to
unarmed people being shot by police,'' Jackson said Thursday at a
Manhattan high school. ''This consistent reaction for the police
who shoot unarmed people before even asking for information,
without showing sympathy to the victims ... that sounds like a
disturbed person.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has used the mayor's reaction to underline a theme of
her campaign: That the irritable Giuliani lacks the temperament to
be a senator.
</P>
<P>
   ''The mayor's utter failure of leadership hurts the communities
he won't meet with, and the police who defend the city,'' she said.
''If Rudy Giuliani won't represent all New Yorkers as mayor, how
can we trust him to represent the whole state in the Senate?''
</P>
<P>
   While Giuliani's camp fends off attacks from Democrats, the
mayor also could find himself being challenged from the right.
Anti-abortion activist and Operation Rescue founder Randall Terry
said Thursday he may get into the race because Giuliani, who
supports abortion rights, ''is a threat to the pro-life movement.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I would rather see a pro-abortion Democrat in office than a
pro-abortion Republican,'' said Terry, who lost a 1998 Republican
congressional primary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
