<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mother pleads as Assembly committee considers changes to sprinklerbill  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A mother whose son died in a January
dormitory fire at Seton Hall University begged an Assembly
committee Thursday to require fire sprinklers in every school, as
lawmakers weighed changes in the state's $90 million proposal to do
just that.
</P>
<P>
   ''Please don't put a price tag on our children's lives,'' Candy
Karol cried as she testified before the committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly housing and finance committee had met to consider a
bill similar to one passed by the Senate budget committee Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But that bill didn't satisfy the Assembly members, who suggested
doubling the time that schools would have to install sprinklers,
requiring all off-campus housing to add the protective devices and
using state money to fund the project.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers heard from school officials, fire safety inspectors,
sprinkler contractors and campus police, all supporting any measure
that would force colleges and universities to install the automatic
fire suppression systems.
</P>
<P>
   Several students from Seton Hall, as well as their family
members, crowded the front rows of the hearing room. Three students
died and six were critically injured in the Jan. 19 fire at a
dormitory on the school's West Orange campus.
</P>
<P>
   ''Please take a look at their faces. Don't let them be on the
front pages of a newspaper because they died in a fire,'' said
Karol, of Green Brook.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Karol, 18, planned a career in the FBI, his mother said,
but the school's lack of sprinklers cost him his life. Karol also
told lawmakers that more lives could be saved if every freshman in
the state were taught basic fire safety.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill requires sprinklers in every room in every dorm
in New Jersey by 2002, regardless of whether the building is old,
new, public or private. A 1991 law mandated sprinklers installed in
only new student housing units.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Educational Facilities Authority last month
reported that 36,600 beds in college dorm rooms -- about 71 percent
of the total -- have no sprinklers. This included eight colleges and
universities where none of the dorms have sprinklers in students'
rooms, including Rider University, Kean University and Seton Hall
University.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman John V. Kelly, R-Essex, held the lower house
measure, but did promise Karol that the Legislature would act soon.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly's proposals would require all of the installation to be
done within four years of the law's passage. The bill also would
cover all off-campus fraternity and sorority houses. Three students
died in a fire Sunday at an off-campus fraternity near Bloomsburg
University in Pennsylvania. Two were from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly and other members of the committee suggested a sliding
interest rate on the $90 million in loans to the schools.
Institutions that do the work in the first year would be charged no
interest while the rate increased over the term, Kelly suggested.
</P>
<P>
   There was also talk that the state should give the schools
grants to do the work, using budget surplus or money from the
recent tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill would create a $90 million fund to provide
partial loans at discount interest rates. Public colleges would be
obligated to repay half the debt, and the state would cover the
rest, turning it into what would in effect be a cash grant. For
private institutions, the state would cover a third of the debt,
leaving the rest to the college to pay from its tuition or
endowment sources.
</P>
<P>
   A Rutgers University security official told the committee that
school's estimate is $35 million to install the sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any cost that the sprinkler program brings about will have to
be passed onto the students in the form of rent,'' said Jay Kohl,
the university's executive director for public safety.
</P>
<P>
   One estimate is as high as $190 for each student to cover the
sprinkler tab, Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't want to raise any student's tuition rates. We're out
to save their lives,'' said Assemblywoman Carol Murphy, R-Morris.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
