<HEADLINE> WWII Monument Criticisms Heard  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Objections to the design for a monument to
World War II between the Washington Monument and the Lincoln
Memorial were aired Thursday at a Senate hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism came from Judy Scott Feldman, co-chair of the Task
Force on Memorials at the Committee of 100 on the Federal City, a
private citizens' group.
</P>
<P>
   She objected to 56 columns -- each 17 feet high -- proposed for
the north and south sides of the memorial, to changes in the
reflecting pool that face the Lincoln Memorial, and to restricting
public access to the National Mall through the new structure.
</P>
<P>
   ''No more marches on Washington!'' she said in an interview
after the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Feldman proposed a preview of what the new memorial would be
like by building a full-scale temporary mockup on the site.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Committee of 100 is not opposed to commemorating World War
II,'' she said. ''It is the current design on the Mall location
that is our concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Feldman testified before the subcommittee on National Parks,
Historic Preservation and Recreation of the Senate Committee on
Energy and Natural Resources.
</P>
<P>
   A final design for the memorial has not yet been approved, but
John G. Parsons, associate director of the National Park Service,
said after the hearing that changing the site would be very
difficult.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 1903 </TRAILER>
