<HEADLINE> Highlights of Fiscal 2001 Budget  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Highlights of the fiscal 2001 budget Republicans were
pushing
through the House on Thursday:
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERALL: Would spend $1.82 trillion while collecting $2 trillion
in revenue, yielding a $183 billion surplus, the biggest ever. Of
that, $166 billion of the surplus would come from Social Security
revenues and $17 billion from other sources within the budget.
</P>
<P>
   TAXES: Would cut taxes by at least $150 billion over the next
five years, and by as much as about $240 billion. Clinton proposed
$99 billion in tax cuts and $96 billion in tax increases, largely
on tobacco and some businesses. Over those five years, the
government is currently expected to collect $10.7 trillion in
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   DEBT REDUCTION: Republicans and Clinton would use all $1
trillion in expected Social Security surpluses through 2005 to
reduce the national debt. Republicans assign another $107 billion
in non-Social Security surpluses to debt reduction, though most of
it would vanish under their plans to use the money for tax cuts and
a Medicare prescription drug benefit. Clinton's budget has $90
billion in non-Social Security surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   SPENDING: Republicans would spend $307 billion for defense next
year, $1 billion more than Clinton. For domestic programs excluding
Social Security and other automatically paid benefits, Republicans
propose $289 billion -- $29 billion below Clinton. Both sides
propose increases in 2001 over this year's totals for defense,
education, veterans and biomedical research. Over the next five
years, Clinton would spend enough for overall defense and domestic
programs to stay roughly even with inflation. Republicans would
fall about $110 billion below that.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE AND SOCIAL SECURITY -- Clinton wants to create a new,
voluntary prescription drug benefit for all Medicare beneficiaries.
Republicans set aside money for a more modest version that covers
only lower-income people, or for other changes to the program.
Neither side, however, proposes benefit reductions or payroll tax
increases that many experts say both programs will need to remain
solvent as the baby boom generation begins retiring in a decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
