<HEADLINE> 2 Killed in N.C. Wall Collapse  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- A 26-foot-high cinder-block wall collapsed
at a tire store under construction Thursday, killing two workers
and injuring a third. A gust of wind was thought to be the most
likely cause.
</P>
<P>
   The injured worker was hospitalized in stable condition with a
head injury, said Allison Smith, a supervisor for the Cabarrus
County Emergency Medical Service.
</P>
<P>
   The store was being built for Discount Tire Co. The company's
regional manager in Charlotte did not immediately return messages
left with his office.
</P>
<P>
   Government safety and health inspectors were at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   When all four walls of a building are not complete, the
structure is unstable and concrete blocks can be forced down by
even a light gust of wind, said Scott McAnulty, a county inspector.
</P>
