<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Compromise on WWII Memorial  </HEADLINE>
BY CARL HARTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The text of a ''Japanese American Creed''
would be carved on a war memorial to be built near the Capitol, but
it would not be referred to on the monument by that title under a
compromise disclosed Thursday by a National Park Service official.
</P>
<P>
   John G. Parsons, associate regional director of the park
service, sent a letter earlier this week with word of the decision
to the chairman of a foundation backing the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   The text of the creed is to be carved on a memorial to the
Japanese Americans who fought in World War II, and to the Japanese
American civilians who were interned in camps during the conflict.
Presidents since the war have repudiated the internment, and
Congress has voted to compensate those interned. Ground was broken
last October for the memorial between the Capitol and Union
Station.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am proud that I am an American of Japanese ancestry,'' the
creed says, ''I believe in her institutions, ideals and traditions.
I glory in her heritage; I boast of her history; I trust in her
future.''
</P>
<P>
   It was written by the late Mike Masaoka, a controversial figure
in the Japanese American community because of his cooperation with
federal authorities on the internment. He was a leading figure in
the Japanese American Citizens League.
</P>
<P>
   Parson's decision was sent in a letter Tuesday to Melvin
Chiogioji, chairman of the National Japanese American Memorial
Foundation and a retired U.S. Navy admiral.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have received many letters from people expressing concern
at the potential inclusion of any quotations from (Masaoka),
reference to the Japanese American Citizens League or words from
the Japanese American Creed,'' Parsons wrote. ''Whether he is being
mischaracterized for his actions or not, it is clear to us that the
current controversy surrounding him is not going to be resolved if
his name is removed from the memorial ...
</P>
<P>
   ''Thus we believe that including his name and the words from the
Japanese American Creed, but deleting the reference to it, is the
best compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was not aware of any controversy about the other
quotations to be inscribed on the monument.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
