<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New rules for Megan's Law and sex offender notification  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Acting on orders from a federal court
judge, the attorney general on Thursday issued new statewide
guidelines on how information about sex offenders is made public.
</P>
<P>
   The new regulations require anyone who receives notice that a
sex offender lives near their home or school to sign papers saying
they will not disseminate the information. The court order
requiring changes in the law came after the judge said the state's
practice of community notification violated sex offender's limited
privacy rights.
</P>
<P>
   Megan's Law categorizes convicted sex offenders in three levels,
based on the perceived danger that the felon presents. For those
offenders deemed most dangerous, the law allows prosecutors to make
public an offender's name, age and address, as well as his job and
its location.
</P>
<P>
   But the law says only those people approved by a judge can see
that information. Courts have held that the community at-large is
not privy to all of those details once a sex offender is released
from prison.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rules, in order to get that information, people
must sign a statement that says the material is confidential and
that they ''will submit to the jurisdiction of the court.''
</P>
<P>
   If they don't sign, they don't get all the details, said Roger
Shatzkin, a spokesman for Attorney General John J. Farmer, Jr. One
item left out is the sex offender's street address, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on a class-action lawsuit brought by the state Public
Defender's Office, U.S. District Judge Joseph Irenas in December
said the state failed to implement consistent standards on how
notifications are conducted in all 21 counties.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit cited 45 instances in which rules on privacy and
limitations on spreading information were violated. These cases
include a newspaper that published the information and a school
principal who received a sex-offender warning at home and brought
it to work and photocopied it for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Irenas threatened to ban all future community notifications if
the state did not correct the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''The revised guidelines continue to protect the public's safety
at the same time they address the privacy concerns raised by the
district court,'' Farmer said in a statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will continue to work with county prosecutors and local law
enforcement agencies to ensure that Megan's Law is implemented in a
way that safeguards our most vulnerable populations,'' his
statement read.
</P>
<P>
   All county prosecutors in the state now have the revised
guidelines, Shatzkin said, and notifications will be done in the
same manner, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Different counties had different forms of notification,''
Shatzkin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Defender's Office is reviewing the new guidelines
''and waiting to see what the decision will be,'' said Ed Barocas,
an assistant deputy public defender.
</P>
<P>
   One problem, Barocas said, was that the state still gives out
privileged information, even if a person refused to sign the
waiver.
</P>
<P>
   Recipients are told the name and block number of the street
where an offender lives, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly that breaks the veil of privacy,'' Barocas said.
''Even if it is a huge street, 423 Main St., they will tell you it
is the 400 block of Main Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Megan's Law took effect in 1995, authorities in the 21
counties have registered 6,513 sex offenders and have issued
community notifications for 1,042 of them. Of these, 110 of the
offenders were classified as high risk, triggering door-to-door
notification of neighbors and residents likely to encounter the
offender. The rest were more limited notifications to schools, day
care centers and other facilities with custody of children.
</P>
<P>
   Megan's Law is named for Megan Kanka, a 7-year-old Hamilton
Township girl who was raped and murdered in July 1994 by a
convicted sex offender who lived across the street from her Mercer
County home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
