<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aggressive tuberculosis control program a big success in NJ  </HEADLINE>
By LINDA A. JOHNSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Aggressive tuberculosis control efforts are
paying off in New Jersey, especially in Newark, which has seen a 43
percent drop in cases to only 47 last year and a 71 percent decline
over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, the number of reported cases of the often-deadly,
airborne respiratory disease dropped 11 percent in 1999 to 571, or
7 per 100,000 residents. It was the third straight year that New
Jersey posted a double-digit decline in cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rates are going down nationally, but this is huge,'' said Dr.
Lee B. Reichman, executive director of the New Jersey Medical
School National Tuberculosis Center at the University of Medicine
and Dentistry of New Jersey in Newark. ''43 percent doesn't happen
in many cities, especially cities like Newark.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the credit goes to a program that ensures that TB
patients are cured -- by supplying antibiotics and having health
workers observe patients taking their pills daily for six months,
Reichman said Thursday, the eve of World TB Day, in a telephone
interview from Siberia, where he is helping evaluate a TB control
program.
</P>
<P>
   The World Health Organization, which declared tuberculosis a
global emergency in 1993, gave this year's observance the theme
''Forging New Partnerships to Stop TB'' in an effort to get more
health and government groups to join the battle.
</P>
<P>
   Tuberculosis, especially strains that have become resistant to
multiple antibiotics, is an increasingly serious health threat in
about two dozen foreign countries. It remains the most deadly
infectious disease in the world, each year sickening 8 million
people -- who each can infect 10 to 15 other people -- and killing 2
million.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one-third of the world's population has been infected by
the bacteria, and about 10 percent of them eventually will become
sick from it. Symptoms include coughing up green or yellow sputum,
sometimes streaked with blood, night sweats and shortness of
breath.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the number of tuberculosis cases soared
from 1985 to 1992, until the federal government restored funding
for TB control that had been eliminated in the previous decade.
Health officials blamed the resurgence on that lack of funding,
immigration and increased foreign travel, and the epidemic of AIDS,
which makes people more susceptible to tuberculosis. Last year, the
number of U.S. tuberculosis cases fell 5 percent to 17,528 and the
disease killed about 1,100 people.
</P>
<P>
   Just seven years ago, Newark had the second-highest rate of
tuberculosis cases among major U.S. cities and New Jersey had the
seventh-highest rate among the states; the state's rank has since
dropped to 12th. Last year, the state's case rate, 7 per 100,000
residents was barely half 1993's: 12.6 per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Like New Jersey, New York City on Thursday reported its seventh
straight year of declining TB cases, a 6 percent drop to 1,460
cases.
</P>
<P>
   The disease, which is spread by airborne secretions when sick
people cough or sneeze, killed 32 New Jersey residents in 1997, the
most recent figure available from the state Department of Health
and Senior Services.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Shilkret, manager of the department's tuberculosis program,
said the biggest decreases in TB cases have been in New Jersey
cities that have nurses and outreach workers visit patients each
day at their home or workplace and literally watch them take their
medication. Those programs, operating at Reichman's model center in
Newark and in local clinics in Jersey City, Elizabeth and Passaic,
also serve patients from surrounding communities, Shilkret said.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, he said, county health departments operate similar
programs but normally perform Directly Observed Therapy (DOT) only
for the first two weeks, then check on patients periodically. About
$8.5 million in state and federal funds covers the cost of the four
medications patients must take, salary for health workers and
administrative and other costs.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT program serves about 75 percent of New Jersey's
tuberculosis patients.
</P>
<P>
   It's crucial because without it some patients stop taking
medication when they begin to feel better and go on to develop a
drug-resistant strain, which then requires treatment for 18-24
months with stronger antibiotics, said Dr. Bonita Mangura, director
of clinical studies at the Newark TB center. Those can cause side
effects from diarrhea to deafness and psychotic behavior, she said.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage patients to complete their entire treatment, she
said, the center periodically gives them incentives such as
nutritional supplements and provides bus tickets to patients who
don't want health workers coming to their home or office.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been rewarding because we're seeing the numbers come
down,'' Mangura said. ''That means reducing transmission across the
board.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-23-00 1937 </TRAILER>
