<DOCNO> APW20000323.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long-Term Bond Yields Dip Further  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices of 30-year Treasury bonds moved higher
and the yield dipped further below 6 percent Thursday as investors
moved money out of agency bonds into the safety of Treasurys.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the long-term Treasury bond rose 25/32 point, or
$7.81\ per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the
opposite direction, fell to 5.91 percent from 5.96 percent late
Tuesday. The yield, which dropped below 6 percent for the first
time in six months on Tuesday, is now at the lowest level since the
5.90 percent of Aug 26, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst of the flight into Treasurys was congressional
testimony Wednesday by Treasury Under Secretary for Domestic
Finance Gary Gensler, which dashed hopes among some investors that
agency bonds will replace Treasurys as safe-haven investments.
</P>
<P>
   Gensler recommended that Congress eliminate a never-used line of
credit at the Treasury that so so-called ''government-sponsored
enterprises'' such as Fannie Mae, Freddie Mac and the Federal Home
Loan Bank System may tap on an emergency basis.
</P>
<P>
   Treasurys later reduced their advances and the shorter-term
notes ended lower due to concerns that the Federal Reserve would
need to raise interest rates again in May. The Fed raised rates on
Wednesday by a quarter point, the fifth hike since June.
</P>
<P>
   In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities
were down 1/32 point to 1/16 point, and intermediate maturities
rose by 1/16 point to \ point, reported Bridge Telerate, a
financial information service.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.87 percent as the
discount fell 0.04 percentage point from Wednesday to 5.70 percent.
Six-month yields were 6.12 percent, as the discount rose 0.01
percentage point to 5.85 percent. One-year yields were 6.20 percent
as the discount rose 0.01 percentage point to 5.85 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the
discount is the interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, rose to 6.06\ percent from 6 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds rose 9/32 point to 95 5/16. The average
yield to maturity fell to 5.98 percent from 6.00 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 1949 </TRAILER>
