<DOCNO> APW20000323.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Resolution Would Reunite Families  </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE RIZZO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawmakers announced a resolution Thursday that
seeks to help parents who have been cut off from their children
because foreign courts fail to recognize U.S. custody orders.
</P>
<P>
   ''Children belong with their natural parents and they belong in
the country of their citizenship,'' Rep. Nick Lampson, D-Texas,
said in announcing introduction of the resolution asking America's
allies to abide by a treaty that was supposed to resolve
international custody disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Lampson pledged to use any opportunity to ''embarrass them, if
necessary, point the finger, call the names of Germany and Sweden,
anyone else that is not living by the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tillie Fowler, R-Fla., said the U.S. government needs to
put more pressure on countries that fail to adhere to the treaty,
called the Hague Convention on Civil Aspects of International Child
Abduction.
</P>
<P>
   ''The State Department has been utterly impotent in their
ability to get these contracting parties to live up to their
obigations,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Chabot, R-Ohio and lead sponsor of the resolution,
warned against comparing the cases his measure seeks to address and
the Elian Gonzalez case.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cuba is not a signatory of the Hague Convention,'' he said.
''Germany, Austria and Sweden are supposed to be our allies. In
this particular instance they are not acting like civilized
countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Sylvester of Cincinnati said he won every court action in
the United States and Austria, where his daughter Carina was taken
by her mother in 1995. But Austrian courts later said the child
should remain in her familiar environment.
</P>
<P>
   ''The child was not returned because the order was not enforced;
now the order would not be enforced because the child was not
returned,'' Sylvester said. ''For me, the Hague Convention failed
miserably.''
</P>
<P>
   Chabot said Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has promised
to meet with Sylvester, which would send ''a strong signal to all
of those governments who consistently stonewall our efforts to
bring our children home.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department says there are about 1,100 cases involving
American children taken overseas by a parent. The agency does not
intervene in foreign judicial proceedings but helps American
parents make contacts in the countries where their children have
been taken, and helps parents file applications.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Weiss, director of the Austrian Press and Information
Service, said Sylvester's was a single case that was litigated up
to the Austrian Surpeme Court and ''settled in the favor of the
child.''
</P>
<P>
   ''From that one case to say that Austria does not apply the
Hague Convention is totally false,'' he said. ''To draw from one
case and say there is a pattern of noncompliance is simply not the
case.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: National Center for Missing and Exploited Children,
http://www.missingkids.com
</P>
<P>
   Parents of Internationally Abducted Children,
http://www.childrenabduction.com
</P>
<P>
   Text of the Hague Convention on the Civil Aspects of
International Child Abduction,
http://travel.state.gov/hague--childabduction.html
</P>
