<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore To Visit Mich. School  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- When Claudia and Donald Amboyer got the shocking
phone call that Al Gore wanted to sleep over, they insisted he take
their bedroom. But Gore wanted no special treatment.
</P>
<P>
   So the vice president of the United States was slumbering
Thursday night among their son's toy airplanes -- and studying up on
America's westward expansion from an eighth-grade history textbook.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the latest phase of his presidential campaign --
''getting as close to the grass roots as one can get as a
presidential candidate,'' as one top aide described it -- Gore
bunked with the Amboyers at their Macomb, Mich., home outside of
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning, Gore was getting up early to go to work with
Mrs. Amboyer, a sixth-grade language arts teacher at the L'Anse
Creuse Middle School North, where he was due to chat up teachers
and janitors alike, have lunch in the cafeteria and help teach
Diane Pesha's history class.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to show him a normal school day,'' said principal
John Davia. The school twice has been designated as a Michigan Blue
Ribbon school for excellence.
</P>
<P>
   Davia said he was glad the vice president wanted to visit.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't look at mixed motives or any other thing,'' he said.
''Even if he were just here for an hour, it's something they'll
probably remember for their whole lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ''School Days'' is what the Gore camp has dubbed his latest
means of reaching out to voters in novel, attention-getting ways as
he battles Republican George W. Bush for the title of Education
Candidate.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore told Democratic contributors this week, in order to
improve schools, ''We need to listen to the people where the rubber
meets the road -- the teachers and the principals and the parents
and give them the help by making it a national priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides called ahead to L'Anse Creuse this week and asked for
copies of Pesha's lesson plans and the textbook pages about the
Western frontier that her students were currently studying. He
planned to huddle with her for 15 minutes before braving the
chalkboard. (It was at a classroom chalkboard, after all, that Dan
Quayle infamously instructed a young spelling student to put an
''e'' at the end of potato.)
</P>
<P>
   The Amboyers, both Democrats, got the call about their VIP
houseguest with less than 24 hours' notice. Davia said he chose the
couple because they were ''empty nesters'' whose grown children
left spare bedrooms behind. Gore's Secret Service detail and
military aide also would be nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Amboyer, a retired sheriff and administrator at Macomb
Community College, expected that Gore, arriving late after
collecting $700,000 at two nighttime fund raisers, would want to
talk to Mrs. Amboyer about education policy and hopefully watch the
Syracuse-Michigan State game.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're big Michigan State fans,'' Mr. Amboyer said.
</P>
<P>
   His wife was too busy Thursday afternoon to come to the phone,
Mr. Amboyer said, but not terribly stressed with vacuuming and
dusting, though.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're neat people so the house is pretty clean. We're really
not sure what to expect, we're just so honored,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It just so happens that Mr. Amboyer is one of those voters Gore
has hotly pursued in recent weeks: A ''crossover'' Democrat who
voted in Michigan's Republican primary for John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Amboyer said he has since decided he's all for Gore. ''It
seems to me he has a message for everyone -- not just the elite.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 1958 </TRAILER>
