<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Cops Arrest Murder Suspect  </HEADLINE>
By VIVIAN SEQUERA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Colombian police Thursday arrested a man
they identified as the guerrilla commander responsible for the
kidnap-slayings of three Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect was captured in Saravena, the northeastern city near
where the three Americans were abducted in February 1999 and put to
death by leftist rebels, police spokesman Carlos Perdomo told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   He was identified as Nelson Vargas. Police first gave Gildardo
Gonzalez as his name, later changing it without providing an
immediate explanation.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, police said Vargas was being taken to Bogota
along with a man arrested with him, Leonardo Rodriguez of
Argentina. It wasn't immediately clear if Rodriguez was a suspect
in the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Activists Terence Freitas, 24, of Los Angeles, Ingrid
Washinawatok, 41, of Wisconsin, and Lahe'ena'e Gay, 39, of Hawaii,
were kidnapped and later killed while visiting a Colombian Indian
tribe based near the border with Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Their bound and bullet-ridden bodies were found in a cow pasture
March 4, 1999, just inside the Venezuelan border.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC,
admitted days later that one of its units carried out the killings,
prompting the U.S. government to cut its contacts with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels asked for forgiveness and blamed the act on a
''rogue'' local squad leader it identified as Commander Gildardo.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. and Colombian officials suspected a low-ranking rebel
may have been taking the fall for a more senior commander.
</P>
<P>
   Colombian prosecutors last year issued arrest orders against
German Briceno, the regional FARC chieftain and brother of the
powerful guerrilla movement's second-ranking commander, Jorge
Briceno.
</P>
<P>
   In severing contacts with the rebels, the U.S. government said
relations could only resume if the rebels turn over its guilty
fighters to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The FARC said it would never do so, and instead pledged to
conduct a ''revolutionary trial'' and mete out justice internally.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has been involved in the criminal probe, but the U.S.
Embassy had no comment on Thursday's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   In apologizing for the slayings, a senior rebel leader said the
Americans might have been mistaken for CIA operatives or undercover
drug agents in the country that has become a major U.S. military
aid recipient.
</P>
<P>
   The three activists were in Colombia working with the embattled
U'wa, an 8,000-member tribe which has campaigned internationally to
keep U.S.-based Occidental Petroleum Corp. from drilling on
territory the tribe considers part of its sacred ancestral lands.
</P>
<P>
   Washinawatok's Native American tribal leader in Wisconsin said
he was heartened by news of the capture, but wants Gonzalez to
stand trial in a U.S. court for the murders.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll tell you what would really make me happy, if I hear the
Colombian government say they are going to extradite this guy,''
Chief Apesanahkwat told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ''If that's going to happen then I think the families may see
some justice.''
</P>
<P>
   But Colombian President Andres Pastrana, who is engaged in peace
talks with the 15,000-member FARC, has said he would refuse to
extradite any rebels captured in connection with the killings.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials say there are no extradition requests pending,
even though more than 30 Colombians are wanted by U.S. authorities
for drug trafficking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 2001 </TRAILER>
