<HEADLINE> Mexicans Doubt Resolution of Murder  </HEADLINE>
By KEN GUGGENHEIM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- On the sixth anniversary of Mexico's most
notorious political assassination in recent history, most Mexicans
are skeptical about government efforts to resolve the case,
according to two opinion polls published Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Only one person -- convicted gunman Mario Aburto -- is in custody
in the March 23, 1994, killing of Luis Donaldo Colosio,
presidential candidate for the long-governing Institutional
Revolutionary Party.
</P>
<P>
   Colosio, who would have been almost assured of winning the
presidency, was killed at a campaign rally in the border city of
Tijuana. It was the biggest political killing in Mexico since
president-elect Alvaro Obregon was killed in 1928.
</P>
<P>
   The motive for the killing remains unclear. A special prosecutor
in the attorney general's office continues to investigate whether
Colosio had been the victim of a conspiracy, possibly involving
drug traffickers or political enemies.
</P>
<P>
   The scope of the investigation remains large. The prosecutor's
office has an annual budget of $520,000 and a staff of 100, the
newspaper Reforma reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the two opinion polls show many Mexicans critical of the
government's efforts. A Reforma poll found 68 percent of those
surveyed said the government has had little or no success in
investigating the case and only 16 percent said it had at least
some success. The poll of 1,510 Mexicans had a margin of error of
2.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   A smaller survey, by the newspaper Universal, found that only 19
percent believe there's a real interest in solving the case, while
81 percent think authorities want the case forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Universal said 90.7 percent of those surveyed believed Colosio
was the victim of a conspiracy. That survey, of 508 people, had a
margin of error of 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Colosio's campaign was struggling in the months before the
assassination, but in death he has become almost a legendary
figure, with even opposition politicians praising him as a
political reformer dedicated to helping the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The front-runner in the 2000 presidential race, governing party
candidate Francisco Labatida, frequently cites Colosio in his
speeches. Labastida laid a wreath Thursday at a Colosio statue in
Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   The main opposition candidate, Vicente Fox of the center-right
National Action Party, on Wednesday announced he had won the
backing of a tiny party named after the candidate, the Closest
Revolutionary Party. Fox also criticized government efforts to
resolve the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
