<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate passes bill reimbursing hospitals, doctors, for HMOfailures  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The state Senate on Thursday easily passed
legislation partially reimbursing hospitals and doctors who were
owed $150 million after two managed care companies went bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which has already passed the Assembly, would make
whole the providers who cared for patients insured by the
now-defunct HIP Healthcare of New Jersey and the American Preferred
Provider Plan.
</P>
<P>
   The state would use $50 million in tobacco settlement funds, and
surviving HMOs would also put up $50 million, under the bill. The
doctors and hospitals have agreed to forgive the last $50 million
of the sum owed them.
</P>
<P>
   The state owes it to the providers to make sure they are paid
for the care they provided in the weeks after HIP went bankrupt
last spring, bill supporters said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this happens again, how would hospitals feel if we said we
didn't care about their debt?'' asked Sen. Jack Sinagra,
R-Middlesex.
</P>
<P>
   But the lone bill opponent said it should be up to the parent
companies of the failed HMOs to pay the providers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Taxpayers should not be forced to bail out profit-hungry,
corporate con artists,'' said Sen. Shirley Turner, D-Mercer.
</P>
<P>
   Even a bill supporter chided the governor's oversight of HIP's
demise. State regulators approved a deal in July 1997 to have HIP
turn over most of its assets to a for-profit company, PHP
Healthcare Corp. Within eight months of the transaction, though,
PHP stopped paying health care providers, leaving HIP heavily in
debt.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the state Department of Insurance was on the job, we
wouldn't be here today,'' said Senate Democratic Leader Richard J.
Codey, D-Essex.
</P>
<P>
   The managed care industry lobbied furiously against the bill,
launching an advertising campaign against it and threatening to sue
if it becomes law. HMOs say the measure is unconstitutional because
it forbids them from passing the costs onto ratepayers.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Langevin of the New Jersey Association of Health Plans said
after the 34-1 Senate vote that his group is interviewing lawyers
to take the state to court.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to have to seek a different venue to get some
fairness,'' he said. ''Our message is not resonating in the
Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the head of the New Jersey Hospital Association
said hospitals are pleased that lawmakers agreed with their cause.
</P>
<P>
   ''This sets the groundwork to make sure the patients' needs are
being met,'' said Gary Carter.
</P>
<P>
   The bill now goes to Gov. Christie Whitman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
