<HEADLINE> Daily News appoints new top editors  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Daily News has named Edward Kosner
as editor in chief and Michael Goodwin as senior executive editor,
chairman and co-publisher Mortimer B. Zuckerman announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Kosner, who was the editor of the News' Sunday edition, replaces
Debby Krenek, who had been editor in chief since 1997. Zuckerman's
announcement said Krenek recently informed him she wished to pursue
other opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin has been editorial page editor since 1995. No
replacement was announced for that position.
</P>
<P>
   Zuckerman credited Kosner with revitalizing the Sunday edition
over the past year and added: ''I know he will bring the same
energy, creativity, focus and integrity to every day's edition of
the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosner, 62, began his career on the New York Post and worked 16
years for Newsweek magazine, serving as editor from 1975 to 1979.
He also was editor of New York magazine for 13 years and editor in
chief of Esquire magazine for four years. He joined the Daily News
as Sunday editor in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Daily News has always been a part of my life in New York.
It's an honor and a thrill to be asked to edit the paper I have
been reading as long as I can remember,'' Kosner said.
</P>
<P>
   Zuckerman praised the job that Krenek did as editor, noting she
oversaw investigative projects that exposed the city's most sued
doctors and revealed the depth of the problem of asthma in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Krenek started at the News as a deputy managing editor in 1987
and served as managing editor and executive editor before being
named to the top post.
</P>
<P>
   The News won numerous awards during her tenure, including a
Pulitzer Prize to Mike McAlary for disclosing the Abner Louima
police brutality case.
</P>
<P>
   The early 90s were turbulent years at the paper, which struggled
to publish during a bitter strike that ended when it was sold in
1991 by the Tribune Co. of Chicago to English press lord Robert
Maxwell. Later that year he committed suicide at sea as his
financial holdings collapsed in scandal.
</P>
<P>
   This put the News into bankruptcy proceedings before Zuckerman,
a real estate magnate, purchased it early in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Krenek issued a statement saying it had been an honor to edit
the News. ''I leave with some sadness and regret but pride in our
accomplishments over the last couple of years. We got the subway
fare lowered, by God, and that's what this paper is all about,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The paper crusaded for discounts that became part of the
Metrocard system for subway fares.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin, 50, who had been city hall bureau chief for The New
York Times, joined the News in 1993 as deputy editor of the
editorial page. As editor he oversaw a series of editorials on
reviving the famed Apollo Theater that won the 1999 Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   The Pulitzer board praised the News' ''effective campaign to
rescue Harlem's Apollo Theater from financial mismanagement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
