<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Catchers Like Expos Starters  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. (AP) -- Catchers Lenny Webster and Charlie O'Brien
have seen a lot of good arms in their careers, and they both share
the same enthusiasm about the Montreal Expos' starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal pitchers Dustin Hermanson, Javier Vazquez, Hideki
Irabu, Carl Pavano and Jeremy Powell are a combined 10-1 in spring
training, with a 2.00 ERA (17 ER in 72 2-3 innings) in 17 starts.
</P>
<P>
   With Expos manager Felipe Alou's preference of carrying three
catchers, O'Brien and Webster, both non-roster invitees, are likely
to make the team as backups for starter Chris Widger. Both have
been impressed with the staff's teamwork and desire to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I see is they're feeding off of one another,'' Webster
said. ''If one guy goes out and does well, the other guys say: 'I
want to go out and have a good start too.' I think that's the
reason why they've pitched so well this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Webster, a 35-year-old who is trying to win a spot in his third
go-around with Montreal, has handled such standouts as Curt
Schilling, Mike Mussina and Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien's list of battery mates is even more impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ''Success builds confidence,'' says O'Brien, 38, who has caught
Cy Young winners Greg Maddux, John Smoltz, Tom Glavine, Pat Hentgen
and Roger Clemens in his 12-year career. ''When you have both of
them together it plays a big hand in how you handle the tough
times.''
</P>
<P>
   With the 30-year-old Irabu the only pitcher in the group over
27, O'Brien realizes how important it is for members of a young
staff to react constructively to a tough outing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think to be successful in this game you've got to handle the
down times and learn how to bounce back from them,'' O'Brien says.
''Forget them and come back the next time out and put together a
quality start when you go out there.''
</P>
<P>
   That certainly hasn't been a problem for Montreal this spring as
Powell notched the Expos' sixth straight win Thursday over
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only time I've been back there that we've had bad days,
our pitchers have just missed their spots,'' Webster said. ''As
long as they're down and around the zone, they've been great.''
</P>
<P>
   And they've been willing to accept the advice the two veteran
catchers have to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we get now -- and I'm sure Charlie would say the same
thing -- is you see a lot of hungry kids on the mound, and they want
to do everything right,'' Webster said. ''They see a veteran back
there and they know that they just have to throw the ball where we
want them to throw it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hermanson, 27, who fell to 9-14 with a 4.20 ERA last season
after posting a team-high 14 wins in 1998, has impressed O'Brien
with his bulldog-type attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hermanson is a great competitor,'' O'Brien said. ''He's got
the makeup to be a very consistent pitcher in this game if he
learns to control his emotions. He's got to learn to channel them
in the right direction because his emotions can help him, but they
can hurt in certain situations.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien is also high on Vazquez, 23, who pitched a one-hitter at
Los Angeles last Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   ''Javier has got probably as good stuff as anybody in the
National League,'' O'Brien said. ''It's one of those things where I
don't think he understands how good he can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Webster caught Pavano's last outing, five shutout innings
against Los Angeles on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was the first time I've had a chance to catch him and
he's sharp,'' Webster said. ''A 24-year-old hitting spots -- that's
painting. It's very rare you see a young kid with that kind of
ability.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
