<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Spy Case Lawyers Subpoenaed  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate Judiciary Committee, over the
objections of its Democrats and the Justice Department, on Thursday
voted to subpoena two federal attorneys to discuss the light
sentence given a scientist suspected of spying for China.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., demanded the subpoenas of Justice
Department Criminal Division line attorney Michael Liebman and
former attorney Jonathan Shapiro, saying ''we have been
extraordinarily, exhaustively patient'' with the department but
''we've had precious little cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 10-6, along party lines. Specter plans to hold a
hearing next Wednesday on the case of Taiwanese-American scientist
Peter Lee, who reached a plea bargain with the Justice Department
and escaped prison time despite reports that he had passed advanced
radar technology secrets to China.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said he wanted to find out why a plea bargain was struck
before a full damage assessment of the alleged espionage was
completed.
</P>
<P>
   But Assistant Attorney General James Robinson, in a letter to
Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, Thursday, argued
that the department had discussed the case extensively with the
Senate and that subpoenaing two line attorneys who did not make
final prosecution decisions in the Lee case would have a ''chilling
effect'' on prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said Liebman is currently in New Mexico helping with
the prosecution of Wen Ho Lee, the Los Alamos scientist also under
suspicion of passing secrets to the Chinese, and forcing him to
return to Washington to testify could disrupt that investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy of Vermont, ranking Democrat on the
committee, said the department had supplied Specter with
''voluminous information'' on the Peter Lee case and going to the
extraordinary step of subpoenaing career prosecutors was
unwarranted. ''The argument could be made that it's nothing more
than grandstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said he too was worried about the precedent of issuing
subpoenas but was supporting the action because ''I think Arlen's
been jerked around enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee in late 1997 pleaded guilty to filing a false statement
about a 1997 trip to China and to revealing classified laser data
during a 1985 trip. He was sentenced to a year in a halfway house
with three years' probation and a $20,000 fine. The New York Times
last year reported that Lee, while working on a classified Pentagon
project, had given the Chinese technology to detect and track
submarines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
