<HEADLINE> Colleagues Laud New House Chaplain  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE ZIEGLER DIZON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- The first Roman Catholic appointed U.S. House
chaplain is a master at diplomacy and a stellar representative of
the church, his colleagues say.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Daniel P. Coughlin, 65, was sworn in Thursday as
chaplain, ending a four-month dispute over who would take over as
the minister to House members and their families. Some Democrats
suggested evangelical Republicans had stonewalled the appointment
of a priest as chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin, a 40-year veteran of the Chicago archdiocese, called
his appointment ''terribly unexpected.'' He was most recently the
archdiocese's vicar for priests -- a representative of the church
who intervenes when a priest is having difficulties and gives
spiritual and professional guidance.
</P>
<P>
   ''Father Coughlin has served the diocese well in parishes and in
specialized ministries. He is one of our most deeply respected
priests,'' said Cardinal Francis George, the archdiocesan leader.
''I pray that Father Coughlin -- and the pastoral gifts he brings --
will be well received by those who serve our nation in the House of
Representatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin started in the ministry in 1960 as associate pastor of
St. Raymond Parish in Chicago. In 1969, he was named director of
the archdiocese's Office for Divine Worship, a position he held for
15 years.
</P>
<P>
   He took a one-year sabbatical in 1984-1985 to study East-West
religions, serve with missionaries in India and teach at North
American College in Vatican City. He returned to the Chicago area
as a pastor and ran a retreat house for the church before his
appointment as vicar for priests.
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin grew up on the city's Northwest Side, and his mother --
at 85 -- is an usher at Wrigley Field, home of the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Edwin Conway, who went to the seminary with Coughlin and
has worked with him for 40 years, called the priest ''a smart,
sharp man with a great sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He holds to his principles, but he's very sensitive to others'
needs,'' Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin's colleagues were pleased to hear of his new post.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a fine speaker and he's a diplomat, so I think he'll fill
that role quite well,'' said the Rev. Henry Kricek, a priest at St.
Peter's Catholic Church in Skokie, a suburb north of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. John McNalis of St. Gabriel Catholic Church in Chicago
called Coughlin an excellent choice to represent the church on a
national level.
</P>
<P>
   ''He'll do a very good job,'' McNalis said. ''He's articulate,
and since they've never had a priest, I think what he says when he
delivers a prayer ... he's not going to embarrass the church. He's
not going to be fumbling over words.''
</P>
<P>
   McNalis questioned the political motives behind the choice --
Catholics make up more than 25 percent of the electorate -- but said
he was gratified to finally see a Catholic priest as chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it's to get the political vote, as least they made a good
choice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Archdiocese of Chicago site:
http://www.archdiocese-chgo.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
