<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Muslim officers get to grow beards for now  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A federal court judge has signed an order
temporarily blocking the state Department of Corrections from
establishing a new policy that bans prison guards from growing
beards.
</P>
<P>
   District Court Judge Faith Hochberg signed the order on
Wednesday to prohibit the state, the Department of Corrections and
Commissioner Jack Terhune from dismissing or disciplining prison
guards who refuse to shave pending a hearing on April 4.
</P>
<P>
   The order came after 33 Sunni Muslim officers filed a civil
rights suit claiming the policy infringes on their religious
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ''Despite the fact the U.S. Supreme Court last year let stand
two federal court rulings that struck down a similar ban on beards
among Newark police, the state has imposed its own policy, which
threatens my clients with disciplinary action and dismissal if they
do not shave,'' Robert Cannan, the officers' lawyer, told The
Star-Ledger of Newark for Thursday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   Although 33 senior officers and sergeants filed the action,
Cannan said more officers stand to be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those who filed the action have more than 20 years of
service and all claim to be devout followers of Islam, which
mandates the wearing of beards.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent letter filed to his superiors at South Woods State
Prison in Bridgeton, Officer Samuel Shelton Webster called the
policy an illegal intrusion on his right to freedom of religion.
</P>
<P>
   ''The implication here is that you must prove to the DOC that
you remain steadfast in your faith,'' Webster wrote. ''Monitoring
our religious life from year to year on the job is harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Six months after taking office in March 1998, Terhune rescinded
a longtime policy that permitted prison officers to grow beards.
Enforcement of the policy didn't go into effect until March 1, when
a revamped grooming and uniform policy was enacted.
</P>
<P>
   The officers' action draws upon the Newark police case, in which
federal courts ruled the city had no ''compelling governmental
interest'' in banning beards for religious reasons. The department
had allowed medical exemptions for beards for officers with skin
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The police department's lawyers had argued that the no-beard
policy was intended to present a professional and dignified image
to the public, and to establish discipline and solidarity within
the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   In October, the U.S. Supreme Court sided with the lower courts
against the Newark Police Department policy. Unlike the Newark
police policy, provisions for both medical and religious exemptions
are included in the new corrections grooming standards.
</P>
<P>
   However, the exemptions are not automatic or long-standing. The
policy requires Muslim officers to enter annually in an application
process that offers no guarantees of approvals and no appeals
process for denials, according to Cannan.
</P>
<P>
   The policy requires officers to provide the department's Office
of Employee Relations with a certificate from a religious leader,
which ''states that the maintenance of a beard or some type of
facial hair is a necessary component of your faith.''
</P>
<P>
   The policy also gives an officer up to a 60-day grace period
during the application process or whenever the application is
decided upon.
</P>
<P>
   ''But the application can be rejected in less than 60 days, and
the officer is then faced with having to immediately shave his
beard or face disciplinary proceedings,'' Cannan said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Department of Corrections defended their
policy.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter dated Feb. 21 to several officers, Terhune and Mary
Cupo-Cruz of the department's Equal Employment Opportunity Division
dismissed interoffice claims of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ''The grooming policy applies to all custody staff. It is not
directed solely to Muslims or to black employees,'' they wrote.
''Those with medical exemptions must refile each six months. Those
who qualify for religious exemptions must file annually. The fact
is that medical conditions change and persons may also change their
religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Carden, a spokesman for the Department of Corrections,
would not comment on the order.
</P>
<P>
   ''The department and its legal counsel at the attorney general's
office is reviewing the complaints and we are prepared to go
forward with our case,'' Carden said.

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-23-00 2046 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000323.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.J. Issues New Megan's Law Rules  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Acting on orders from a federal judge, the
state attorney general Thursday issued new guidelines to make sure
information about sex offenders isn't disseminated as widely under
the so-called Megan's Law.
</P>
<P>
   The new regulations require anyone notified that a sex offender
lives near their home or school to sign papers saying they will not
disseminate the information. The judge who ordered changes in the
law said sex offenders' privacy rights were being violated under
the old system.
</P>
<P>
   Megan's Law is named for Megan Kanka, a 7-year-old New Jersey
girl who was raped and murdered in 1994 by a convicted sex offender
who lived across the street from her home. Every other state has
some type of sexual offender law modeled after Megan's Law, but
many have come under fire.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the U.S. Supreme Court refused to reinstate
Pennsylvania's sexual-predator law, which was thrown out by that
state's highest court on the ground that it violated defendants'
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Megan's Law categorizes convicted sex offenders in three levels,
based on the perceived danger they present. For those offenders
deemed most dangerous, the law allows prosecutors to disclose an
offender's name, age and address, as well as his job and its
location.
</P>
<P>
   But the law says only people approved by a judge can see that
information. Under the new rules, in order to get that information,
people must sign a statement that says the material is confidential
and that they ''will submit to the jurisdiction of the court.''
</P>
<P>
   If they don't sign, they don't get all the details, said Roger
Shatzkin, a spokesman for Attorney General John J. Farmer, Jr. One
item left out is the sex offender's address, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on a class-action lawsuit brought by the state Public
Defender's Office, U.S. District Judge Joseph Irenas in December
said New Jersey failed to implement consistent standards on how
notifications are conducted in all 21 counties.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit cited 45 instances in which rules on privacy were
violated. These cases include a newspaper that published the
information and a school principal who received a sex-offender
warning at home and brought it to work and photocopied it for
everyone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 2047 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000323.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republican drops out of Senate race to seek House seat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Unable to gain traction in the Republican race
for Senate, former state lawmaker Brian T. Kennedy said Thursday he
will run instead for House by challenging Rep. Frank Pallone in the
6th congressional district.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, an attorney who lives and works in Sea Girt, said
Monmouth County GOP leaders encouraged him to challenge Pallone,
D-Long Branch, who is in his sixth term. The 6th district includes
parts of Monmouth and Middlesex counties.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many in his party, Kennedy favors more federal
involvement in public schools. He has said schools should be
required to teach ''character development'' to address ''the lack
of values and the problems of drug abuse and teenage pregnancies
and suicides in our schools.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he supports federal projects that protect New
Jersey's beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy represented Monmouth County in the state Senate from
1978 to 1983. Pallone, then a member of the Long Branch City
Council, defeated him in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy then ran unsuccessfully for House in 1984 and 1986
against Democrat James Howard. Pallone won the seat in 1988 after
Howard's death.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy declared last fall that he would seek the Republican
nomination to succeed retiring Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   He said he started too late to mount a successful challenge to
four other Republicans in the race -- Rep. Bob Franks, R-Berkeley
Heights; state Sen. William Gormley of Atlantic County; college
professor Murray Sabrin; and Essex County Executive James
Treffinger.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Michael Ferguson, who ran against Pallone in 1998,
had planned a second run this year but chose instead to move to the
neighboring 7th district to seek the seat being vacated by Franks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kennedy has some company in the 6th district.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Cerrato, an Edison stamp dealer, said he is seeking the
GOP nomination. So is Charles Hutchins of Piscataway, a corporate
attorney. A third Republican, Paul DiLorenzo, appeared before a
screening committee in Middlesex County, according to the state
party.
</P>
<P>
   The primary is June 6.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
