<HEADLINE> NEA Seeks $150M From Congress  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chairman Bill Ivey asked Congress on Thursday
for $150 million to support the National Endowment for the Arts in
the year beginning Oct. 1, a $52 million increase over this year's
appropriation.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's budget has dropped 59 percent since 1992, he said.
Members of Congress have attacked the NEA for supporting projects
they called obscene and blasphemous, but bipartisan support for the
agency frustrated an attempt by the Republican leadership to
abolish it.
</P>
<P>
   Ivey said $49 million of the proposed increase would go to a
program called Challenge America, which Congress refused to fund
for the current year.
</P>
<P>
   ''It engages the arts to offer young people creative, positive
learning opportunities during the most vulnerable times of their
day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He explained a study had shown that violent juvenile crime
triples in after-school hours when many teen-agers have often have
little constructive to do and no adult supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Ivey reported that last year NEA projects reached more than 5
million children, supported about 7,500 concerts and performances
and 200 fairs and festivals, helped more than 1,000 artist
residencies, backed creation of more than 400 works of art,
benefitted nearly 4,000 locations beyond actual recipients and
conserved over 3,000 works of art, artifacts and collections.
</P>
<P>
   He was testifying before a subcommittee on the Interior
Department and related agencies of the House Appropriations
Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
