<HEADLINE> Thursday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------
Alberta Promises To Protect Medicare
</P>
<P>
   CALGARY (AP) -- Alberta has pledged to protect the principles of
medicare within its new private health bill, Prime Minister Jean
Chretien said Thursday after meeting the Alberta premier.
</P>
<P>
   ''(Ralph Klein) said to me very clearly to me that he wants to
respect the five conditions of medicare,'' Chretien said.
</P>
<P>
   Chretien refused to comment specifically on Alberta's Bill 11,
which will allow for-profit clinics to do minor surgeries and keep
patients for overnight stays, until after it has passed.
</P>
<P>
   Tension between the two leaders seemed evident. Klein
interrupted Chretien several times as the two took questions from
reporters after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Klein said he found Chretien more conciliatory during Thursday's
meeting than federal Health Minister Allan Rock, who has suggested
the Alberta Tories should scrap the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Murderer McGray Says He Killed More
</P>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia (AP) -- Michael Wayne McGray claimed
responsibility for 16 slayings Thursday, some as far away as
Seattle, and said the urge to kill remains in him like a hunger.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm getting very, very strong urges again,'' McGray said
during a phone interview with The Canadian Press from his
segregated cell at the Renous penitentiary in New Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   ''From the moment I wake up, every time I'm around people, all I
want to do is lash out. I need to hurt somebody in order to satisfy
me. It's like (a) high for me.''
</P>
<P>
   McGray, a 34-year-old drifter, received a life sentence Monday
with no chance of parole for 25 years after pleading guilty to
slitting the throat of Joan Hicks in Moncton, New Brunswick
</P>
<P>
   McGray said he is responsible for at least 16 killings in cities
across Canada and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Defence Rests in Case of Teen Accused of Murder
</P>
<P>
   VANCOUVER (AP) -- A teenaged boy in jail for killing Reena Virk
told a fellow inmate Kelly Ellard would be blamed for the crime and
everyone else would go free, a witness testified Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year-old woman, who met Warren Glowatski in a youth
detention center, was among the last of 31 witnesses called at
second-degree murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   The jury didn't hear from Glowatski, who is serving a life
sentence with no chance of parole for seven years for his role in
Virk's death.
</P>
<P>
   The defence concluded its case Thursday. The jury will hear
final arguments Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ellard, 17, is the last of eight teens charged in Virk's death.
</P>
<P>
   She turned 15 shortly before Virk's death, but has been raised
to adult court due to the seriousness of the crime. The trial has
been moved to Vancouver from Victoria because of pre-trial
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Virk was 14 when she was swarmed by a group of teens under a
bridge on a suburban Victoria waterway called the Gorge on Nov. 14,
1997. Police found her battered, half-naked body eight days later.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Judge Grants Bail To Egyptian Accused of Terrorism
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- A judge granted bail Thursday to an Egyptian
refugee suspected of being part of an alleged plot to bomb Israeli
government buildings in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Bernard Grenier said the Crown did not sufficiently prove
that Tarek Adealy Khafagy needs to be kept behind bars to protect
the public.
</P>
<P>
   Khafagy, 30, was charged March 4 with three explosives-related
charges after police found explosives hidden in his bathroom
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and co-workers have agreed to post $5,000 bail for
Khafagy's release. He will return to court April 25 for a
preliminary hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Grenier also ordered Khafagy to obey a curfew when he's not at
work, report to RCMP twice a week and remain in Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   A third suspect, Kim St-Louis, of Hull, Quebec, faces two
explosives charges.
</P>
