<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Smugglers Said Sought $3.15M  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Three businessmen who were arrested in a sting
operation, including a ranking member of Thailand's top opposition
party, plotted to earn about $3.15 million by illegally buying
Iraqi oil and selling it in Asia, U.S. officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Each has been charged with conspiring to violate U.N. sanctions
with a scheme to buy more than $20 million in Iraqi oil.
</P>
<P>
   They came to San Diego this week to make final arrangements to
purchase the oil, said John Mallamo, a U.S. Customs agent in San
Diego. They expected to meet an executive of an international
trading firm, but the executive really was a Customs agent.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities on Tuesday arrested Amnard Vorachard, 58, of
Thailand; Surasak Nanaukool, 56, a member of Thailand's opposition
New Aspiration Party; and Simon Tan, 44, of Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   The oil smuggling investigation began four years ago when
Vorachard, who represents Thailand-based Action Dynamic Enterprises
Group, was under surveillance for another matter that has been
closed.
</P>
<P>
   The men, who made an appearance in federal court Wednesday but
did not enter pleas, were being held without bond. A detention
hearing was scheduled for Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq can sell oil only under U.N. financial controls, with the
proceeds used for financing humanitarian programs and Gulf War
reparations. The sanctions, imposed after the invasion of Kuwait in
1990, cannot be lifted until the U.N. Security Council certifies
Iraq is free of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   A court-appointed lawyer representing Tan said the undercover
agent lured the three men to California under false pretenses.
''All three of them thought they were involved with a legitimate
representative of the U.S. government,'' said defense lawyer Mark
Chambers. ''They would not have come here had it not been for the
agent's misrepresentation of what he could do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
