<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine, Florio appear together but speak separately  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Jim Florio came out swinging Thursday but
his opponent, Jon Corzine, had already left the ring.
</P>
<P>
   The former governor and former Wall Street banker are facing off
in the Democratic primary for U.S. Senate, and they appeared
together at Thomas Edison State College for a political forum set
up by the nonpartisan Partnership for New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The forum kept the two candidates apart. Florio said he wanted a
direct, side-by-side debate, something he has been hammering at
since last summer, while Corzine said the opportunity to speak to
the audience separately without rebuttals suited him just fine.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine took the first turn at the podium with some 100 business
officials who were enrolled in a leadership conference. He
patiently explained details of his positions on Social Security,
health insurance coverage, a larger role for the federal government
in public education, and pharmaceutical benefits for elderly
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Two of those in the audience, Martin Hirsch of Montclair and
Mary Wachter of Trenton, were complimentary. ''I was very impressed
with his presentation. I thought his thoughts and ideas were
good,'' Hirsch said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine did not mention Florio at all until afterward when
reporters asked him about the former governor's criticism of him.
</P>
<P>
   When Florio took his turn with the audience, he skirted the
issues and keyed on his experience, his credibility, and spent a
lot of time criticizing his wealthy opponent's inexperience and
reluctance to defend his proposals man-to-man.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would have been a much better program if the two of us
could have sat up here, given our views of things, and then had the
opportunity for you to ask questions, and to have give-and-take
between the two of us, my ability to respond, his ability to
respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio said Corzine in his unchallenged speeches was tapping
into issues everyone knows are popular.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you get to this point, you can memorize 15 minutes on
anything,'' Florio said. ''Part of the dilemma of not having (a
debate) between candidates is there is no opportunity to hear or
ask those penetrating, tough questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio said New Jersey needs a tested, forceful senator to
protect Northeast urban states from the conservative Republicans
running Congress and distorting federal funding.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who do you want to send down there to stand up for you and
your children and the values that you all have? Amateur or
professional, knowledgeable or not knowledgeable, forceful or not
forceful. That is the set of choices that people have. I am not
going to need any on-the-job training.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio attacked Corzine for what many expect will be high
spending, claiming Corzine rejected an agreement capping spending
at $9 million for the whole campaign. ''If you can't sell a message
for $9 million, maybe there is something wrong with the message,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking privately with reporters, Corzine said he was tiring of
Florio's constant attacks, saying no one wants that kind of a
campaign. ''I am presenting myself to the voters, and I presenting
myself on the issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every one of the ads (by Florio) that I read says Jon Corzine
favors Social Security privatization, and that is nonsense,'' he
said, adding his plan was the same as President Clinton's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said he would debate the former governor later in the
primary campaign but that he did not see urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ''He says I am unwilling to debate when I have been on the same
forum with him... a whole series of times,'' Corzine said. ''There
will be time for debates, and we will make sure they happen.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the viewers, Hirsch said, ''I suppose I was impressed
with the forcefulness, the depth of views, the experience that Gov.
Florio conveyed today.''
</P>
<P>
   Wachter said, ''I don't think (Corzine) was as deep on the
issues as Florio was. Obviously, he lacks the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   But she added that Corzine ''definitely has a genuineness about
him that is appealing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
