<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AM-NY--Got Steer?, 1st Ld-Writethru,470  </HEADLINE>
By VICKI SMITH, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHEELING, W.Va. (AP) -- Airing the tape-recorded execution of a
900-pound steer on a nationally syndicated radio show may have done
more to help animal rights causes than sign-waving protesters ever
could have, an activist said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Friedrich, vegetarian campaign coordinator for the
Virginia-based People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, said
New York talk show host Mike Gallagher should have gone one step
further with his broadcast, showing video of Old Blue's death on
television.
</P>
<P>
   And Gallagher should have watched instead of turning away as
meat-packer Bill Bledsoe fired a .22-caliber Magnum bullet into the
steer's furry white head, Friedrich said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I only wish you'd had the integrity to watch,'' he said by
telephone during Gallagher's live broadcast from the Capitol Music
Hall. ''It might have made an impression on you.''
</P>
<P>
   The steer was killed on Gallagher's orders in a concrete and
cinderblock room at a remote Marshall County slaughterhouse
Wednesday evening. The stunt, devised as a way to protest PETA's
recent anti-milk campaign, was intended to ''give them a taste of
their own medicine,'' the conservative Gallagher said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, PETA withdrew its ''Got Beer?'' campaign after
Mothers Against Drunk Driving and conservatives like Gallagher
charged the anti-milk promotion encouraged underage drinking.
</P>
<P>
   The irreverent campaign was intended to be a humorous way to
discourage the consumption of beef and milk, both of which PETA
argues are unhealthy and foster animal cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher didn't watch Old Blue's execution but he remained
unrepentant about it Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mankind has dominion over animals,'' he said. ''This is sort
of the circle of life. ... I'm not cruel. I'm not a sadist or
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   He did have second thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   When the time came for Old Blue to enter the killing room, the
steer balked. It took five men and a long yellow rope to drag him
into his cubicle.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm seriously thinking maybe we shouldn't do this. ... I
really can't bail out now, can I? Would people be mad if I backed
out?'' Gallagher asked his producer. ''Maybe we can give him a
reprieve.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Old Blue went out with a bang and a shudder.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Dave Hall got a check for $850, charities and shelters in
the Northern Panhandle will get some 500 pounds of meat, and
Gallagher got the satisfaction of pulling a stunt against the
activists he likes to call ''kooks.''
</P>
<P>
   Protesters picketed Gallagher's New York studio as he left the
city Wednesday, threatening to chain themselves to the front door
as he took a freight elevator to the basement with his gun-toting
bodyguard.
</P>
<P>
   But none showed up when he arrived at the airport or the music
hall, despite Gallagher's claim that he has had two dozen death
threats in the past week.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.mikeonline.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.meatstinks.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-23-00 2108 </TRAILER>
