<HEADLINE> Buchanan Vows Taxes on Oil Nations  </HEADLINE>
By SCOTT LINDLAW, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Taking a hard line on a pocketbook issue,
Reform Party presidential candidate Pat Buchanan promised Thursday
to slap new tariffs on oil-producing nations that systematically
withhold their product to ''gouge the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   With gas prices rising dramatically since last summer and
expected to cost $2 per gallon by summer, Buchanan charged a global
conspiracy'' by these countries to inflate prices.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference here, he pledged to cut financial aid,
including World Bank and International Monetary Fund loans, to any
country he deemed part of a plot to ''withhold oil and gouge the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's rivals for the White House -- Republican George W.
Bush and Democrat Al Gore -- also have weighed in on the issue, and
with different approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Bush said he was considering calling for the
suspension of a 4.3 cents-per-gallon increase in the federal gas
tax to combat the rising prices. Gore disagrees with that proposal
and said the solution is ''tough negotiating'' with the
organization of oil-producing countries.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan is in California for a swing of public appearances and
fund-raisers, although he said he did not know how much money he
would raise.
</P>
<P>
   ''All we need is enough to keep me and (wife) Shelly on the road
until our convention, and then thanks to the generosity of the
American taxpayer we're going to get $12.5 million, which will be
enough to run our bus across the country,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
