<HEADLINE> Mavs' Nelson Back in Front Office  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN MARSHALL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Don Nelson's job as general manager and coach of
the Dallas Mavericks had been in question since Internet mogul Mark
Cuban purchased controlling interest of the club in January.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson got the answer he had hoped for Wednesday when Cuban, an
owner-in-waiting until the league approves the sale, said he wants
Nelson back next season.
</P>
<P>
   While making his first public statement regarding Nelson's
return, Cuban created another question. Will Nelson coach the
Mavericks again?
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said he would like to keep Nelson in the front office; he
has three years left on his $1.65 million contract. However, he
also might try to persuade the 22-year veteran to coach another
season. Nelson has contended this season would be his last on the
bench, but said Thursday he would at least be receptive to what
Cuban had to say.
</P>
<P>
   ''From a personal standpoint, I don't think that would be what
is best for the team, but if, for whatever reason, he wants me to
come back, I'm sure going to talk to him,'' said Nelson, who turns
60 in May. ''I want whatever is best for the Mavericks.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban promised changes when the sale of the team was announced
and Nelson, who has won 35 percent of his games in three-plus
seasons, was thought to be on is way out. But the more Cuban worked
with Nelson, including their agreement to bring Dennis Rodman to
Dallas, it became apparent Nelson would stick around.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't known for a long time, but the bottom line was how
well Nellie and I communicate,'' Cuban said. ''The most important
part is that Nellie puts winning ahead of everything else. He puts
winning ahead of ego, which is not usual in this business.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said bringing Nelson back as the coach was not a priority,
but he would like Nelson as part of what he calls a ''brain
trust.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Cuban has hired Brad Davis, Garfield Heard and
Del Harris as assistant coaches, creating a football-style staff
atypical to the NBA. Cuban said he envisions Nelson as the
experience part of the brain trust.
</P>
<P>
   ''The idea is to try to get more brains into the group,'' Cuban
said. ''The players in the league are much younger, in general, and
I think it's important to have a balance in terms of how you relate
to players. Nellie obviously gives us the experience factor, so
we're looking to balance that side, potentially.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he got the feeling Cuban wanted him back, but was
not sure until he actually heard the words.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never asked because I didn't think it was my place to, but I
was happy to read it in the paper,'' Nelson said. ''If he thought
it was best for the team to get rid of me, then I would have
accepted it. I'm really happy he wants me back. I want to be
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Mavericks find a new coach or bring back Nelson, it
will be with input from the players. Cuban said he plans to poll
the players after the season before deciding. Nelson says its a
good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think Mark will be asking the players for specific
names of coaches, but more along the line of what qualities they
want in a coach,'' Nelson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
