<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramseys Make Promotional Push  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- After their fifth straight appearance on the
''Today'' show Friday, John and Patsy Ramsey's television tour
takes them next to an unprecedented two nights in front of Larry
King's microphone on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   JonBenet Ramsey's parents -- suspected of being involved in her
murder by some who follow the case -- are getting an extraordinary
amount of attention with their decision to break their public
silence and promote their new book about the case.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the ratings, it has proved compelling to many viewers
and discomfiting to others.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have a really hard time with it,'' said Karen Krieze, a
Montclair, Calif., woman whose daughter was murdered five years
ago. ''I started to look at one interview, but I decided I didn't
want to watch the rest of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ramseys' interview with Barbara Walters on ABC's ''20/20''
March 17 earned the newsmagazine its highest ratings of the season.
''Today'' drew an extra 400,000 viewers beyond its season average
Monday for Katie Couric's chat with the Ramseys.
</P>
<P>
   That boost is consistent with the story's history. The
sensational case has been a staple of television newsmagazines
since 6-year-old JonBenet's body was found in the Ramseys' Boulder,
Colo., home on Dec. 26, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second most-covered newsmagazine story in 1997,
topped only by Princess Diana's death, and the third most popular
story in 1999, according to NewsTV Corp., which monitors news
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is getting harder and harder to have a story that could be
claimed appointment television,'' said Russ Ptacek, president of
NewsTV. ''JonBenet Ramsey is a proven appointment-setting segment
where viewers are going to change their schedules for a new
development. And the Ramseys talking is a new development.''
</P>
<P>
   Giving the Ramseys five days to talk is unusual but not
unprecedented, said Jeff Zucker, ''Today'' executive producer. The
show also had a four-part interview with Regis Philbin this week.
''Today'' devoted about as much airtime to the Ramseys as
''20/20,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the core, it's a dramatic story,'' Zucker said. ''Everyone
sees something different in this story and everyone reads their
answers differently. And that's drama.''
</P>
<P>
   In their interviews, the Ramseys have professed their innocence
and promoted the theory that an intruder killed their daughter.
</P>
<P>
   In Boulder, Colo., on Thursday, Police Chief Mark Beckner said
his department is discussing the conditions for giving the Ramseys
a lie-detector test since they volunteered to take such a test in
the media interviews. They told ABC's Walters they were never asked
to take a lie detector test.
</P>
<P>
   Beckner has said he doubts the couple will follow through on the
offer. But on Wednesday he met with investigators to discuss the
ground rules if a test is given.
</P>
<P>
   The Ramseys said they had no doubt they would be able to pass a
lie detector test.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would expect it to be fair, we would expect it to be
administered independently, and we would like the results to be
released publicly,'' John Ramsey told Denver's KUSA-TV. ''And if
the Boulder police would like to come to Atlanta and do that we
would be happy to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Boulder police investigator Steve Thomas, who himself has
a book coming out on the case, says he asked the Ramseys to take a
lie detector test shortly after the body was found in their
basement.
</P>
<P>
   They are scheduled to appear Monday and Tuesday on CNN's ''Larry
King Live.'' It is the first time guests not involved in a breaking
news story have been given two straight nights on King's program, a
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   National news programs spend far more time on crime stories than
they did a decade ago, said Robert Lichter, president of the
Washington-based Center for Media and Public Affairs. The networks
figured they needed to mimic local news and tabloid shows to
survive, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ramseys also fill a sudden news vacuum created with the
presidential nominees all but decided, Lichter said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This story is everything that's wrong about television
newsmagazines,'' Ptacek said, ''and at the same time, it's exactly
what the newsmagazines are supposed to be doing -- telling dramatic
stories about dramatic people.''
</P>
<P>
   The heated ratings competition in the morning has something to
do with ''Today'' giving the interview five days, said Steve
Friedman, executive producer of CBS's competing ''The Early Show.''
Friedman, who has read the Ramseys' book, understands the
motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't seen any news that I didn't know before,'' he said.
''But if they had come to us, I would have put them on.''
</P>
<P>
   Krieze, for one, is sick of it. She resents the attention the
Ramseys get when other murders are all but ignored. She also
wonders why the Ramseys are spending time writing a book and
talking on television.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it was my child,'' she said, ''I would not spend one minute
other than looking for the killer of that child.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 2130 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
