<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Called Upon To Vacate Lebanon  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Critics of Syria's dominant role in
Lebanon called Thursday on Damascus to begin withdrawing its army
from the country, fearing a Middle East peace settlement could
strengthen Syria's position in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The calls came ahead of a Sunday meeting in Geneva between
President Clinton and Syrian President Hafez Assad that could lead
to the resumption of stalled Syrian-Israeli peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   A peace accord between Syria and Israel likely would lead to a
deal between Israel and Lebanon, where Syria dominates with 30,000
troops. Critics of Syrian policy fear Damascus could end up with
even more clout in Lebanon because its troops could be used to help
the Lebanese government implement any peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In a front-page commentary, the leading Beirut daily An-Nahar
called on Syria on Thursday to begin withdrawing its troops from
Beirut and coastal parts of Lebanon in line with a peace agreement
that ended the 1975-90 civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Gebran Tueni, An-Nahar's managing director, said many Lebanese,
mainly Christians, rejected the Syrian control over their country.
</P>
<P>
   ''The demands of the Lebanese for the redeployment (of Syrian
forces) do not make them traitors or enemies. They are suppressed
citizens waiting for answers that will dispel justified fears,''
Tueni said in an open letter to Col. Bashar Assad, the influential
son of the Syrian president. Assad also is Syria's heir apparent
and the man in charge of policy on Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian troops first entered Lebanon in 1976, ostensibly as
peacekeepers to put a stop to civil war. The Lebanese government,
split equally between Christians and Muslims, has supported
continued Syrian military presence and political involvement as a
stabilizing factor during the nation's recovery from the war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 2136 </TRAILER>
