<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Security Costs Up to $3.9M  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS WILLIAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Texans have spent $1.3 million so far this
year on security for Gov. George W. Bush while he campaigned for
president, according to figures released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The amount is more than four times the $286,000 that it cost to
protect Bush and his family in 1998, when he was not a candidate
for president, according to previously released numbers.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, the state has spent $3.9 million on security for
the Bushes in the 15-month period beginning in January 1999,
according to new figures from the Texas Department of Public
Safety.
</P>
<P>
   The DPS released the information in response to several
requests, said spokeswoman Tela Mange. In keeping with policy, it
did not provide a detailed breakdown of how the money was spent due
to concerns that the information would compromise Bush's security,
Mange said.
</P>
<P>
   Previously released figures show the state spent $2.65 million
on Bush's security in 1999, or about $221,000 a month. The costs
have risen to about $432,000 per month this year.
</P>
<P>
   Mange said her department expects the costs to decrease now that
the federal Secret Service is now handling security for Bush. The
DPS still protects his family, however, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will not have the volume of expenses that we did earlier
this year,'' Mange said.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Edwards, a spokeswoman for Bush, said the state was
required by law to pay for his security, whether he is in or out of
state, until the Secret Service took over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 2137 </TRAILER>
