<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blazers' Sabonis Out Indefinitely  </HEADLINE>
By LANDON HALL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Portland Trail Blazers center Arvydas
Sabonis is out indefinitely after severely spraining his right foot
against the Detroit Pistons on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Sabonis fell and got his right leg twisted underneath him after
he was bumped by Detroit's Christian Laettner with four minutes
left in the third quarter. The Blazers led 75-64 at the time, but
the Pistons shot 64 percent after the injury and won 104-95.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays and a CAT scan were negative for Sabonis, but he won't
travel with the Blazers for Friday night's game at Golden State.
Sabonis, 35, has been relatively durable the past two seasons,
missing only five games, but the foot may take a few games to heal.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're probably looking at starting Jermaine O'Neal, with
Rasheed (Wallace), and then going accordingly based on the teams we
play,'' Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy said after Thursday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   Portland also will consider bringing Brian Grant and 38-year-old
center Joe Kleine off the injured list Friday. Kleine, who
postponed retirement to sit the bench just for this type of
emergency, has played in just seven games. Grant has missed the
last eight games with inflammation of the fascia in his right foot
but worked out hard Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers also could use 6-foot-11 Antonio Harvey off the
bench, but he hasn't played more than one or two minutes since
early January and is recovering from arthroscopic surgery on his
right knee. Harvey was at the hospital Thursday -- with his wife,
who is scheduled to give birth soon.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage of big men comes at a bad time for the Blazers, who
dropped six games behind the Los Angeles Lakers in the Pacific
Division and have all but given up hope of catching them for
homecourt advantage throughout the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   With or without the 7-3 Sabonis, the Blazers have been
inconsistent lately. They played well in a 97-96 win at Seattle on
Saturday, but on three days' rest, they turned the ball over eight
times in the third quarter against the Pistons, who were playing on
consecutive nights.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're really disappointed with our second-half performance,''
said O'Neal, who goes against the Knicks' Patrick Ewing and Marcus
Camby on Sunday. ''It's almost like we gave up a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers have been on autopilot much of the time since a Feb.
29 home loss to the Lakers, when both teams shared the league's
best record at 45-11.
</P>
<P>
   Portland has gone just 5-5 since that defeat, and has lost four
of six at home after winning 16 straight. The Blazers blew
fourth-quarter leads to Minnesota and Detroit, and a 19-point loss
to Toronto was their worst of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got to bounce back, because teams are crawling up our
backs right now,'' O'Neal said, even though the Blazers are
comfortably six games ahead of Phoenix for the No. 3 playoff spot.
''We're not concerned about really catching (the Lakers), we're
just concerned about winning games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 2207 </TRAILER>
