<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres 4, Flames 2  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN WAWROW, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Jay McKee and Miroslav Satan scored in the
final 2:08 to lift the Buffalo Sabres into eighth place in the
Eastern Conference with a 4-2 victory over the Calgary Flames on
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Satan, who ended a 13-game goal drought, had two goals while
Geoff Sanderson also scored for the Sabres, who moved one point
ahead of the idle Montreal Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Bureau and rookie Jeff Cowan scored for the under-manned
Flames, who were missing three regulars, including second-leading
scorer Jarome Iginla, who injured his knee in Wednesday's 2-2 tie
at Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The Flames' playoff hopes grew slimmer, as they remain in 11th
place in the West, six points behind the eighth-place San Jose
Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   Maxim Afinogenov, who had with two assists, set up McKee's
go-ahead goal. Working his way around the Flames net, Afinogenov
hit McKee at the left point with a pass. Turning toward the net,
McKee blasted a shot that beat goalie Fred Brathwaite on the short
side.
</P>
<P>
   Satan sealed it, scoring on a breakaway 57 seconds later.
</P>
<P>
   After Cowan put the Flames ahead eight minutes into the third,
Sanderson tied it with 10:14 left in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Each team scored on its first shot.
</P>
<P>
   Bureau, on a 2-on-1 break, converted Valeri Bure's pass to open
the scoring 75 seconds into the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres tied it on Satan's goal less than two minutes later.
It was Satan's 30th goal of the season and 100th as a member of the
Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   The goal inspired a curious celebration from Satan, who flipped
off his glove and smashed it a few times with his stick.
</P>
<P>
   The Flames were also missing Phil Housley, their defensive
scoring leader, who was home in Minnesota after his mother died
earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres welcomed back two regulars to their lineup: captain
Michael Peca, who missed seven games with a dislocated shoulder,
and Alexei Zhitnik, who missed six with a broken finger.
</P>
<P>
   Peca, among the NHL's hardest checkers, did not shy away from
physical play. In the first, he hammered Bureau behind the Sabres
net. Bureau needed help to get off the ice and did not return.
</P>
<P>
   Then, six minutes into the second, Peca briefly sent Bure to the
dressing room after being leveled with a right forearm to the chin.
</P>
<P>
   The Flames were down to 10 reserve skaters before Bure returned
to the bench about three minutes later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
