<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kings 3, Flyers 2, OT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Jozef Stumpel scored the tying goal late in
the third period, and had the game-winner in overtime as Los
Angeles beat Philadelphia 3-2 Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel, who tipped in Craig Johnson's shot from the front of
the net to tie the game 2-2 with 2:15 left in regulation, helped
the Kings snap a four-game winless string. (0-3-1)
</P>
<P>
   His wrist shot from high in the slot trickled between the pads
of Flyers' goalie Brian Boucher at 1:20 of overtime for the
game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's Gino Odjick tapped in a rebound of Kent
Manderville's shot to give the Flyers a 2-1 lead with 9:27 left in
the third, just 57 seconds after Luc Robitaille's power-play goal
tied it for the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Jody Hull scored Philadelphia's other goal in a game
overshadowed by center Eric Lindros comments about the treatment of
his second concussion of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles, which had lost its last five games in Philadelphia,
snapped the Flyers' two-game winning streak. Philadelphia was 3-1-1
in its previous five.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher, who shut out Nashville 2-0 on Tuesday, had not allowed
a goal in 141 minutes, 27 seconds before Robitaille scored to tie
Dave Andreychuk for 16th place on the NHL's career goal scoring
list with 551.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles goalie Stephane Fiset, making his first appearance
since suffering a groin injury against Nashville on March 4,
preserved the tie when he made a brilliant glove save on Mark
Recchi's shot from the crease with 33 seconds left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Hull gave the Flyers a 1-0 lead at 13:38 of the second when he
redirected Manderville's tip of a shot from the left boards by
Odjick. The assist was Manderville's first point since being
acquired from Carolina on March 14.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Lindros blamed himself and also criticized
the Flyers organization for its handling of the circumstances
surrounding his Grade II concussion that will sideline him for the
rest of the regular season. Lindros suffered the injury against
Boston on March 4, but played in four games after that.
</P>
<P>
   The severity of Lindros's fourth concussion in two years wasn't
diagnosed until the Philadelphia captain was examined in Chicago
this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers issued an ''organizational statement'' before
Thursday's game in which they defended the ''integrity and skill''
of their training team and medical staff.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to missing Lindros, the Flyers played without rookie
Simon Gagne, who has the flu.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers also announced that coach Roger Neilson was released
from Philadelphia's Hahnemann University Hospital on Thursday.
Neilson, suffering from cancer, underwent a stem cell transplant on
Mar. 10 and is ''doing extremely well,'' according to his
physician, Dr. Isadore Brodsky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
