<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Warns U.N. on Funding Needs  </HEADLINE>
EDITH M. LEDERER
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke warned
Thursday that it will be impossible to fund increases in U.N.
peacekeeping operations unless the United Nations makes the payment
system fairer.
</P>
<P>
   He said that without a chance, the United Nations will be unable
to carry out its most important responsibility: dealing with
peacekeeping challenges from Africa to Kosovo and East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ''We face a potential train wreck between our aspirations for
successful peacekeeping, especially in Africa, and our current
system for funding those same peacekeeping efforts -- an antiquated
and inequitable system that will no longer bear the burdens and
obligation placed upon it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke's warning came in his first appearance before the
General Assembly's finance committee since Congress voted in
December to pay $926 million in U.N. arrears over three years --
provided the United Nations meets about two dozen conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Two key conditions call for a reduction in the U.S. share of the
U.N. peacekeeping budget from the current 31 percent to 25 percent,
and in the regular budget from 25 percent to 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke used his committee appearance to justify the
Congressional demands, arguing that the scale of assessment for
peacekeeping operations was established in 1973 to fund a single
mission in the Sinai -- with about 90 percent of peacekeeping costs
paid by less than 10 countries.
</P>
<P>
   During the past few months, Holbrooke has been lobbying the 187
other U.N. members to agree to the revamped payment scale, most
recently the leaders of China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been little sympathy for the U.S. effort, because
most U.N. members blame the U.N. financial crisis on the U.S.
failure to pay its dues on time and without conditions, as called
for in the U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said agreement on a revised scale is particularly
important now since the peacekeeping budget is expected to double
to $2 billion this year and grow even larger next year because of
the expected expansion of the peacekeeping operation in Congo. But
he said the United Nations doesn't have the management structure or
financial system to support such an expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Before addressing the committee, Holbrooke joined Russia's U.N.
Ambassador Sergey Lavrov in announcing that Moscow and Washington
would intensify cooperation to try to get all U.N. members behind
the reforms.
</P>
<P>
   l
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 2221 </TRAILER>
