<HEADLINE> Report: Accused Killer Said Insane  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- An eminent psychiatrist hired by the
prosecution concluded a schizophrenic accused of stabbing his
pregnant girlfriend to death was insane at the time, defense
lawyers said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor's conclusion, filed in court Thursday, gives lawyers
for Michael Laudor a major weapon to buttress his insanity defense.
</P>
<P>
   None of the parties would release the two-page report by Dr.
Park Dietz of Newport Beach, Calif. But defense attorney Andrew
Rubin said it confirms what defense experts have already concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is what we've expected from the beginning,'' he said.
''This case was a terrible tragedy and here's their own doctor
confirming what our doctors have found, that Michael was not
responsible for his actions.''
</P>
<P>
   If the District Attorney decides to accept an insanity plea
rather than go to trial, Laudor would remain institutionalized
until he's no longer a danger to himself or others. The
prosecutor's office did not return phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Laudor's girlfriend, Caroline Costello, 37, was found slashed to
death two years ago in the kitchen of the Hastings-on-Hudson
apartment she shared with Laudor. Laudor, who fled in her car, was
tracked to Ithaca and charged with murder.
</P>
<P>
   He had been considered a role model for victims of schizophrenia
who control the disease with medication. Laudor, 37, had a law
degree from Yale and had sold book and movie rights to his story.
But friends said that before the killing he had been troubled by
his father's death and his inability to finish his book, and may
have stopped taking his medication.
</P>
<P>
   Dietz, who has been involved in the cases of John Hinckley,
Jeffrey Dahmer, Theodore Kaczynski and Lyle and Erik Menendez,
refused to comment on his report.
</P>
</TEXT>
