<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Insurer Faces License Loss  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID MARK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- A St. Petersburg insurance company
faces a possible loss of its license for allegedly trying to
intimidate a state regulator by hiring a private investigator to
follow him and dig up dirt on him.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance Commissioner Bill Nelson said Thursday he is taking
action against Bankers Insurance Co. for sending the investigator
to follow Kevin McCarty, who has worked for the state Department of
Insurance for nearly 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The company is said to have followed McCarty to a bar and a
grocery store, looked into his bank records and tapped into his
telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the company said it ''is deeply disappointed by
what it believes are politically motivated actions against a proven
and professional management team.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Bankers acknowledged in the very beginning that the
investigation may have been inappropriate and publicly apologized
but was advised that nothing illegal was done by Bankers or its
management.''
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Insurance has 21 days to request a hearing on the
complaint, or face a penalty ranging from a fine to the suspension
or revocation of its license to do business in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers allegedly hired the private investigator after it lost a
$16-million contract with Florida's Joint Underwriting Association,
the group that acts as the state insurance pool for homeowners who
cannot get coverage on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   McCarty supervised the JUA at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson pursued the charges after a judge earlier this month
released court records from a civil case McCarty earlier brought
against the insurance company. That case is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   According to the insurance commissioner's office, McCarty first
learned he was being followed in August 1995, when an FBI agent
told him his phone was tapped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 2246 </TRAILER>
