<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Alliance Files for Chapter 11  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif., (AP) -- First Alliance Corp., which lends money
to home buyers with poor credit, filed for bankruptcy protection
Thursday and said it will lay off 85 percent of its staff and stop
making loans.
</P>
<P>
   The Irvine-based company said it would close all its branches,
located in 10 states, and will lay off approximately 300 people.
</P>
<P>
   The company is being investigated by the U.S. Department of
Justice and seven state attorneys general because of complaints
about its lending practices. The company also faces lawsuits filed
by stockholders and customers, also alleging deceptive business
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the company was the subject of an
investigative article in The New York Times and a segment of the
ABC News program ''20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   Company Chairman Brian Chisick blamed the recent ''unwarranted
negative publicity'' for the decision to seek Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection.
</P>
<P>
   ''These unfair and inaccurate stories have devastated the
company's 30-year reputation and acutely hindered the company's
relationships with businesses, consumers and regulators,'' Chisick
said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
   In its annual report, filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission on March 13, the company cited a number of lawsuits and
investigations and said it was discussing settlement of a suit
filed in 1998 by the American Association of Retired Persons and
one filed in 1998 by the attorney general of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said it was cooperating with the Justice
Department in its inquiry. It also discussed a class-action lawsuit
filed in 1998 by a group of the company's stockholders, alleging
the company conspired against the stockholders by ''failing to
disclose known material adverse conditions in making certain public
statements about the company's growth prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   Those prospects have been less than healthy in recent years. The
company's annual earnings have been dropping steadily since 1995.
In 1999, the company reported net income of $3.8 million, down from
$14.2 million in 1998 and $32.7 million in 1997, according to its
annual report.
</P>
<P>
   The company has branches in California, New York, New Jersey,
Illinois, Arizona, Colorado, Maryland, Oregon, Utah and Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
