<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court gives phyisician another chance to reclaim license  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL GORMLEY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The state must consider restoring the
medical license of a physician who lost his practice for
''negligent and incompetent'' abortions nine years ago in which one
woman later died, state officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The state Appellate Division reversed a lower Supreme Court
ruling and sent the case of Dr. Andre Nehorayoff back to the state
Board of Regents. The Board of Regents must reconsider restoring
the physician's license from when he worked at the Manhattan
Women's Health Center, according to the decision released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Nehorayoff's license was suspended in 1991 for negligence and
incompetence, according to state Health Department spokeswoman
Claire Pospisil.
</P>
<P>
   One 18-year-old woman died of what a medical examiner described
as ''hemorrhage due to incomplete abortion,'' according to the
state Attorney General's Office. A 36-year-old woman had an
emergency hysterectomy after suffering a lacerated uterus and a
portion of an 18-year-old woman's bowel was delivered through her
cervix, the court record stated.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 months later, the Regents revoked the license for
''negligent treatment of five patients'' from 1983-90 and poor
record keeping, court records stated.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, he tried to get his license back. Two years later, he
appeared before the Peer Review Committee, which concluded
Nehorayoff had ''sufficiently fulfilled the standards of remorse,
rehabilitation and re-education'' to practice again with three
years' probation. Another professional review by the Committee on
Professions also recommended the doctor return to medicine, but
with 10 years probation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the state Board of Regents found the recommendations
weren't enough. The board didn't return the license because of the
seriousness of the offense and ''a lack of an appropriate degree of
concern'' by the physician. The board also noted the concerns of a
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Nehorayoff took the Regents to court, but the
Supreme Court sided with the Regents.
</P>
<P>
   The Appellate Division court, however, ruled the lower court
failed to make a balanced review of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate justices said the physician was contrite, accepted
punishment and attended class to improve his skills and knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Appellate Division Justice Thomas
Mercure said his colleagues shouldn't have overruled the lower
court because the Regents decided restoring the license would pose
a risk to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Nehorayoff couldn't be found Thursday for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The state Attorney General's Office is considering an appeal to
the state's highest court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-23-00 2251 </TRAILER>
