<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 23:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boy Held Classmates At Gunpoint  </HEADLINE>
By THOMAS J. SHEERAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON, Ohio (AP) -- A 12-year-old who told authorities he wanted
to be with his mother in jail briefly held his sixth-grade class at
gunpoint Thursday before a teacher persuaded him to give up the
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   No one was hurt and no charges were immediately filed against
the boy, who was taken into custody.
</P>
<P>
   The boy said ''his biological mother was in jail and he wanted
to visit her, be with her,'' said Anthony Krukowski, superintendent
of Lisbon schools.
</P>
<P>
   Police Sgt. Fred Carlisle confirmed the boy wanted to reunite
with his mother. ''Yes, that's what he told a teacher and one of
the police officers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's father told police the weapon -- a loaded, 9 mm
semiautomatic -- had been stored on a dresser top with a fully
engaged trigger lock.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief John Higgins, who would not disclose the boy's name
because he is a juvenile, said the boy apparently found the key and
removed the trigger lock.
</P>
<P>
   About 8:45 a.m., the boy stood up in his classroom at McKinley
Elementary School, pointed the gun at the floor and told his fellow
students and teacher to get down, Higgins and Krukowski said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seemed like forever we were sitting on the ground. It was
probably a few minutes,'' said the teacher, Dan Kemats, 24.
</P>
<P>
   A student in the hall overheard the exchange and summoned
another teacher, Linda Robb, Krukowski said.
</P>
<P>
   Robb stood in the doorway of the classroom and asked the boy if
she could talk to him. The two walked out into the hallway and
hugged, and the boy handed the gun over to Robb, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The student was taken into custody by police in this city, which
is about 25 miles south of Youngstown in northeastern Ohio, near
the West Virginia and Pennsylvania state lines.
</P>
<P>
   The Vindicator of Youngstown reported that the boy was on
crossing duty with another sixth-grader, Katie Hartman, on Thursday
morning. The girl said that at the end of their duty the boy told
her: ''Goodbye, Katie. I won't be back.''
</P>
<P>
   She asked what he meant, but he didn't answer.
</P>
<P>
   Sixth-graders were sent home, but the other students were kept
in class because the district didn't want younger children going
home without making sure their parents knew, Krukowski said.
</P>
<P>
   The school, which has about 650 students from kindergarten
through sixth grade, will be closed on Friday but will be open for
student counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ''Naturally the students were shook up, any time you have an
incident like that,'' Krukowski said.
</P>
<P>
   Krukowski said he wasn't very familiar with the boy and was
unaware of any behavior problems.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, campaigning at a Cincinnati elementary
school, said the incident ''once again raises the question that has
confronted us so often in the past year or two or three. That is,
how can we all come together to give our children better values?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the student's access to a firearm points out the need
for gun control measures such as child-safety trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican nominee,
said the government should provide mentoring and support programs
for the 1.3 million sons and daughters of people in prisons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 2301 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000323.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coast Guard Orders 10 Pct. Cut  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORFOLK, Va. (AP) -- The Coast Guard's top admiral in the
Atlantic, citing overworked crews and equipment, has ordered his
cutters and aircraft to reduce operations by 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is time to achieve an understanding among the American
people and in Congress, that the Coast Guard is losing its edge,''
Vice Adm. John E. Shkor said Thursday before a chapter of the Navy
League of the United States. ''New missions, without new resources,
have cut too deep and have taken their toll.''
</P>
<P>
   From now on, he said, ''we will operate our assets to the level,
and only to the level, that can be sustained by the systems which
support them.''
</P>
<P>
   Shkor said his order means:
</P>
<P>
   -- fewer ships and airplanes on counter-drug patrols and ''more
cocaine on our streets.''
</P>
<P>
   -- fewer ships and airplanes securing maritime borders against
alien smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   -- less of a presence on offshore fishing grounds and enforcement
of fishing regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Shkor said the Coast Guard will still rush to search and rescue
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to make a more conscious effort to keep people and
equipment fresh for the emergencies we know will come,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard's 35,000 active duty personnel, 5,700 civilians
and 7,000 reservists ''are straining to keep up,'' said Shkor, who
has headed the Atlantic Area command since September.
</P>
<P>
   He is responsible for operations in 40 states, all inland waters
east of the Rocky Mountains and Atlantic coastal waters from Maine
to the Caribbean Sea, including the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Coast Guard Web site: http://www.uscg.mil/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
