<HEADLINE> Texas Goes After 7th Swim Title  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Troy Dumais won the 1-meter springboard and
the 400-meter medley relay team collected a title Thursday night as
Texas took a 22-point lead over defending champion Auburn after the
first day of the men's NCAA swimming and diving championships.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a big thing,'' said Dumais, who won the diving title by
accumulating 605 points. ''Last year, we were down 30, 40 points
after one day. It's a big up for us to be in the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas had 173 points to 151 for Auburn, which has been first or
second the last four years, and 114{ for Arizona. Texas is bidding
for its third title in 10 years and seventh overall.
</P>
<P>
   The team of Tom Hannan, Russell Chozick, Nate Dusing and Bryan
Jones won the 400 medley relay in 3 minutes, 31.23 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona senior Ryk Neethling, a native of South Africa, picked
up his eighth NCAA championship by winning the 400 freestyle in
3:40.47.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a little disappointed with my time, but it's more
important for the team to get 20 points,'' Neethling said. ''I want
to be the best in the world. I'm not yet, so there's room for
improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Auburn's Matthew Busbee, Aaron Ciarla, Oswaldo Quevedo and
Gregory Busse won the 200-meter freestyle relay in 1:25.14.
</P>
<P>
   Former Hungarian national team member and Olympic gold medalist
Atilla Czene, a freshman at Arizona State, made his NCAA
championships debut by winning the 200 individual medley in
1:54.65.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's much more fun here,'' said Czene, who won the gold medal
in the 200 IM in the 1996 Olympics at Atlanta. ''In Europe, there's
much more pressure. I like it here.''
</P>
<P>
   The meet is being contested for the first time in a 25-meter
pool instead of the 50-meter pool used for international and
Olympic competition.
</P>
</TEXT>
