<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Milosevic Denounces NATO Nations  </HEADLINE>
By DUSAN STOJANOVIC, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- President Slobodan Milosevic branded
NATO countries Europe's new fascists Thursday as he laid a wreath
on a memorial to mark the first anniversary of the 78-day allied
bombing of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let there be eternal glory for the heroes of our fatherland
who died in the defense of freedom and dignity of our country and
its people from new fascism,'' Milosevic wrote in a memorial book
at the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier on Mount Avala, 10 miles outside
Belgrade. A television tower on the mountain was repeatedly
targeted by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav government plans rallies Friday to mark the
anniversary of the air campaign, launched March 24, 1999, to stop
Milosevic's crackdown against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   State-sponsored rallies are scheduled in Serbia's capital,
Belgrade, in Montenegro's capital, Podgorica, and throughout the
two republics that now form Yugoslavia. The ceremonies will include
a marathon along a course that will take runners past bombed-out
government buildings in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the celebrations and triumphalism are in bad taste because
there is nothing to celebrate,'' opposition leader Zoran Djindjic
said Thursday. ''Everyone has lost, Serbia most of all.'' Another
opposition figure, Goran Svilanovic, called the government
festivities ''perverse.''
</P>
<P>
   An anti-Milosevic student group -- Otpor, or Resistance -- has
scheduled its own protests for Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to resist the irrational actions of the international
community, but also resist the aggression carried out by the regime
against its own citizens,'' Otpor said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   But Serb supporters didn't wait for Friday to protest. In
Athens, Greece, more than 5,000 demonstrators, chanting ''NATO out,
Greece is no protectorate'', marched through the city center to the
U.S. embassy Thursday to mark the anniversary. Smaller rallies were
also held in other Greek cities. Despite their country's NATO
membership, most Greeks condemned the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   In the Montenegro capital of Podgorica Thursday, about 2,000
pro-Serb protesters gathered to demand that U.S. leaders be tried
for the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO bombing campaign forced Milosevic to withdraw his
forces and hand Kosovo over to NATO peacekeepers and U.N.
administrators, who now find themselves struggling to end reprisal
attacks by ethnic Albanians against the province's dwindling Serb
community.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's secretary-general, Lord Robertson, and its military
commander for Europe, Gen. Wesley Clark, are due to visit Kosovo on
Friday to mark the anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's grip on power remains unshaken a year after the
bombing campaign. Yugoslavia's divided opposition has failed to
mount a serious challenge to his rule or to respond effectively to
a growing crackdown on dissent.
</P>
<P>
   In a preface to a book on police and military casualties
published by the government to mark the anniversary, Milosevic
repeated his claim that that his forces defeated NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ''In that undeclared war, all our people were the target of the
aggressor: children in maternity wards, sick people in hospitals,
soldiers in their trenches,'' Milosevic said in the book, entitled
''Heroes of the Fatherland.''
</P>
<P>
   The book includes names and biographies of 1,002 Yugoslav
policemen and soldiers killed during the NATO airstrikes. The
government has never released an official toll on the number of
civilian casualties, despite Milosevic's promise to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ''With their courage and with the support of the population, the
members of the Yugoslav army and the police proved that they are
invincible,'' Milosevic wrote in the preface.
</P>
<P>
   The allied bombing campaign -- which destroyed oil refineries and
much of Yugoslavia's other infrastructure -- provided Milosevic with
a scapegoat for the country's economic and social decay.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia's self-imposed isolation after the raids also gave
Milosevic a free hand to crack down on opposition leaders and the
media.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leader Zarko Korc said Friday is ''a sad anniversary
of the same policies that have triggered the war.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The people who are responsible for the tragedy and isolation
of Serbia are still in power and they are now conducting a war
against their own citizens,'' he said. ''The regime is trying to
portray March 24 as the day of its triumph, but it is the day of
Serbian tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Yugoslav government site: http://www.juga.com/
</P>
<P>
   University College London School of Slavoic and East European
Studies site: http://www.ssees.ac.uk/yugoslav.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
