<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Official Gunned Down  </HEADLINE>
By AMPARO TREJO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Gunmen opened fire on an ex-federal agent
reportedly accused of having drug ties and three others at a Mexico
City hotel on Thursday. One person in the group was killed and
three others wounded.
</P>
<P>
   One of those shot was Cuauhtemoc Herrera Suastegui, formerly
with the Mexican attorney general's anti-crime unit. Officials
first said he had been killed, but later said he might be among the
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Herrera was entering the Imperial Hotel with his body guard and
two women when four gunmen opened fire, officials from the Mexico
City attorney general's office said.
</P>
<P>
   One person in the group died at the scene and three others were
hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to clarify the conflicting reports on who was killed, Hugo
Lenoardo Vera, assistant attorney general for Mexico City said,
''We can't confirm anything at this point. We are investigating in
order to be able to give truthful information.''
</P>
<P>
   Visible next to the body that lay in the hotel lobby was a
folder containing Herrera's resume and a black briefcase.
</P>
<P>
   Six people were detained, including the hotel manager.
Authorities believed a seventh had fled the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Herrera, who resigned from the attorney general's office on Jan.
14, was under investigation for possible links to the powerful
Juarez drug cartel, the daily newspaper La Cronica reported Monday
and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Herrera was linked to the cartel by the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration's chief of international operations, La Cronica
reported.
</P>
<P>
   One of the women accompanying Herrera identified herself to
police as a court official in northern Mexico. The other was an
agent in the anti-drug unit of the federal attorney general's
office, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting comes on the sixth anniversary of the assassination
of Luis Donaldo Colosio, then-presidential candidate for Mexico's
governing party, the Institutional Revolutionary Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 2330 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000323.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Ends 1999 With Surplus  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United Nations ended 1999 with more
than $1 billion to spare but expensive U.N. operations in Kosovo
and East Timor may eat up budget surpluses in 2000, the top U.N.
financial official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, however, the financial situation of the organization is
much improved over the past several years -- largely because of
increased payments by the United States, the U.N.
undersecretary-general for management, Joseph Connor, told the U.N.
budget committee.
</P>
<P>
   He urged Washington to pay its bills for 2000, as well as its
more than $1 billion in outstanding dues, so that the United
Nations can continue to improve its viability and fund new
peacekeeping missions this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''In 1999, the United Nations took a step back from the
financial brink,'' Connor said. ''The year 2000 has the potential
to overturn the progress made in 1999, to slip back once more to
the brink.''
</P>
<P>
   Connor told the committee that the United Nations ended 1999 on
a positive note, with $1.1 billion in surplus cash, compared with
$736 million a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the past four years, the United Nations didn't have to
borrow money from its peacekeeping account during the lean months
before the United States made its payment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And when the United States did pay, it made a much larger
contribution than in previous years. In 1999, Washington sent
checks for nearly 150 percent of its regular budget bill. In 1995,
the United States paid just under 50 percent of what it was billed.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations is counting on having cash surpluses in 2000,
but that prediction is based on Washington making a contribution
similar to what it paid in 1999, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is billed 25 percent of the U.N. budget and 31
percent of its peacekeeping budget -- the most of any U.N. member
state. But Washington has withheld partial payment for the past
several years and last year made payment of $926 million of its
outstanding bills conditional on agreement by the other 187 U.N.
member states to reduce its share.
</P>
<P>
   Connor said the U.N. administrations in Kosovo and East Timor
pose the biggest financial challenge to the United Nations in 2000
and may warrant a special review since funding so far has been slow
and unpredictable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
