<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Mich. Delegates Up for Grabs  </HEADLINE>
By KATHY BARKS HOFFMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- As Michigan Republicans begin meeting to
choose delegates for the Republican National Convention, some
backers of John McCain worry that George W. Bush's supporters will
get the seats that should go to them.
</P>
<P>
   McCain spokesman Todd Harris suspected Thursday that Gov. John
Engler -- one of Bush's biggest advocates in the state -- may be
trying to get Bush supporters into some of the delegate spots that
McCain earned by winning Michigan's GOP presidential primary on
Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   McCain picked up 52 of the state's 58 national convention
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   But two-thirds of voters who identified themselves in exit polls
as Republicans backed Bush in the primary. So McCain supporters
attending GOP county and district conventions held to elect
delegates could find themselves in the minority.
</P>
<P>
   Engler spokesman John Truscott said there was no move afoot to
challenge McCain supporters vying for delegate spots.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing like that is happening in the state,'' Truscott said.
''There is no talk of stealing McCain delegates.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's spokesman was skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ''They could not beat us in their own primary, so they are now
attempting after the fact to defeat our delegates in small party
caucuses and behind closed doors,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's Michigan co-chairman, state Sen. John Schwarz, plans to
sit down with Engler and state GOP Chairman Rusty Hills on Monday
to discuss Michigan's delegation to the July 31-Aug. 3 GOP
convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ''Could the Bush people make mischief for the McCain delegates?
Yes,'' said Schwarz, the only lawmaker in Michigan to openly back
McCain before the primary. ''The people who voted for McCain would
be pretty upset if they think their vote for McCain delegates
didn't go to that purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Truscott said it's likely that some Bush supporters may get some
of the delegate spots won by McCain, but they would have to vote
for McCain at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz said that's not necessarily true. He said the fact that
McCain suspended his campaign after the March 7 elections could be
interpreted by Bush backers as a meaning they're not obligated to
vote for McCain on the first ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Unless state party rules are changed, Engler would have to
attend the convention as a McCain delegate. The governor is
expected to be one of 10 statewide delegates McCain won in addition
to the 42 delegates he picked up in congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said Thursday that at the convention he would free the
more than 230 delegates he won during the primaries so they could
vote for any candidate. And, for the sake of party unity, he said
he would not allow any move to nominate him as the GOP presidential
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think that's necessary at all,'' McCain said during a
joint interview, with his wife Cindy, on CNN's ''Larry King Live.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz, meanwhile, blamed some of the friction over delegates
on the chilly relationship between Bush and McCain. Although McCain
has suspended his campaign, he has not endorsed Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over delegates ''could be solved very amicably if
Governor Bush and Senator McCain would sit down and communicate, or
it could be something less than amicable if we have to go into an
aggressive mode to claim the delegates which we won the right to
elect in the primary,'' Schwarz said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is politics. No one said it was a non-contact sport.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-23-00 2331 </TRAILER>
