<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Public Workers Strike  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) -- About 20,000 people marched in the
streets of the Costa Rican capital Thursday, the first day of a
strike by public employees protesting plans to end the state
electric and telecommunications monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Strikers blocked streets and highways and paralyzed the state
oil refinery and the country's two ports. Some public hospitals
canceled appointments and schools failed to open.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear how many workers participated in the strike.
</P>
<P>
   Costa Rica has had daily protests leading up to and following
the National Assembly's approval of a bill Monday to divide the
Costa Rican Institute of Electricity into two businesses -- one for
telecommunications, the other for electricity -- and open them to
private investment. The bill will be reviewed by the Constitutional
Court before being submitted to another vote.
</P>
<P>
   Unions claim it would result in job losses and high rates for
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of serious violence or major clashes with
police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
