<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State agency's final approval on hold  </HEADLINE>
dttvfons
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A judge's ruling Thursday will delay the
expected state approval of a controversial $500 million mall in New
Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Jerry Wagner ruled the state Office of
Policy and Management cannot issue it's final decision until he
decides whether there should be a new public hearing on the
proposed mall at Long Wharf.
</P>
<P>
   Critics contend the new mall would take as much as 28 percent of
downtown New Haven's retail sales, and up to 23 percent of some
suburban retail business. They went to court seeking the new public
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's budget office was expected on Friday to give
final approval to a report that found no significant impact from
the mall on traffic, the environment or the regional economy. The
approval is one of several needed to free up about $28 million in
state financing for the project by the end of April.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he will make his decision on a public hearing by
April 12.
</P>
<P>
   New Haven Mayor John DeStefano Jr. took the latest delay in
stride.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a big project and we've been at it for three years. So
another couple weeks aren't going to cause me to lose any sleep,''
DeStefano told The Associated Press Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Mall supporters say the project will provide thousands of new
construction and retail jobs and give the city and region a major
economic boost.
</P>
</TEXT>
