<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3d World Debtors Club Proposted  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Business officials meeting here for talks in
advance of next month's Third World summit on Thursday proposed the
creation of a debtors' club to help negotiate their country's debts
with wealthier nations.
</P>
<P>
   The group also proposed creation of a new banking institution
for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   Wrapping up the meeting of about 200 businessmen from 30
countries, Cuban Commerce Minister Ricardo Cabrisas called for
reforms in the World Trade Organization that would allow developing
countries to improve their economies through increased
international trade.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals will be presented later to the heads of state from
around the globe who attend a summit by the Group of 77 in Havana
April 10-14. The gathering is aimed at by helping put developing
nations in the mainstream of the global economy and the technology
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The group was established in 1964 by 77 developing countries and
has increased its membership to 133 nations. It is the largest
Third World coalition at the United Nations, promoting the economic
and social interests of the world's poorer nations.
</P>
<P>
   Next month's ''South Summit'' will examine growing
globalization; access to knowledge and technology; improving
dialogue between countries in the south and the richer developed
nations in the north; and increasing cooperation, investment and
trade among the southern nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
